On 27th August 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced influenza-like symptoms, injection site pain, injection site swelling, injection site erythema, injection site warmth, muscle pain, shivering and headache. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient had the Zostavax vaccine many years ago and he got shingles later. The patient received Shingrix in his left arm at physician's office. acute viral syndrome; This subject was enrolled in a blinded study. The subject received daprodustat (gsk1278863) vs rhepo from 27th July 2018, for chronic renal failure anemia.   On 12th June 2019, 320 days after the first dose of daprodustat (gsk1278863) vs rhepo, the subject developed mild - grade 1 weakness generalized. Serious criteria included clinically significant/intervention required. Daprodustat (gsk1278863) vs rhepo was continued with no change. The outcome of weakness generalized was recovered/resolved on 16th June 2019.   The investigator considered that there was no reasonable possibility that the weakness generalized may have been caused by daprodustat (gsk1278863) vs rhepo.  Follow up information received on 03 Jul 2019: The subject's demographics age sex (Female) and weight (88.1 kg) were included. This 71 year old female subject was enrolled in a blinded study. Concurrent medical conditions End stage renal disease and Diabetic peripheral neuropathy were included. The Seriousness Criteria of the event Generalized weakness is updated to requires or prolongs hospitalization (Previously it was clinically significant) Other possible cause of the event Generalized weakness included medical condition (End stage renal disease and Diabetic peripheral neuropathy). Concomitant medications sevelamer carbonate, pantoprazole dr, gabapentin, docusate, diltiazem and apixaban were included. Treatment medications 0.9 percent sodium chloride, acetaminophen, albumin, ceftriaxone, hydrocodone-acetaminophen 5-325, insulin glargine, lidocaine 5% patch, senna, simethicone and vancomycin were included. Other Relevant Risk Factors were none.  Relevant lab: On 14 Jun 2019: labs baseline for patient glucose 175, 307. On 16 Jun 2019: labs baseline for patient except glucose 169. On 15 Jun 2019: normal x ray for pelvis, left. Elbow, right. Elbow, lumbar x ray no evidence of acute trauma. Right and left knee no evidence of fracture were included.  Narrative remark: 14 jun2019 subject went to  emergency room and complained of generalized weakness and myalgia's x2 days since receiving shingles vaccine. Upon admission, patient started vancomycin or ceftriaxone, discharged on 14 Jun 2019 low suspicion for bacterial process. Patient missed dialysis of 11 Jun2019, 13 Jun2019 and 15 Jun2019. patient reported fall at home, patient monitored closely at hospital due to high fall risk. Patient denied head strike. Knee, elbows, pelvis and lumber spine x ray completed. Patient discharged with pain controlled, per oral tolerated, worked with physical therapy or occupational therapy.  Query responses: The site confirmed that the primary discharged diagnosis was generalized weakness. Thought to be a result of Acute Viral Syndrome indicated as separate AE(Adverse event).  Follow up information received on 05 Jul 2019: Verbatim was updated to acute viral syndrome (previously reported generalized weakness). Relevant assessment: On 15 Jun 2019 total bilirubin was 0.1, Alanine aminotransferase was 13, Aspartate aminotransferase was 17. On an unknown date albumin was 3.1. Query response: Site confirmed that albumin for subject was baseline 3.1, but low comparatively to reference ranges. No loss of consciousness, arrhythmias or seizures noted by subject or discharge summary. Glucose reference range was 70-100 mg/dL.  Follow up information received on 22 Jul 2019 : Shingrix was updated as concomitant medication. Narrative remark: 14 Jun2019 subject went to emergency room and complained of generalized weakness and myalgia's x2 days since receiving shingles vaccine (Shingrix).  Follow up information received on 24 Jul 2019 and 26 Jul 2019 : The adverse event (Acute viral syndrome) form includes following information : Narrative remarks : Weakness and myalgias were deemed likely due to recent shingles vaccine (Shingrex), Per discharge summary. Patient presented with general weakness & myalgias x 2days, post-shingrix dose. Patient was admitted and monitored. Influenza panel was negative and workout unremarkable. Symptoms improved with care and deemed likely due to shingrix. Query response from site : The site confirmed that shingles vaccine (SHINGRIX) was likely the cause of the weakness and myalgias patient discharge summary shows that.  Follow up information received on 14 Aug 2019 : The intensity of the event (Acute viral infection) was updated to Moderate-Grade 2 (Previously reported as Mild Grade-1). Query response from site : The event term was verified and updated.  Follow up information received on 20 Aug 2019 : Shingrex updated as co suspect medication. The subject was vaccinated with shingrex on 12 Jun 2019 the dose was 50 ug single. The other possible cause for the event was updated as concomitant medication and medical condition. (Previously reported only medical condition). Narrative remarks : 14 Jun2019 subject went to  emergency room and complained of generalized weakness and myalgia's x2 days since receiving shingles vaccine (Shingrex). Query response from site : The site confirmed that fall was caused by generalized weakness -fall was reported as AE and generalized weakness reported as AE .; Reporter's Comments: The company considers that there was no reasonable possibility that the event viral infection may have been caused by the study drug. The patient's medical history/risk factors could be considered as confounding factors. The co-medication (shingrix) could be considered as alternative cause.

Iritis; blood shot eyes; This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of iritis in a 74-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) (batch number YA724, expiry date unknown) for prophylaxis.   Concomitant products included triamcinolone (Triamcinolone Cream).   On 31st July 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On 9th August 2019, 9 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced iritis and bloodshot eye. The patient was treated with steroids nos (Oral Steroid (Brand Unknown)) and difluprednate (Durezol Eye Drops). On an unknown date, the outcome of the iritis was not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the bloodshot eye was unknown.   The reporter considered the iritis and bloodshot eye to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information received were as follows: The patient received Shingrix on left arm. The patient experienced blood shot eyes (may had been a little before this date, but this was the date it was diagnosed) and progressed into iritis, which was pretty severe. The patient's eye doctor believes it was related to the Shingrix. The patient was prescribed an oral steroid and Durezol 0.05 percent eye drops, 1 drop each eye four times a day until resolved. The patient was also using topical triamcinolone cream all over body (for a previous diagnosis, which they held for the vaccine but had been using this month a lot). The oral medication was unknown. The reporter consented to follow up. The expiry date was unknown.

Ultimate diagnosis:  acute disseminated encephalitis  Event Details July 1, 2019, 9:20 PM ? Headache behind left eye came on over the course of about 10 minutes, followed by intense nausea, beginning about an hour later.  About mid-way through the nausea, left facial numbness began, starting at left tip of tongue, and progressing over the course of less than an hour to the left upper palate, upper and lower left teeth, nose, check, forehead, scalp, and jaw, to the front of the left ear.  Sense of taste on the left side of the tongue disappeared, as well.  Headache abated at or before start of numbness.  No loss of coordination, loss of strength, confusion, slurring, drooping of muscles or other symptoms beyond those described above.  Went to urgent care after finding that the numbness persisted into the following morning.  Urgent care staff directed me to the emergency room.  Will begin a course of 4 days of IV steroid.  Currently pending insurance coordination and facility scheduling.
LAB_DATA: CT scan (with and without contrast) showed ?normal sulcal pattern and gyro configuration.  Gray and white matter differentiation is normal.  No parenchymal mass or hemorrhage is seen.  Sinuses show opacification of the ethmoid air cells and left sphenoid sinus.  Aorta is normal in caliber.  Brachiocephalic artery, left subclavian artery and left carotid artery are widely patent.  Both common carotid arteries are widely patent in the neck with widely patent carotid bifurcations.  Internal carotid arteries are widely patent to the skull base.  The petrous portion of the carotid arteries widely patent.  ACAs, MCAs, and PCAs are widely patent.  Both vertebral arteries are widely patent.  The basilar artery is a small vessel, but is widely patent.  Dural venous sinuses appear to enhance appropriately.  No parenchymal mass is seen.  Salivary tissue appears normal.  No cervical adenopathy is seen.  Thyroid appears normal.  Impression:  Sphenoid and ethic sinus disease, but negative CT angiography of the head and neck.?  Tick-borne Ab Panel, Serum:  Negative for ehrlichia, anaplasmosis, babesiosis, and Lyme.  ESR ( sed rate ) Value 16  ANA panel (EIA) negative  Antineurotrophilic cytoplasmic AB ( anca neutrophilic pANCA cANCA ) Negative for cANCA and pANCA patterns by immunofluorescence  Lyme disease antibody, Western Blot IGG immunoblot:  negative IGG detected against:  none  IGM immunoblot:  negative IGM detected against:  none  Brain MRI with and without contrast showed ?There is normal sulcal  pattern and gyro configuration.  No cortical encephalomalacia seen.  There is a single 10 mm white matter lesion in the centrum semiovale on the right radiating outward from the corpus callous suggestive of demyelinating plaque.  There is a large lesion in the left middle cerebral peduncle.  Tiny 1-2 mm lesions are seen in the frontal white matter and occipital white matter.  There appears to be subcortical U-fiber involvement in the frontal lobes bilaterally.  The appearance is consistent with demyelination and multiple sclerosis, particularly at the left middle cerebellar peduncle lesion.  No other abnormal enhancement is seen.  Trigeminal nerves appear normal.  Meckel?s cave appears normal.  Cavernous sinus appears normal.  Incidental developmental venous anomaly seen in the right cerebellar hemisphere.?    Vitamin B12 value 359  Vitamin D 25 - OH value 25  T event - holter monitor report:  ?1.  The basic rhythm is sinus.  There is no atrial fibrillation.  2.  Sinus node function is normal with average rate of 67 beats per minute.  No sinus pauses.  Sinus bradycardia is present 32% of beats.  3.  AV conduction normal.  4a  Supraventricular arrhythmia:  There was 1 episode of paroxysmal supra ventricular tachycardia of 7 beats duration at 127 beats per minute.  4b. Ventricular Arrhythmia:  There were no ventricular tachyarrhythmias detected.?  T Ultrasound (Carotid Duplex Scan). ?Findings.  Left Carotid Artery:  Duplex imaging of the left carotid artery system notes that it is tortuous.  There is a very small shelf of smooth mixed plaque at the bifurcation and extending into the origin of the external carotid artery.  The left internal carotid artery is without plaque.  Velocity measurements in the internal carotid artery of 120/47 cm per second and the 2-D image support no significant disease or stenosis in the internal carotid artery.  The left vertebral has normal integrate flow, the left subclavian has normal traphasic flow.  Blood pressure in the left arm is 120/70.  Impression:  Normal left carotid study. Right Carotid Artery:  Duplex imaging of the right carotid artery system reveals normal vessels that are tortuous without plaque.  Velocity measurements in the internal carotid artery of 93/34 cm per second are negative for any hemodynamically significant lesion.  The right subclavian/innominate have normal traphasic flow.  Blood pressure in the right arm is 122/70.  Impression:  Normal right carotid study.  I do not have available to me at this time a copy of the results of the lumbar puncture test.  What I can remember of the results that I reviewed with my neurologist, is that the results were inconsistent with either a viral infection or MS.  Overall, and combined with the results of all other information and diagnostic testing to date, the results were consistent with a diagnosis of acute disseminated encephalitis; likely triggered by an adverse reaction to the Shingrix vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: Budesonide (as a daily nasal wash), Nasonex (occasionally, as a nasal spray), sildenafil (occasionally, as needed)

About 12 hours after the two shots, I got very cold and shivering. Once I warmed up, my face got very hot. My entire body felt terrible; my back ached, I felt dizzy upon standing, and my head would throb and ache whenever I moved my neck. Some of the time, I felt like throwing up. I slept restlessly for 11.5 hours, feeling immense pain every time I moved. The next morning, I felt pain behind my ears when I turned my head and my head throbbed when bending down. I was also sensitive to loud noises and bright lights.
CUR_ILL: Slight cough at time of vaccination

SYMPTOM_TEXT: No adverse effects; one patient received one dose of improperly stored ROTATEQ; This spontaneous report has been received from an office manager referring to a patient of unknown age and gender. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history, concomitant therapies and drug allergy or reactions were not reported.         On 27-JUN-2019, the patient was vaccinated with one dose of improperly stored rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ) (lot # R025713, expiration date 20-JUN-2020; dose and route were not reported) for prophylaxis (improper storage of product in use). No additional doses were administrated. No adverse effects were reported.   The administrated vaccine experienced the following temperature excursion: total time and lowest temperature below 36 degree Fahrenheit (33.9 Fahrenheit) for 40 minutes. The digital data logger was involved. Previous temperature excursions included total time and lowest temperature below 36 degree Fahrenheit (30.3 Fahrenheit) for 90 hours and 7 minutes, total time and lowest temperature below 36 degree Fahrenheit (30.5 Fahrenheit) for 1 hour and 45 minutes and total time and lowest temperature below 36 degree Fahrenheit (35.2 Fahrenheit) for 2 hours and 5 minutes.

Additional details were provided as follows: The patient was 68 years old at the time of reporting. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient had so many physician appointments, etc. due to having "Stage 4 Nash"(a hereditary liver disease), a "Stage 3" kidney disease, diabetis, fibromyalgia, sleep apnea, among other things, she needed medicine for, so it was hard to remember when she had the shot or when she got the letter. bilateral sensorineural sloping hearing loss; vertigo; post herpetic neuralgia; herpes zoster; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history and concomitant medications were not reported.  On or about 05-DEC-2016, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot number and expiry date were not provided) for routine health maintenance and the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date (reported as shortly after vaccination), the patient suffered a sharp pain in her head and was diagnosed with herpes zoster. As further result of herpes zoster, the patient suffered and was diagnosed with bilateral sensorineural sloping hearing loss, vertigo, and postherpetic neuralgia. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using vaccine. The patient also experience mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of patient's condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt suffered severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use, she had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.  The reporter considered the events to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  Upon internal review, the event of bilateral sensorineural sloping hearing loss was determined to be medically significant. The events were considered to be disabling.

Additional information received were as follows: The patient was a physician who received both doses of the Shingrix vaccine. The lot number was unknown. The patient received Shingrix on left deltoid in the evening. The patient experienced sore injection site that resolved the next morning of vaccination date. At 7:00 pm that evening, the patient again had chills and felt warm, but he did not take his temperature.  On 28th August 2019, the patient went to bed at 9:30 pm and woke up on 29th August 2019 with all symptoms resolved.  The reporter was unable to provide any additional details and unable to locate case number for first case. The caller stated that all symptoms had resolved, however, he still had a little soreness in his left arm. The patient also mentioned that he had experienced soreness at the injection site following previous flu shots (unknown manufacturer).  The caller did not provide any additional details. This was 1 of the 3 cases reported by same reporter.

double pneumonia; Also suffered an outbreak of herpes zoster and cellulitis of her face resulting in facial swelling, severe pain, ear problems and medical treatment; Also suffered an outbreak of herpes zoster and cellulitis of her face resulting in facial swelling, severe pain, ear problems and medical treatment; ear problems; swelling of her lower extremities; edema; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. On 03-JUN-2016, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (the dosage regimen information was not reported). In December 2016 (also reported as "shortly thereafter"), the patient was diagnosed with double pneumonia, which was caused by the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, resulting in her hospitalization (unknown dates). As a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient also suffered an outbreak of herpes zoster and cellulitis of her face resulting in facial swelling, severe pain, ear problems and medical treatment. Since zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination, the patient suffered swelling of her lower extremities and edema that continued at the time of the report. As a direct and proximate result of the zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination, the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition and has suffered economic losses due to her inability to work. The outcome of the events was considered as not recovered. The events were considered to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The adverse events were considered to be disabling as the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and inability to work.  Upon internal review, pneumonia and cellulitis were considered to be medically significant.

patient had custard icecream and afterwards had an extreme reaction/ patient had strawberry yogurt and had another reaction/ teacher gave the patient a donut hole and patient had allergic reaction; Chest was sunken in and he could hardly breath; Chest was sunken in and he could hardly breath; This spontaneous report was received from the patient's mother referred to a 2 year old (currently 15 year old) male patient. The patient did not have any medical history, and concomitant medications. The patient had numerous food allergies including pears, peaches, legumes, soy, mustard, hot dogs, pepperoni, peanuts, eggs, chicken, pumpkin, squash, and strawberries. On an unknown date, approximately in 2006 (reported as about 13 years ago), when the patient was 2-year-old, he was vaccinated with measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) dose 1, for prophylaxis (normal shots from pediatrician) injected in the arm (dose, route, lot # and expiry date were not reported). On an unknown date, approximately in 2006 (reported as about 13 years ago), one week after receiving the vaccine, patient had custard ice cream and afterwards had an extreme reaction. It was reported that, the patient's chest was sunken in and he could hardly breath (chest discomfort, dyspnoea). The next week the patient had strawberry yogurt and had another reaction. The reporter took the patient to pediatrician on an unknown date after the first reaction and the patient had skin and blood tests for allergies. The reporter stated that, the patient was allergy tested every 6 months and on an unspecified date switched allergy testing every year. At the time of reporting, the patient was being tested yearly. The patient had gradually outgrown all the allergies but eggs, tree nuts, peanuts and chicken (reporter was not sure about chicken). On an unknown date, a teacher in school gave the patient a doughnut hole and patient had an allergic reaction (food allergy). At the time of reporting, the patient was extremely allergic to eggs. The patient was treated with diphenhydramine (BENADRYL) for the reactions. The outcome of the events was not resolved. The reporter did not provide any causality assessment. Product quality complaint was not involved.
CUR_ILL: Food allergy (numerous food allergies including pears, peaches, legumes, soy, mustard, hot dogs, pepperoni, peanuts, eggs, chicken, pumpkin, squash, and strawberries.)

The patient's pertinent medical history included Crohn's disease. The patient did not have any drug reaction or allergy. Acute Gastroenteritis; received (delayed penta concordant dose); missed last dose of rotarix vaccine; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of acute gastroenteritis in a infant patient who received Rota (Rotarix liquid formulation) for prophylaxis.  Co-suspect products included DTPw-HBV+Hib (DTPw-HBV/Hib) for prophylaxis and Rota (Rotarix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included DTPw-HBV/Hib (1st dose received on an unknown date).   On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Rotarix liquid formulation, the 1st dose of DTPw-HBV/Hib and the 2nd dose of Rotarix. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Rotarix liquid formulation and DTPw-HBV/Hib and not applicable after receiving Rotarix, the patient experienced acute gastroenteritis (serious criteria hospitalization), drug dose administration interval too long and incomplete course of vaccination. On an unknown date, the outcome of the acute gastroenteritis, drug dose administration interval too long and incomplete course of vaccination were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the acute gastroenteritis to be related to Rotarix liquid formulation and DTPw-HBV/Hib.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of acute gastroenteritis in an infant aged between 14 weeks and 36 months who was vaccinated with diphtheria-tetanus-whole cell pertussis-hepatitis B-Haemophilus influenzae type B (DTPw-HepB-Hib) vaccine (manufacturer unknown) and rotarix vaccine (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis. The patient was part of the active rotavirus surveillance platform from 2013 to 2017. That aimed to examined the timeliness of rotavirus vaccine versus DTPw-HepB-Hib (pentavalent) vaccine first dose and last dose were compared at 15 and 32 weeks of age, respectively, which was concurrently administered without age restrictions, in two RV1 (rotarix) introducing countries and two RV5 (Rotateq) introducing countries that implemented vaccination between 2012 and 2014. As these countries made the decision to implement rotavirus vaccination prior to or soon after WHO0s 2013 decision to remove age restrictions. They hypothesized that the previous age restrictions might have had some impact on the timeliness of rotavirus vaccination. [In this study, surveillance and enrollment periods varied by country. A stool specimen that tested rotavirus-negative were included in the analysis. A total 3568 Rotavirus-negtive children were enrolled in the surveillance programs, 464 children, median age ranged from 45 to 49 weeks old, 169 were female. No information on patient's medical or family history or concurrent condition were provided. [In this study, on unspecified date, the 438 patient's received  1st dose of rotarix on-time (penta concordant dose) 1st dose of diphtheria-tetanus-whole cell pertussis-hepatitis B-Haemophilus influenzae type B (DTPw-HepB-Hib) vaccine and 9 patient's received 1st dose of rotarix as delayed (penta concordant dose)]. (administration route and site unspecified, batch number not provided for both vaccines). The age of vaccination was not provided]. On unspecified date, the patient had received (delayed penta concordant dose) 2nd dose of diphtheria-tetanus-whole cell pertussis-hepatitis B-Haemophilus influenzae type B (DTPw-HepB-Hib) vaccine and missed last dose of rotarix vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, batch number not provided for both vaccines). The age of vaccination was not provided. [In this study, two oral live attenuated rotavirus vaccines are currently licensed for global use Rotarix (RV1), a 2-dose vaccine administered at 6 and 10 weeks of age. The countries introduced rotavirus vaccine at (April 2012). In 2009, the World Health Organization (WHO) recommended routine vaccination against rotavirus worldwide, with unique age recommendations to administer the first dose before 15?weeks of age and last dose by 32?weeks of age. This analysis includes infant, who were born at least 2 months after rotavirus vaccine was introduced into the national vaccination program. For the last dose of RV1, the concordant pentavalent dose was the second dose in the series]. On an unspecified date, unknown period after vaccination, the patient fecal specimen was obtained to test for the rotavirus and the patient experienced acute gastroenteritis. The patient hospitalized between February 2013 and April 2015. Due to the delayed penta concordant 2nd dose, the patient missed last dose of rotarix, which led to missed dose (i.e incomplete course of vaccination). [In this study, a missed opportunity for rotavirus vaccine was defined as a pentavalent vaccine dose administration without concordant rotavirus vaccine dose administration. Delayed vaccine administration was defined as vaccine administration at least 1 week after the recommended rotavirus vaccination schedule. Active surveillance for acute gastroenteritis hospitalizations was conducted using the WHO generic protocol and a fecal specimen was obtained to test for rotavirus. The median number of months between the date of rotavirus vaccine introduction and the date of admission was lowest for children (22 months]. Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not provided.  The author commented, "Delayed pentavalent vaccine administration was clearly associated with missed rotavirus vaccination opportunity for the first dose alone. Children who received a delayed concordant dose of pentavalent vaccine were also more likely to miss a last dose of rotavirus vaccine as compared to children who had received concordant pentavalent dose on time, and findings were not confounded by age on admission, months between vaccine introduction and admission date, and sex. However, when restricting the cohort to children who had received first dose of rotavirus vaccine and pentavalent vaccine, there was no association between missed last dose of rotavirus vaccine and timeliness of concordant pentavalent dose in any country. This indicates that rotavirus vaccine last dose findings were driven primarily by missed rotavirus vaccine first doses." The author concluded "Rotavirus vaccine administration was timely among children enrolled at sentinel sites in these four early rotavirus vaccine introducing countries, and age restrictions had minimal impact on rotavirus vaccine use due to timely vaccine administration. In countries with less timely vaccine administration, disparities in coverage between rotavirus vaccine and pentavalent vaccine may be more prominent if age restrictions continue to be followed to some extent and this should be examined in future evaluations.". This is 1 of the 2 valid cases reported in this literature article.      Lab Comments: Lab test don on an unknown date before enrollment in the study. In this study, surveillance and enrollment periods varied by country. A stool specimen that tested rotavirus-negative were included in the analysis. A total 3568 Rotavirus-negtive children were enrolled in the surveillance programs.

classic neurophathy; warm on the bottom of feet; face tingling; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of neuropathy in a male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Shingrix (received 1st dose on 17th February 2019, refer case US2019AMR161883 ). Concurrent medical conditions included bone spur.   In May 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On an unknown date, less than 3 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced neuropathy (serious criteria GSK medically significant), localized feeling of warmth and tingling. Rechallenge with Shingrix was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the neuropathy and tingling were unknown and the outcome of the localized feeling of warmth was not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the neuropathy, localized feeling of warmth and tingling to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were reported as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient received dose 2 of Shingrix and that months later he started to feel warm on the bottoms of his feet and it feels like, classic neuropathy to him. He states he sought medical care and his physician told him it was bone spurs and not related to Shingrix, but patient felt it was incorrect.  The patient stated that 3 weeks ago he experienced like his face was started tingling as well. The reporter consented to follow up.

Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of urethral gonorrhea infection in a male patient of unspecified age who was vaccinated with unspecified meningococcal B vaccine (Unknown manufacturer) for prophylaxis. The patient was part of dataset constructed by combining surveillance and medical record data from men diagnosed with uropathogenic, non-groupable Neisseria meningitidis (NmNG) clade urethritis in a local sexually transmitted disease (STD) clinic. Time-to-event analyses of clinic visits between January 2015 and April 2018 was used to examine prospective urethral gonorrhea risk. In this study, subsequent gonorrhea acquisition for men with NmNG clade urethritis at baseline was compared to men with Neisseria gonorrhea (Ng) urethritis (n=255), chlamydial urethritis (n=253), or no infection (n=257) at baseline. [In this study, participants were primarily Black and heterosexual with a median age of 28 years. At baseline, 13% had prior gonorrhea history]. No information on patient's medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received unspecified meningococcal B vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided.  On an unspecified date, an unknown period after vaccination, the patient was diagnosed with uropathogenic, non-groupable Neisseria meningitidis (NmNG) clade urethritis in a local STD clinic. Subsequently, on an unspecified date between January 2015 and April 2018, the patient developed urethral gonorrhea infection.  Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not provided. [In this study, half of men returned for STD screening at least once during the follow-up period.] The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of urethral gonorrhea infection and unspecified meningococcal B vaccine. The authors stated, "Men with NmNG clade urethritis at baseline had similar gonorrhea risk as men with Ng at baseline. Results were not meaningfully different when assessing extragenital gonococcal infections, or after adjustment for time since baseline, age, race, sexual orientation, prior gonorrhea infection, and sexual behavior (number of partners, condom use, and oral sex). In contrast, those with NmNG clade urethritis had increased gonorrhea incidence compared to men with chlamydial urethritis and men with no infection at baseline." The authors concluded "Natural infection with NmNG urethritis clade does not appear to protect men against subsequent acquisition of gonorrhea".      Lab Comments: On an unspecified date between January 2015 and April 2018, the patient was diagnosed with NmNG clade urethritis in a local STD clinic.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: hearing loss; vertigo; Information has been received from a lawyer and the patient regarding a case in litigation concerning a female patient (age unknown). On or about 26-SEP-2017, the patient (pt) was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), (lot# and route unknown) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). Shortly after  zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination, the pt suffered hearing loss and vertigo (dates unspecified).   As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the product. The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of the Company's wrongful conduct, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of the Company's conduct, the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events were considered not resolved. The events were considered related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  Hearing loss and vertigo were considered to be disabling events. Upon internal review, the event hearing loss was determined to be medically significant.

Intrauterine growth restriciton; Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Preterm birth; Low birth weight; Laryngomalacia; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 06-Aug-2019, concerning an infant subject. The mother was a 24-year-old, female pregnant subject of body weight: 221 lbs, height: 60 inches and body mass index (BMI): 43.2, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The mother's concomitant medications included prenatal vitamins (unspecified vitamins and minerals, 1 tablet orally every day, from 18-Oct-2018 to 08-Feb-2019, for pregnancy and promethazine for nausea. The mother's medical history included nausea.  The mother's obstetrical history included three previous pregnancies: two live births and one spontaneous abortion. The mother had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation nor maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The pregnancy status of the mother was collected and there were no complications noted.  The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) was 15-Jun-2018. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The estimated delivery date (EDD) was 22-Mar-2019 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was 05-Mar-2019.   On 18-Oct-2018, haemoglobin electrophoresis, spinal muscular atrophy screen and fibrosis mutation analysis were done and no major congenital malformation (MCM) were noted.  On 01-Nov-2018, at gestation age of 19 weeks, the mother was administered with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 252664, route of administration, expiration date and anatomical location were not reported] (explicitly coded as foetal exposure during pregnancy) for influenza immunisation. On the same day, ultrasound was performed and no MCM were noted.  On an unspecified date, the mother developed oligohydramnios.  On 08-Feb-2019, three months and seven days after vaccination, at 36,4 weeks gestation, the mother gave a live birth to normal female neonate by caesarean delivery. The neonate's birth weight was 1928 grams (head circumference and body length were not reported). The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 at one minute and 8 at five minutes. APGAR score was not reported for 10 minutes. On the same day, the congenital malformation laryngomalacia was noted by neonatal intensive care unit, possibly due to preterm birth and intrauterine growth restriction, as reported.   At the time of follow up, the outcome of the events low birth weight, preterm birth, intrauterine growth restriction and laryngomalacia was not reported.   This case is linked to 201904355, the corresponding mother report.  Follow up received from other health professional on 03-Sep-2019 and process together on 04-Sep-2019 included: The events of laryngomalacia and intrauterine growth restriction added. Indications for concomitant medications populated with null flavors. Narrative was amended accordingly.   Company comment: Reportedly, the female neonate subject was delivered as premature baby, low birth weight baby, with laryngomalacia and foetal growth restriction after foetal exposure during pregnancy, at gestation age of 19 weeks with the suspect product Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. Chronology is plausible. The mother's historical conditions of class 3 obesity (BMI 43.2) may have contributed to development of the events. Causality was confounded by therapy with concomitant medication promethazine. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated based on company's conventions. For all other events, causal role of the suspect product cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related.; Reporter's Comments: Reportedly, the female neonate subject was delivered as premature baby, low birth weight baby, with laryngomalacia and foetal growth restriction after foetal exposure during pregnancy, at gestation age of 19 weeks with the suspect product Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. SIRS; Administered flu vaccine intravenously; This is a spontaneous case, initially received from pharmacist via Agency (reference number: SEQ19-02270) on 04-Sep-2019, concerning a 33-year-old female patient.  The patient's medical history included chest pain, symptomatic anaemia and viral gastroenteritis.  The patient's concomitant medications included ferrous sulphate, amitriptyline, Duoneb (ipratropium bromide, albuterol sulfate), Zofran (ondansetron), Percocet (oxycodone, acetaminophen), oxycodone, Miralax (polyethylene glycol 3350) and senna; all for unknown indication.  On 11-Jan-2019, while was in hospital due to chest pain related to anemia, the patient was administered intravenously Afluria Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, dose: 0.5 ml, batch number: YG40008, expiration date and anatomical location not reported] (explicitly coded as �Inappropriate route of vaccination') for influenza prophylaxis. On the same day, the patient was discharged home.  On 12-Jan-2019, one day after vaccination, the patient developed nausea and vomiting with elevated white blood cell count. The patient was readmitted to hospital and diagnosed with Systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS).  On 15-Jan-2019, the event of SIRS was resolved.  It was unknown if the event of SIRS was caused by IV administration of influenza vaccine or from viral gastroenteritis.  The reporter assessed the case as serious.  Company Comment: The patient experienced systemic inflammatory response syndrome after incorrect route of the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent administration (reported as flu vaccine intravenously administered). Chronology is plausible. Medical history of anaemia and viral gastroenteritis may have contributed to development of the event systemic inflammatory response syndrome. Causality was also confounded by therapy with multiple concomitant medications. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and the event systemic inflammatory response syndrome is assessed as related and as not related for incorrect route of product administration.; Reporter's Comments: The patient experienced systemic inflammatory response syndrome after incorrect route of the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent administration (reported as flu vaccine intravenously administered). Chronology is plausible. Medical history of anaemia and viral gastroenteritis may have contributed to development of the event systemic inflammatory response syndrome. Causality was also confounded by therapy with multiple concomitant medications. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and the event systemic inflammatory response syndrome is assessed as related and as not related for incorrect route of product administration.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pre-eclampsia; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 05-Sep-2019, concerning a 35-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight: 213.8 lbs, height: 59 inches and body mass index (BMI): 43.2, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study. The subject's obstetrical history noted that she had no previous pregnancies and that she was in advanced maternal age. Also, the subject had no relevant maternal and paternal medical history. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject's medical history included depressive disorder, left lower quadrant pain, anxiety, seasonal allergies, dyspareunia and heartburn. The concomitant medications of the subject included Prenatal gummy as health supplement, ranitidine for heartburn and fluticasone propionate for seasonal allergies.   The subject's last menstrual period date was 01-Dec-2018, the estimated delivery date and corrected delivery date were reported as 07-Sep-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 21-Jan-2019, the subject underwent prenatal tests toxoplasma IgG and IgM and no major congenital malformations were noted.   On 04-Feb-2019, at gestational age of approximately nine weeks, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL [influenza vaccine, batch number: YF41608, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.   On 27-Feb-2019, the subject underwent Maternal serum alfa-fetoprotein (MSAFP)/ serum markers test, Essential panel and Non-invasive prenatal test and no major congenital malformations were noted.   On 22-Apr-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and no major congenital malformations were noted.   On 20-Aug-2019, approximately six months after vaccination, the subject experienced pre-eclampsia and was treated with labetalol at a dose of 200 mg, administered two times per day via oral route.   At 37.9 gestational week, the subject vaginally delivered live birth male neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 2841 g, length 48.9 cm and his head circumference 34.5 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). APGAR score was not reported for 10 minutes. There was no major congenital malformation identified at birth.   At the time of initial reporting, the subject had not recovered from the event of 'pre-eclampsia'.  Company Comment: The subject experienced pre-eclampsia 6 months and 16 days after vaccination with the suspect product Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy.  Chronology is unsuggestive due to long latency onset. Medical history of depressive disorder, seasonal allergies and pregnant state may have contributed to development of the event. Causality was confounded by therapy with concomitant medications ranitidine and fluticasone propionate. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related and as related for the event pre-eclampsia.; Reporter's Comments: The subject experienced pre-eclampsia 6 months and 16 days after vaccination with the suspect product Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL. Patient received her second Meningococcal B (Bexero) vaccine today, 9/10/19, at 8:20 am.   The first dose was given on 7/30/19. The vaccine was given properly in the left deltoid after the patient passed the nursing protocol for administration.  When patient left, she was feeling well and had no complaints.  Her mother called our nurse triage line at 11:05 am stating that she was having left arm pain, numbness and weakness and that she was unable to make a fist or raise her arm above her head.  She arrived to our clinic at 12:45 to be seen by a provider.  She was having chills, left arm pain 6/10 and generalized body aches/pain 8/10 and felt shaky. Her vitals were as follows: temperature 39 degrees Celsius, blood pressures were 72/38 initially and then 90/38, pulse 89, and 99% oxygen saturation.  The patient was given something to eat as she had only a small breakfast and no lunch.  After further discussion with the provider, the mother stated that the symptoms started an hour and a half after she received the vaccine.  There was no swelling, redness or warmth at the injection site.  Patient?s repeat blood pressure thirty minutes later was 98/61 and pulse was 89, she was not flush-appearing and was starting to feel better.  The arm weakness had improved prior to being seen in clinic, and was completely resolved prior to her leaving the clinic.  She was observed for over an hour in clinic and was sent home with instructions to return should symptoms reappear.

Shortly after recieving the vaccination i expierenced the usual symptoms (fatigue, sore arm, etc). After a few days i noticed i had a lump inferior to the mid clavicle area. I assumed it to by a lymph node, and waited 4 weeks to see if it went away. When it did not go away I made an appt w/ my Dr. He ordered an ultrasound. It took almost three weeks to get an appt for ultrasound. They confirmed it was a 1.4cm lymph node, possible reactive. The report stated they could not rule out malignancy and suggested further test. My provider ordered a chest X-ray which came back negative for lung effusion or masses. However, once again the report said it could not rule out soft tissue tumors or malignancy. Im not awaiting a surgical consult for biopsy. Ive had this lymph node for nearly 3 months.
LAB_DATA: After the lymph node persisted >4 weeks, Dr ordered ultrasound, it revealed a 1.4 cm reactive inferior clavicle lymph node. Suggested further evaluation given the area and highly likelihood of malignancy associated with those lymph nodes.  Provider then ordered a chest X-ray. Report came back clear, no effusions or tumors. However it suggested further work up because it could not rule out soft tissue tumors in chest/breast. Currently awaiting general surgery consult for biopsy. Consult is scheduled for 9/16/19.

Previously administered products included Shingrix with an associated reaction of injection site reaction (received 1st dose on 8th October 2018, refer case US2019107209).   On 4th June 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 4th June 2019, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced drug dose administration interval too long. In June 2019, the patient experienced injection site pain, erythema, cough and influenza-like symptoms. Rechallenge with Shingrix was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site pain, erythema, cough, influenza-like symptoms and drug dose administration interval too long were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site pain, erythema, cough and influenza-like symptoms to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient received Shingrix in left arm. The pharmacist stated that the patient experienced injection site reactions. The pharmacist notes the injection was given by a rotating pharmacist.  She states the patient gives permission for GlaxoSmithKline to reach out to her. On 7/8/19 while preparing for vacation, patient began acting a bit unlike her usual self the night before leaving.  The morning (4:30am) of the trip she said she was not feeling great but we all seemed to think this was due to lack of sleep.  When we drove to the airport about 2 hours later she began showing signs of confusion and had obvious trouble with word finding. She also had some occasional "tick like" jerking of her arms/legs.  She could not tell what year it was.   We were taken to hospital.  Stroke was ruled out from MRI.  An abnormal EEG indicated a weakness toward seizure activity. A lumber puncture the next day indicated inflammation in the spinal fluid with an slightly abnormal high viral count.  After 24 hours her symptoms had cleared completely.  She was released from the hospital after 2 nights.

HISTORY: Sleep apnea, overweight, breast cancer detected and removed 2015

About 6 days after my daughter received  her routine 12 month shots, she developed hives all over her body. Spots included: belly button, inner thighs, arm pits, eye lids, back of her neck, and torso. I figured it was just a normal reaction to the measles shot so I took her to the pediatrician just to be sure. They informed me it was not a normal reaction to MMR shot, but that it was hives. The told me it was something she came in contact with, food or household items that she was allergic to. However, all the food or other products she has had since then or before that date and never had hives. She had the hives for a fee weeks. We visited the pediatrician twice during that time and the urgent care once due to the hives and a strong fever. Nothing they prescribed worked. They prescribed benadryl and hydrocortisone ointment. Every time we visited for this matter, they said it was nuts, eggs, shellfish, milk. Since she was 12 months, we have given her these food items on a regular basis, weekly, and no hives. Hives have not come back since this time period.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Oligohydramnios; Insomnia; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 06-Sep-2019, concerning a 33-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight 155 lbs, height: 63.5 inches and body mass index (BMI) 27.1, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study during pregnancy.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had 5 previous pregnancies which included three full term live births, one preterm live birth and one spontaneous abortion. No birth defects were reported. Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The subject did not have a prior history of use of tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject's medical history included hypothyroidism. The subject's concomitant medications included Prenatal Vitamins (mineral NOS, vitamin NOS) as a supplement.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 30-Nov-2018, estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 06-Sep-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 24-Jan-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound scan, and no major congenital malformation was noted.  On 31-Jan-2019, at gestation age of 8.9 weeks, the subject received Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL [influenza vaccine, batch number: YF41608; dose, expiration date, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.  On 05-Apr-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound scan, and no major congenital malformation was noted.  On 19-Aug-2019, approximately six months after vaccination, the subject developed insomnia. The subject received Ambien (zolpidem tartrate) at a dose of 5 mg, administered via oral route, every day as required, as a corrective treatment.  On 27-Aug-2019, approximately six months after vaccination, the subject developed oligohydramnios.   At gestational age of 39 weeks, the subject vaginally delivered live birth, female neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 3439 g, head circumference 35.5 cm and length 53.3 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). No major congenital malformation was identified at birth. Oligohydramnios was noted as pregnancy complication.  On the same day, the subject recovered from the event 'oligohydramnios'.   At the time of initial reporting, the patient had not recovered from the event of 'insomnia'.  Company comment: A pregnant subject was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL at 8.9 weeks of gestation. The subject developed insomnia and oligohydramnios, approximately six months after vaccination. Received the Hepatitis B #2  vaccine at 3:30 pm. Went out to dinner with family around 6:30. When we arrived at the restaurant, we sat outside and I described that I "felt weird." My heart was racing, I was covered in goosebumps even though I was sitting in direct sunlight, and I felt dizzy. It felt that I had to try harder to swallow and it took longer to start breathing again after swallowing. I went into the bathroom at the restaurant and had really bad diarrhea. Another adult at the table asked if I had any medication allergies and I told her I couldn't have Cephalosporins or Penicillins. She asked if I needed an Epi Pen, but I got confused and told her that I couldn't have it because I was allergic to Penicillin (even though my normal self was aware they are completely different things). I felt like something awful was going to happen. I continued to be confused and she gave me Benadryl from her purse. A friend stayed with me for the next couple hours. I was exhausted and felt awful, but no more symptoms occurred.
LAB_DATA: I called the Student Health Center the following day to report what happened. MSN, RN told me that what I experienced were adverse effects and that Benadryl has no effect in an allergic reaction.  I did not know at the time that I could self-report a reaction.
PRIOR_VAX: MMR and Hep B received together in the month or two previous. Age 23. Adverse event was heart racing for full day following vacc

He has not been able to participate in physical activities if his PLT are below 50,000 due to concern of internal bleeding. He plays Club Soccer at a high level year round along with High School soccer with the goal of being recruited & scholarship to play in college. He has to go weekly for bloodwork to see if his PLT counts are high enough each week to play. He has had to take Prednisone to increase PLT counts so he can participate in Club championship/state/regional games multiple times to ensure high enough counts & be able to play! His numbers have continued fluctuating & dropping down to 13,000 requiring Promacta prescription medicine to force his bone marrow to increase PLT production. Zofran also needed to deal with nausea from Promacta. He has been told his ITP could last 6 months to 5 plus years until his body re-sets itself & stops attacking his own PLT. We have his liver/organs checked each month to ensure the Promacta does not damage his liver & cause future health issues. This MMR vaccination has changed our son's life dramatically now & well into his future!

acute encephalopaty; stroke/weakness on his left side/Altered mental status; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a male patient of unknown age. No information was received regarding the patient's past medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medication. On or around 16-JUN--2017, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot number, dosage and route of administration not provided), for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). Shortly after, the patient was admitted after suffering weakness on his left side, acute encephalopathy, altered mental status and he was ultimately diagnosed with a stroke. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the product.  The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained serious, progressive, severe and permanent personal injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment, suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events were considered not recovered. The events were considered related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  Upon internal review, the events stroke and encephalopathy were considered to be medically significant.

At the time of the report, the outcome of herpes zoster, fatigue, headache and pyrexia was considered as not recovered. Patient initially developed a local reaction on the Friday she received the vaccine. On Sunday, she presented to the emergency department with a rash that was treated with Benadryl. After the Benadryl, she had improvement in her symptoms and was discharged home. On Monday, she presented to our emergency department with return of her symptoms, diffuse urticarial, and fevers to 101. Biopsy of the rash returned as superficial and deep perivascular dermatitis with eosinophils consistent with dermal hypersensitivity reaction. Her infectious disease workup remained negative. During her hospitalization, her highest temperature recorded was 102.5F. She is presently being treated with famotidine, hydroxyzine, loratadine, diphenhydramine, and IV methylprednisolone. Her skin rash is visibly improving, although she remains febrile and still has the rash. She at present still hospitalized.

I had a positive HPV test on 6/18/19 and I decided to get the HPV vaccine based on the recent FDA recommendations. I received my first and only HPV vaccine on 7/23/19. Two days after the vaccination I had flu like symptoms including high temperatures, body aches, headaches, and fatigue. The body aches improved after a few days but high temperature and weakness continued to be a problem intermittently.  I had some labs done to rule out infection including CMP (normal). About one week following vaccination I went to urgent care and was given antibiotics for possible sinusitis. I finished the course of antibiotic with no improvements. The high temperatures were not intermittent anymore and I started having severe joint and bone pain around 8/14/2019. The pain was worst in my hands. My PCP ordered some inflammatory markers (ANA, ARP, RA factor, ESR) to rule out RA, the labs were all negative. It has been about 7 weeks since my vaccination now, bone and joint pain have improved but fatigue continues to be an issue. I sometimes experience the warm feeling (almost like hot flashes) and also miscellaneous body pains (abdominal pain, muscle and joint pain, headache).  I have to point out that prior to this event I was a perfectly healthy individual, I have no history of chronic diseases or reactions to vaccines. I am also a clinical pharmacist and completely pro-vaccine. I understand that current data and research does not support some of the current public concerns about this vaccine but I truly believe that a closer investigation needs to be done regarding these concerns.
LAB_DATA: CMP, TSH, ANA, ARP, RA factor, ESR (all normal/negative)

Bilateral optic neuritis; This is a literature case, initially received on 10-Sep-2019, concerning a 6-year-old, child, female patient.   The patient had no previous medical problems. There was no family history of autoimmune, ocular, or neurologic disorders.  On an unknown date, the patient was administered with unspecified Flu vaccine [quadrivalent inactivated flu vaccine, route of administration: intramuscular, dose, batch number and anatomical location: not provided] for an unknown indication.   On an unspecified date, one week after receiving a flu vaccine the patient developed bilateral vision loss and was diagnosed with bilateral optic neuritis.  The patient's identical twin received the same vaccination without subsequent changes in vision.  At presentation to the emergency department, her visual acuities were hand motion in the right eye and counting fingers in the left with no afferent pupillary defect (APD). Examination revealed severe optic disc swelling with vessel obscuration bilaterally and peripapillary hemorrhages on the left. There were no anterior chamber cells, vitreous cells, or macular exudates in either eye. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brain, orbits, and spinal cord with and without intravenous (IV) contrast showed increased T2/FLAIR signal and abnormal enhancement in the retrobulbar optic nerves bilaterally, but no white matter lesions in the brain or spinal cord. Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) analysis revealed 1,000 red blood cells/mL, 5 nucleated cells (WBC)/mL, protein level of 23 mg/dL, and glucose level of 58 mg/dL. There were no oligoclonal bands, positive cultures, Lyme antibodies, aquaporin-4 antibodies, or evidence of any of the following by polymerase chain reaction in the CSF: Epstein�Barr virus, herpes simplex virus, and varicella-zoster virus. Serologic testing was also negative for culture growth, Lyme antibodies, and aquaporin-4 antibodies; white blood cell count, erythrocyte sedimentation rate, C-reactive protein, and angiotensin-converting enzyme levels were normal.  The patient was treated with intravenous methylprednisolone.   After 5 days of IV methylprednisolone, visual acuities improved to 20/20, and she recognized 10/10 Ishihara color plates with each eye. The patient was discharged to home without a steroid taper.  Six days after her last dose of IV steroids, the patient experienced decreased vision in the left eye. Examination showed visual acuities of 20/25 in the right eye and no light perception in the left eye. There was a left APD.   Ophthalmoscopy showed mild atrophy of the right optic disc from her initial inflammation and swelling of the left optic disc. Optical coherence tomography (OCT) of the peripapillary retinal nerve fiber layer showed average thicknesses of 144 �m in the right eye and 203 �m in the left eye, consistent bilateral disc edema.   The patient was started oral prednisolone 2 mg/kg/day. Two weeks later, her visual acuities returned to 20/20 with normal color vision (14/14 Ishihara plates) in each eye. Optic disc swelling in the left eye had resolved, leaving mild pallor of both optic discs. The oral steroid dose was tapered over the subsequent 4 weeks without recurrence of vision loss. At her last follow-up evaluation (11 weeks after the influenza vaccination and 10 weeks after initial vision loss), neuro-ophthalmic examination was stable.  The patient has remained without recurrence off steroids over the past 2 years.  Per reporter, the divergent reactions to the influenza vaccine in their patient and patient's identical twin suggest that the interplay between environmental exposures and genetic predisposition in postinfluenza vaccination optic neuritis may be more complicated and warrants further research.  Company Comment: The patient experienced optic neuritis one week after vaccination with unspecified Flu vaccine. Chronology is plausible. It was reported that the patient had no previous medical problems. Examination revealed severe optic disc swelling with vessel obscuration bilaterally and peripapillary haemorrhages. No concomitant medications were reported. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and the event is assessed as related.; Reporter's Comments: The patient experienced optic neuritis one week after vaccination with unspecified Flu vaccine. Chronology is plausible. It was reported that the patient had no previous medical problems. Examination revealed severe optic disc swelling with vessel obscuration bilaterally and peripapillary haemorrhages. No concomitant medications were reported. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and the event is assessed as related.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Preterm labour; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case initially received from other health professional on 10-Sep-2019, concerning a 25-year-old pregnant, female subject of body weight 179 lbs, height 64 in and body mass index (BMI) 30,7, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had two previous pregnancies with two spontaneous abortions. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation. Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The subject did not have a prior history of use of tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject's medical history included depression. Concomitant medication included Prenatal vitamin (vitamin NOS, mineral NOS), clonazepam and Effexor XR (venlafaxine hydrochloride).  The subject's last menstrual period was on 23-Apr-2018 and estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated delivery date was reported as 28-Jan-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 07-Jun-2018, the subject underwent ultrasound scan and no major congenital malformation was noted.  On 16-Aug-2018, the subject underwent ultrasound scan and quad screen and no major congenital malformation was noted.  On 17-Sep-2018, the subject underwent ultrasound scan and no major congenital malformation was noted.  On 08-Oct-2018, at gestational age of 24 weeks, the subject was administered Flucelvax QIVc [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 252664, dose: 0.5 ml, expiration date, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.  On 06-Dec-2018, the subject underwent ultrasound scan and no major congenital malformation was noted.  At gestational age of 36.9 weeks [explicitly coded as 'premature labour'), the subject vaginally delivered female neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 3459 grams, head circumference was 33 cm and length was 50.8 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes), and no data was reported for APGAR score at ten minutes. No major congenital malformation was identified at birth.  This case is linked to 201904583, the corresponding child case.  Company comment: The patient was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD at 24 weeks of gestational age (coded as vaccine exposure during pregnancy). The patient experienced premature labour (at gestational age of 36.9 weeks) 3 months after vaccination. Chronology seems plausible. The patient's medical history of two spontaneous abortions and concomitant use of clonazepam and Effexor XR confound causality. However, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and it is assessed as related. The event of vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.; Reporter's Comments: The patient was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD at 24 weeks of gestational age (coded as vaccine exposure during pregnancy). My left arm hurt a great deal all the time for 2 weeks after getting the vaccine on Jan. 15, 2019, with stiffness beginning in my both my arms. I woke up around the date of  Jan. 25, 2019 and could not left myself up from my bed because my arms were too weak and I couldn't lift them up. I had to roll out of bed and crawl to a chest of drawers to pull myself up using the knobs.   Along with that, my hips and legs became stiff and painful. By Jan. 31 and shortly before that date, I had trouble walking and could only take small steps. After taking Prednisone 10mg  starting May 13, 2019 I felt as I could finally walk and move well.  On this date of 9-13-19 I still feel a lot of pain in my arms and legs and the pain comes and goes.  A rheumatologist confirmed  on July 29, 2019 that I have Polymyalgia. I've tapered off to 7 mg a day of Prednisone but still feel the symptoms, although I can get out of bed easier and walks outside a few times a week when the pain isn't severe.

Intramuscular formulation administered by other route; Tenderness; Redness; Swelling; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of tenderness in a 71-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 4th July 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 3rd September 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 4th July 2019, 30 min after receiving Shingrix and not applicable after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced tenderness, erythema and swelling. On 3rd September 2019, the patient experienced intramuscular formulation administered by other route. On an unknown date, the outcome of the tenderness, erythema and swelling were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the intramuscular formulation administered by other route was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the tenderness, erythema and swelling to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information received were as follows: The patient received Shingrix on left arm. Approximately 30 minutes after the injection, the patient experienced tenderness, redness, and swelling. After 36 hours, the symptoms resolved. The patient received 2nd dose of Shingrix, was not administered intramuscularly because she didn't even feel the vaccine going into her muscle, which led to inappropriate route of vaccine administration. The patient experienced no local site reaction at all. The reporter consented to follow up. The reporter could follow-up with the patient directly.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient has redness at site of administration. Also stated site of administration is slightly warm upon touching.

Next day, during volleyball game heart started racing, arms felt funny--tingling in her fingertips--, felt somewhat faint.   Reporter is not sure for long how symptoms lasted; patient ate and went to sleep. Next day patient went to school, complained that she was weak, that her vision was not right�seeing little things-- and started crying.   On 8/28 at around 12:38pm, took patient to ER visit due to the palpitations. All symptoms experienced were discussed, including ringing in the ears, with the doctor and upon discharge ER doctor recommended follow-up with doctor to possibly get a holter cardiac monitor a psychiatric consultation. On 8/29 went to follow-up with doctor after ER visit, again mentioned all the symptoms to the doctor including palpitations and that arm was sore/hurting at vaccination site. Doctor did not link any of the symptoms to the vaccination and gave order for labs and a holter cardiac monitor. Doctor also revoked the sports clearance that had been granted to the patient.  On 8/29 went to get labs including blood and urine samples; all came back normal.  Not sure, which day it was after the vaccination but patient woke up with a swollen arm and swollen help; she thought her allergy medication helped to control it. On 8/31, patient started wearing monitor until 9/9.   Patient went back to the same ER on 9/4 complaining of bad shortness of breath; the doctor still considered that it was related to panic attacks.  At the ER, heart monitor company (Cardiomedic) faxed results they had so far for review and they showed heart a little heart rate increase but not out of normal.  Contacted doctor to let them know they were back at the ER but did not have a follow-up appointment available until 9/9.   On 9/7, patient had difficulty breathing again so taken to doctor to get possibly a breathing treatment.   Per doctor, she could not give patient a breathing treatment and specified that the symptoms mentioned were not related to the vaccine.  Patient's parents were given the vaccine handouts that day�they had not received them before.   Patient reviewed the vaccine adverse event sheet and highlighted the following adverse events that were listed:   soreness, redness and swelling at site, shoulder and face, headache, feeling dizzy, vision problems, ringing in the ears, and difficulty breathing.   Went to follow-up appointment with doctor on 9/9 and discussed all symptoms highlighted and they were still blaming it on anxiety; patient's parents filed a complaint with the facility about the doctor's care they had received so far and that they did not receive the proper paperwork.  Patient is following up with cardiologist to review holter heart monitor results.  The cardiologist in their facility did not have any open appointments soon so she is going to a different one.  As of now patient reports that vision have improved, she still has difficulty breathing, arm still hurts bad and still is feeling weak.  Patient will also use the Behavioral order to follow-up for anxiety just in case.     Patient started taking Omeprazole for acid reflux on 8/27 and continued taking it daily until 9/7 when doctor told her to stop The last vaccination patient received was in March for Meningitis.
CUR_ILL: Prior week heart rate racing  but cleared for sports physical; Heart racing probably due to anxiety

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was very nervous and anxious about getting a vaccine and had not eaten since 6 am. About 30 seconds after vaccine was administered patient stated she felt a little dizzy and started to look pale. I had the patient remain seated in the chair and within a minute she passed out, going completely limp in the chair. Her boyfriend was standing right next to her and held her up in the chair while I checked her pulse, breathing and looked at her injection site for any symptoms of allergic reaction. She did not appear to be struggling to breathe or have any symptoms of an allergic reaction. We kept her safely supported in the chair, and called out her name trying to help her regain consciousness. Within 45 to 60 seconds patient began to regain consciousness and was able to respond to her name and then answer some questions. Her color came back and we gave her water and saltine crackers. Patient stated she didn't even remember losing consciousness. Patient never experienced any difficulty breathing and the injection site did not appear red or swollen. Patient remained seated for about 25 minutes and then felt well enough to walk out of the store. When I called to check on the patient 2 hours later she had eaten and was feeling better.

On an unspecified date in 2016, she was diagnosed with adenocarcinoma of the cervix. Medical attention was sought with office visits. She had the following procedures colposcopy, loop electrical excision procedure (LEEP) and cold knife conization. On an unknown date, the adenocarcinoma was fully removed with surgery and she recovered from the event. She was monitored every 6 months with Pap smears. Eventually she would have a hysterectomy, however, she was still in her childbearing ears. It was reported at time of diagnosis, the event was not life threatening. However, if she had left the adenocarcinoma untreated, it eventually would have become life threatening. The patient mentioned that she recently had a baby. She confirmed that she was not pregnant when she received the one dose of quadrivalent human papillomavirus (types 6,11,16,18) recomb. vaccine (GARDASIL) (maternal exposure before pregnancy).  The causality between quadrivalent human papillomavirus (types 6,11,16,18) recomb. vaccine (GARDASIL) and adenocarcinoma of the cervix was not provided.  Upon internal review, adenocarcinoma of the cervix was determined to be medically significant.
