DRUG EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY; This case was reported by a healthcare professional and described the occurrence of drug exposure during pregnancy in a 18-year-old female subject who was vaccinated with tetanus toxoid, reduced diphtheria toxoid and acellular pertussis vaccine, adsorbed (Boostrix, GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis while pregnant.  Concurrent vaccination included hepatitis B vaccine recombinant (Merck) given intramuscularly on 10 October 2007. Concurrent medications included Prenatal vitamins.   On 10 October 2007 at 16:25 the pregnant subject received a dose of Boostrix, intramuscularly, at 0.5 ml in the right arm.  This was considered a case of drug exposure during pregnancy.  No events were reported.  The subject is reportedly due to deliver in December 2007.  At the time of reporting the outcome of the event was unspecified.  Upon internal review done on 13th September 2019, the pregnancy outcome was updated to lost to follow-up.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: No adverse event (No report of any adverse reactions following previous vaccinations.  No history of prenatal care.)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: VACCINE EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY; This case was reported by a healthcare professional and described the occurrence of vaccine exposure during pregnancy in a 15-year-old female subject who was vaccinated with tetanus toxoid, reduced diphtheria toxoid and acellular pertussis vaccine, adsorbed (Boostrix, GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis while pregnant.  Concurrent vaccination included hepatitis B vaccine (Recombivax, Merck), inactivated poliomyelitis virus vaccine (Sanofi) and seasonal influenza vaccine (Fluzone, Sanofi) given on 15 January 2009. Pervious vaccination included two TD vaccines given in 2005.  On 15 January 2009 at 10:45 the subject received a dose of Boostrix at 0.5 ml in the left arm. This was a case of vaccine exposure during pregnancy. No adverse events were reported.    On 27 January 2009, follow-up information was received from the reporting nurse. The nurse reported that the subject received only immunization series from her Health Department. She reported that she had no way of assessing the information requested on the Pregnancy Initial Notification Form. She tried to call unspecified phone numbers, but no one was available.  Upon internal review done on 13th September 2019, the pregnancy outcome was updated to lost to follow-up.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: No adverse event (The subject has no relevant medical history and no history of adverse events following previous vacc)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: VACCINE EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY; This prospective pregnancy case was reported by a consumer (the subject's mother) and described the occurrence of vaccine exposure during pregnancy in a 19-year-old female subject who was vaccinated with tetanus toxoid, reduced diphtheria toxoid and acellular pertussis vaccine, adsorbed (Boostrix, GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis during pregnancy. A physician or other health care professional has not verified this report.  Concurrent medications included Prenatal vitamins.   On an unspecified date in April 2011 the subject received a dose of Boostrix (details unknown), and experienced vaccine exposure during pregnancy.  The subject was 27 weeks pregnant at the time of vaccination.  The consumer believed that the dtap vaccine administered was Boostrix, but was not sure.  The subject had had 3 ultrasounds since the vaccination and there were no abnormalities or issues identified.  The pregnancy had been without complications at the time of reporting.  Estimated delivery date was 13 September 2011.   Upon internal review done on 13th September 2019, the pregnancy outcome was updated to lost to follow-up.

VACCINE EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY; This prospective pregnancy case was reported by a healthcare professional and described the occurrence of vaccine exposure during pregnancy in a 40-year-old female subject who was vaccinated with tetanus toxoid, reduced diphtheria toxoid and acellular pertussis vaccine, adsorbed (Boostrix, GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis during pregnancy.   The subject's medical history included two previous normal full-term live births. Concurrent medical conditions included anemia and depression.   Concurrent medications included Sertraline hydrochloride (Zoloft).   On 1 September 2011 the subject received a dose of Boostrix (.5 unknown units, intramuscular, unknown site), and experienced vaccine exposure during pregnancy.  The subejct was approximately 25 weeks gestation at the time of vaccination.  Date of last menstrual period was 15 March 2011 and estimated delivery date was 09 December 2011.  The subject had not been using contraception prior to becoming pregnant and the conception was reported to be normal.  Prenatal testing, including ultrasound and amniocentesis on 21 July 2011 revealed no evidence of a defect.   Upon internal review done on 16th September 2019, the pregnancy outcome was updated to lost to follow-up.      Lab Comments: Lab Tests: Ultrasound and amniocentesis on 21 July 2011 revealed no evidence of a defect.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Anemia; Live birth

On 5th September 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced blistery rash, painful rash, injection site pain, local swelling, axillary pain and inappropriate age at vaccine administration. On an unknown date, the outcome of the blistery rash, painful rash, injection site pain, local swelling, axillary pain and inappropriate age at vaccine administration were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the blistery rash, painful rash, injection site pain, local swelling and axillary pain to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information received were as follows: A day before the reporting date, at 10:30 am, the patient received Shingrix. In the evening of the day before the reporting date, the patient experienced blistery-painful rash on side. The patient called the pharmacy who gave the vaccine to ask about side effects and they told the patient to call patient's MD. The patient was seeing MD in the afternoon but wonder if this was an expected reaction. The event was not listed in the common reactions. The patient also experienced extremely painful arm at injection site and my armpit was swollen and tender on injection site arm. The reporter thought that the longer needle was used thus she thought it was intramuscular. The NDC number was reported as 58160-0823-11.

RASH ON FACE/RASH ON BODY; rash is pimply; This case was reported by a nurse via sales rep and described the occurrence of generalized rash in a 13-year-old female patient who received Men B NVS (Bexsero) (batch number ABXA12BA, expiry date 28th February 2021) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included HPV 16-18 (HPV vaccine) (batch number RO24271 ?, expiry date 8th May 2021) for prophylaxis and MENACTRA (batch number U6521AA, expiry date 26th January 2021) for prophylaxis.   On 27th August 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Bexsero, HPV vaccine and MENACTRA. In August 2019, less than a week after receiving Bexsero and HPV vaccine, the patient experienced generalized rash and papular rash. The patient was treated with doxycycline and prednisone. On an unknown date, the outcome of the generalized rash and papular rash were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the generalized rash and papular rash to be related to Bexsero and HPV vaccine.  Additional information received were as follows: The licensed vocational nurse stated that received Bexsero and Menactra a week before the reporting date and experienced a rash on their face and body that was not itchy. The reporter had had 3 patients that had experienced a rash after having Bexsero, not itchy, on the face and body. First they thought it was giving the menectra and bexsero together the other had them both. On the reporting date, the third person and she did not had any other vaccine called complaining of the same rash. The healthcare professional stated that they assumed the rash was due to Bexsero since one of the patients experienced the rash received no other vaccine.  All patients reported the rash appearing within 2 days of vaccination.  The rash was pimply in appearance on face, arms, and neck. The rash lasted for 3 weeks where she saw the doctor again on 4th September 2019 and was given doxycycline and prednisone. The patient was told to see the doctor again in 10 days. The MSL confirmed that patient had not yet been back to the office on the reporting date. For the other 2 patient's, it is unknown how long the rashes lasted and if they were treated because they only called in to report the adverse event. The reporter consented to follow up. No additional details regarding patients or product were available but licensed vocational nurse was agreeable to follow up recontact. This case is 1 of the 4 linked cases, reported by the same reporter.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediately after the vaccine, I felt no symptoms, when I went to the check out desk approximately 3-4 minutes later, I felt a surge of tightness and flushing in my head, neck and arms.  I thought I had broken out in a rash on my arms, but it didn?t appear so. The feeling intensified and I felt I needed water or something for the throat constriction. After reporting to the desk clerks that something was wrong, I sat down before being escorted into a room. The constriction feeling continued along with a severe pulsating abdominal pain- feeling like deep bone pain. I couldn?t stand because of it and the weakness in my legs. I laid down. The nurse continued to monitor me and ask questions. I felt more numbness throughout my arms, hands and legs. The constriction subsided, but was followed by my upper lip feeling swollen and numb. I felt somewhat dizzy throughout.  After awhile I determined I could drive home. I did feel somewhat unsteady, but okay. The time when I left was about noon or a little after. I came home and took a benedryl and slept for a couple of hours. I still have what feels like soreness in the hip and back areas. I felt a little short of breath and had some chest discomfort off and on the remainder of the day and next. I wonder if it was an allergic reaction common to some Ehlers- Danlos patients.
HISTORY: Hypothyroidism, high cholesterol, Ehlers-Danlos Type3 Hypermobile
PRIOR_VAX: Fainting with penicillin at age 6 approximately 1958

This Other-HCP reported on behalf of another Other-HCP . A 16-year-old female patient received meningococcal group b rlp2086 (TRUMENBA, Lot Number: X46476, Expiry date: 30Apr2020) intramuscular in right deltoid on 16Aug2019 at 0.5 ml single dose for immunization at a health fair for back to school. Medical history included asthma chronic prevention inhaler. Ongoing concomitant medications included mometasone furoate (ASMANEX) (started before 22Sep2016), fluticasone propionate (PROAIR) (noticed in 2016 already started). On 16Aug2019 a physical was did on her. The patient experienced severe pressure in chest, like she was choking, it was intense sharp pain, at level 10 on 16Aug2019. From what she read at the time, if the pressure was blood vessles constricting then this was angina. She required her rescue inhaler at least twice during these episodes and that was when she fainted on 16Aug2019. She had numbness in her arms on 17Aug2019, that progress to all 4 limbs on 03Sep2019. The biggest things with her complaint was the intense pressure on the chest, she has been in the office for the intense chest pressure for follow up. The patient did go to the Emergency Room but was not admitted into the hospital. If she kept having this then would refer her to cardiology for echocardiogram, they did do electrocardiogram (EKG) and it came out to normal and prescribed her prednisone to help with inflammation. It was also reported that there was a double temperature excursion on the vaccine, it went to highest point of 56.3 degrees Fahrenheit and above range for 7 hours, they were simultaneous, with another at 13 hours and 55mins at 32.7 degrees Fahrenheit. Her pain level was now at a 7. The patient still got lightheaded and dizzy as of 09Sep2019. All tests were done on 04Sep2019, EKG, C-reactive Protein, Creatinine Kinase, CBC/CMP, and red blood cell sedimentation rate all resulting in normal. The events "sharp pain at level 10", "numbness in her arms/progress to all 4 limbs" were considered serious as medically significant, the event "fainted/required an rescue inhaler" was considered serious as life threatening. The outcome of event "fainted" was recovered on 16Sep2019, outcome of "pain", "severe pressure in chest/ intense pressure on the chest" was recovering, outcome of "numbness in her arms, that progress to all 4 limbs" was not recovered, the outcome of rest events was unknown.; Sender's Comments: The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. She had her vaccine late evening on September 11th.  The next morning when she woke up she said her leg hurt and it hurt to walk. I just told her she would be fine.  Then I looked at her leg  when I got her dressed. It was a little swollen (which I expected) a little red and warm to the touch. She had a slight fever of 99.8.  She went to school and I picked her up at 11:30.  Her leg looked much worse. I called the dr office and they told me to put cold compress on the site and give her motrin.  I went back to work and an hour later I received a call that my daughter is really hurting. She is saying her head hurts and is not herself at all.  I called back the dr and got an apt to go in.  I saw a nurse for about 2 mins max. She looked at her leg and just said it was normal. No vitals were taken.  On the way home I stopped to pick up motrin from the store and gave it to her in the parking lot.  I picked up my son and we went home. When I got home I took her temp again (after I gave her motrin).  It was almost 103.  By that evening (5:00pm) Her whole upper thigh was huge.  Over the size of a baseball.  It was very red and very hot to the touch.  The next morning 9/13 there was no change in her leg.  Her fever was down to the upper 100's with no Motrin given.  She still said her leg hurt to walk.  On 9/14 the swelling went down slightly but was still very red and hot to the touch.  She no longer had a fever.  That evening she developed diarrhea.  9/15 she still had diarrhea that morning. Her leg was still red and  hot to the touch.  The swelling did go down a little more.  9/16 No diarrhea. The swelling continues to go down along with the redness.  It is no longer hot to the touch.
CUR_ILL: She had a cold a week prior to vaccine

Painful; Wrong Injection Technique; This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in a male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain and wrong injection technique were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were reported as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The reporter administered the 1st dose of Shingrix injection in the deltoid muscle and the patient asked why the injection was given in the deltoid muscle. Feeling of weakness; feeling of overall fever; Site of injection is very hot; Injection site red; Injection site a little tough to the touch; Side Effects; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of feeling hot in a female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 3rd September 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 3rd September 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced feeling hot and adverse drug reaction. On 4th September 2019, the patient experienced feelings of weakness. In September 2019, the patient experienced injection site warmth, injection site erythema and injection site induration. The patient was treated with paracetamol (Tylenol). On 4th September 2019, the outcome of the feeling hot was recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the feelings of weakness was unknown and the outcome of the injection site warmth, injection site erythema and injection site induration were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the adverse drug reaction was recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the feeling hot, feelings of weakness, injection site warmth, injection site erythema, injection site induration and adverse drug reaction to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. On Tuesday evening, the patient had feeling of overall fever (but no high temperature was registered on thermometer) until midday on Wednesday. The next day morning, the patient had feeling of weakness.  The patient stated, till the time of reporting, the site of injection was very hot, red and a little tough to the touch (60 plus hours post injection). The other side effects were gone about 30 hours post injection. The patient had been taking extra strength Tylenol to help and was icing the injection site.  The patient asked if these were typical reaction occurs after vaccination and also asked if GlaxoSmithKline have any suggestions for it.

that one of the nurses went to give a patient the Pentacel vaccine and didn't realize she had to mix with ActHIB portion of it, no adverse event; Initial information received on 26-Aug-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a nurse. Follow-up was done on 27-Aug-2019.  This case involves a patient of unknown demography for whom it was reported that one of the nurses went to give a patient the DIPHTHERIA/TETANUS/5 HYBRID AC PERTUSSIS/IPV(MRC5)/HIB(PRP/T) VACCINE [PENTACEL] and did not realize she had to mix with acthib portion of it (lot number, exp date, route and site of administration were not reported) on an unknown date.  The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.   It was a case of actual medication error due to product preparation issue. Following our Dr's instructions I got my Shingrix shot on 9/4. The IM shot stung more then I would have expected. I have a pre existing condition with my left leg, I had a bulging disk at L4-5 approximately 19 years ago and again involving the right leg 3 years ago. With the left leg, every once in a blue moon I would have what feels like a wasp sting about mid shin on the outside of the leg which would cause me to jump when it hits. This would happen every couple of months or so or maybe when I exerted my lower back more then I should have. On the night of the 4th morning of the 5th after I went to bed, I had that stinging event occur. The bazaar thing was that I would lay quiet and it would hit, followed by two more times forcing me to move by sheer reaction. Then I would lay still and it would happen again, so I would move again and after a while it would start again, as long as I was in motion it wouldn't hit but when I laid still it would come back. Initial "sting" followed by two more if I stayed still. This went on all evening to the point my Fitbit didn't record any sleep at all; that was a first since I've it! When I got up in the morning for the day I no longer experienced the discomfort and it did not return the next night.
OTHER_MEDS: 40 mg Atorvastatin daily, losartan 50 mg daily, ranitidine 150 bid prn, 2 grams calcium carbonate at bedtime, an occasional multivitamin
CUR_ILL: former smoker, alcohol use in the evening.

Over the course of a month my son started experiencing paralysis until he was no longer able to walk. Multiple trips to his pediatrician over the course of the month. His pediatrician was perplexed as to patient's condition. My son went from active 2 1/2 year old to paralyzed with no use of his legs.  We were told by our pediatrician to go to the emergency room. We were checked into Hospital. After a spinal tap, multiple blood tests, MRI, X-rays a Neurologist diagnosed patient with Guillain-Barr� syndrome.  We stayed in the hospital so my son could receive the IGIV treatment for a week and monitoring by doctors. He then endured months of physical therapy to regain his ability to stand/walk. This diagnosis of Guillain Barre was directly linked to the HepB vaccine.
LAB_DATA: March 2018 X-RAYS  Blood Work MRI  Spinal Tap

Generalized Vaccinia; This case was obtained from a scientific literature on date 03SEP2019.  A 19-year-old-male patient developed generalized vaccinia (GV) (PT: Generalised vaccinia) and Epstein Barr Virus Infection/ mononucleosis (PT: Infectious mononucleosis), following the administration of ACAM2000 (smallpox (vaccinia) vaccine, live)   Case report: A 19-year-old presented to his aid station with concern for a spreading vesicular rash 9 days after a primary inoculation with the smallpox vaccine. The rash was limited to the inoculation site on his left shoulder. He had no medical history of eczema, atopic dermatitis, or other rashes and reported no systemic symptoms. His vitals also were within normal limits. A clinical diagnosis of inadvertent inoculation (also termed accidental infection) with satellite lesions was made, and he was discharged with counseling on wound care and close follow-up. Two days later, on post vaccination day 11, he presented with new symptoms of a headache, fever, chills, diffuse myalgia, sore throat, and spreading erythematous macules, papules, and vesicles on his arms, chest, abdomen, back, legs, and face. His vital signs were remarkable for tachycardia with heart rate of 100 bpm and a fever of 103 degree Fahrenheit (39.4 degree Celsius). He was sent to the emergency department with a presumed generalized GV diagnosis.   A complete blood count, liver function tests, and basic metabolic panel were unremarkable. Given his symptom of pharyngitis, a rapid strep test was performed. The test was negative, and a throat culture showed no growth. A mononucleosis screen also was performed and was positive. The patient was diagnosed with mononucleosis and GV. His condition improved, and his vital signs stabilized with conservative treatment without the need for vaccine immune globulin (VIG). He convalesced for 72 hours and was referred to dermatology on the following day. He was quarantined in a single occupancy barracks room until all lesions crusted over to address the concern for spread of the virus to non-immunized coworkers or family members.   On post vaccination day 12, the patient continued to be clinically well, and he remained afebrile. The dermatologist obtained a skin biopsy from a lesion on the patient's right shin. The biopsy demonstrated marked epidermal necrosis with peripheral keratinocytes showing ballooning degeneration and viral cytopathic changes consistent with GV. Antibody titers showing high levels of Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) capsid IgM and IgG present confirmed mononucleosis infection within the past 6 months. The patient remained clinically well and was released from quarantine on post vaccination day 22 when all lesions crusted over.  Author's comment: The smallpox vaccination is unique among vaccinations. It is the only vaccine that is administered via inoculation with a bifurcated needle, requires regular follow-up care, and can be spread to casual contacts. It is important for any practitioner administering the smallpox vaccine to be aware of associated AEs. A greater knowledge of the unique challenges with the smallpox vaccine allows for better patient selection that eliminates those with conditions that impair their immune system and improves patient education.  Company' comment:The Company considers that the generalized vaccinia (GV) was probably related to the ACAM vaccination. Such widespread skin reaction to vaccine occurs due to virus dissemination beyond the initial inoculation site of small pox vaccine throughout systemic transmission. Mononucleosis is considered concurrent condition and present symptoms were probably due to a relapse or worsened due to the GV. Because the tests showed an onset of about six months, mononucleosis a concurrent infection and not considered as an adverse event. Symptoms are not coded as per MedDRA point to consider. The case met the criterion of medically significant.; Sender's Comments: The Company considers that the generalized vaccinia (GV) was probably related to the ACAM vaccination. Such widespread skin reaction to vaccine occurs due to virus dissemination beyond the initial inoculation site of small pox vaccine throughout systemic transmission. Mononucleosis is considered concurrent condition and present symptoms were probably due to a relapse or worsened due to the GV. Low lying placenta; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case initially received from other health professional on 31-Oct-2018, concerning a 30-year-old female, pregnant subject (race and ethnicity: not reported), with unknown body weight, height and body mass index (BMI), enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had no previous pregnancies. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation. Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The father did not receive any medications prior to conception. The subject did not have a prior history of use of tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's medical history was not reported. The subject's concomitant medications included Citra Natal Bloom as prenatal vitamin.  The subject's last menstrual period was on 03-Apr-2018 and estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 08-Jan-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 28-Jun-2018, nuchal translucency and first trimester screen was performed, and no major congenital malformation was found.   On 27-Jul-2018, ultrasound was performed and no major congenital malformation was found.  On 08-Oct-2018, the pregnant subject was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (batch number: YF40208, expiry date, dose, route of administration, and anatomical location: not reported) for immunization for influenza virus (explicitly considered as vaccine exposure during pregnancy). The pregnancy status of the subject was collected, and pregnancy complications included Rh negative (risk factor) and low-lying placenta.  On 05-Jan-2019, 89 days after vaccination, the subject delivered a full-term male neonate at 39.6 weeks gestation. Delivery method was vaginal. The neonate's birth weight was 3560 grams and no data was provided for head circumference and body length. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). APGAR score was not reported for 10 minutes. There were no pregnancy complications and no major congenital malformation was identified at birth.  The outcome of low lying placenta was not reported.  Significant follow up report received from other health professional on 10-Apr-2019: The delivery date (05-Jan-2019), delivery type (vaginal), birth type (live birth), fetal outcome (normal) weight (3560 grams), APGAR score (8 and 9) and delivery notes were updated in the patient tab. The narrative and case comment were amended accordingly.  Significant follow up received from other health professional on 11-Sep-2019: Laboratory data and relevant tests were updated in the relevant fields. It was provided that no major congenital malformation was identified on birth. Event of Low lying placenta was added. Therefore, the case was upgraded to serious (per medical judgement). Narrative was amended accordingly.  Company comment: A 30-year-old, pregnant female subject was administered suspect vaccine Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (coded as vaccine exposure during pregnancy). The subject was diagnosed placenta previa on an unknown date after vaccination. The decision to administer a vaccine during pregnancy is related to medical decision making by the subject and her physician and is not related to any property of the medication. The event of vaccine exposure during pregnancy was assessed as not related considering the intended use of the vaccine, while for placenta previa causality is assessed as related.; Reporter's Comments: A 30-year-old, pregnant female subject was administered suspect vaccine Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (coded as vaccine exposure during pregnancy). The subject was diagnosed placenta previa on an unknown date after vaccination. The decision to administer a vaccine during pregnancy is related to medical decision making by the subject and her physician and is not related to any property of the medication. The event of vaccine exposure during pregnancy was assessed as not related considering the intended use of the vaccine, while for placenta previa causality is assessed as related.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per order of N.P. Pt to receive HPV #2 and Flu vaccine today.  When pt was approached to receive the same,he stated, "Wait, can I go to the bathroom first?"  Pt went to bathroom to void.  Upon returning to exam room, pt stated, "I don't want any shots.  I'm scared.  I don't like shots."  Reassurance given to pt.  Offered this pt to have his dad present now, because initially he did not want dad present.  Pt states, "Yes.  Can you get my dad?"  Summoned pt's dad.  He presented into exam room and told pt to relax.  Dad informed me that pt 'gets worked up' prior to any experience that he does not want to do.  Dad states, "He even gets this way when his mother reprimands him.  He gets all worked up and like a panic attack.  He breathes fast and everything."  Reassurance given.  Dad held pt so that he could safely receive his Flu and HPV #2 vaccine.  Flu vaccine was given as ordered in right deltoid.  Pt let out a scream and said, "Ow.  That hurts me.  It's burning!"  At this point, pt's sister had entered the room and told pt to relax and settle down.  Pt began to use foul language and his sister told him that his language was inappropriate.  Dad was still holding pt and pt told him that his right arm was now ok.  Dad then informed pt that he would now get his second vaccine and then they would go home.  Pt began to cry and said that he didn't want any more shots.  Dad said to pt, "You're a big boy and you're getting just one more shot.  Don't be a baby."  Dad then informed me that he had a good hold on this pt and that I could go ahead and give the HPV vaccine.  Informed dad that pt would need to sit after receiving his HPV vaccine to assess for any side effects.  Dad stated compliancy regarding the same.  At 1615 HPV vaccine was given into pt's left deltoid area.  Pt again let out an outburst of crying.  Pt then states, "I can't breathe.  I can't breathe."  pt had a near syncopal episode.  Pt did not have any loss of consciousness.   VS:  110/76-86-26.  O2 sat 100 %.  I then assisted this pt with slowing down his breathing.  Pt was somewhat compliant and diaphoretic at this time.  Cool cloth applied to pt's forehead and neck area. RN was then in to see pt.  She attempted to give pt O2 via mask. N.P. presented and assessed pt's O2 sat still at 100%.  She stated that O2 not necessary at this time.  Pt was not responding well at this time.  Positioned pt in left side lying position.  110/80-84-24  O2 sat 100%. Per N.P., RN placed Ammonia Salts Ampule under pt's nose.  Pt immediately sat up and was combative, stating, "What happened?"  Reassurance given to pt and his dad. Informed pt that he had a near syncopal episode. M.D. In to see pt.  She heard wheezing throughout all lung fields of this pt.  Per order of M.D. Albuterol Neb was given at 1625 to pt.120/66-84-22 O2 sat 100%.  At 1633, pt was reassessed by M.D. No audible wheeze was present per M.D. At 1645:  110/60-83-20 O2 sat 100%.  Pt resting in room.  Pt then sat up and stated that he was feeling better.  Pt was alert and oriented to time, place, person and situation.  Pt told me and his dad, "I'm better now.  I want to go home."  Reassurance given to pt.  Told pt that he would be reassessed in 15" and then N.P. would determine if pt were able to go home.  At 1700, pt was breathing well with good respiratory rate.  Lung sounds clear to auscultation.  Coloring good.  Skin warm and dry.  110/60-80-18 O2 sat 100%.  Pt was then reassessed by N.P. And was then released home by the same.  Pt stood on the floor, holding his dad's hand.  Pt denied any lightheadedness or vertigo.  Pt states, "I'm just tired."  Pt was alert and oriented to time, place, person and situation.  Pt's gait was slow, but steady.  Pt ambulated to his dad's car, with the assist of his dad and his sister.

In July 2019, the patient experienced injected limb mobility decreased. On an unknown date, the patient experienced injection site pain, general body pain, ear noises, difficulty breathing, abnormal vision, generalized pruritus and lump feeling in throat. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site pain, ear noises, abnormal vision, pain in hand, headache, upper back pain, neck pain, shoulder pain, generalized pruritus, lump feeling in throat and injected limb mobility decreased were unknown and the outcome of the general body pain was not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the difficulty breathing was recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site pain, general body pain, ear noises, difficulty breathing, abnormal vision, pain in hand, headache, upper back pain, neck pain, shoulder pain, generalized pruritus, lump feeling in throat and injected limb mobility decreased to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information received were as follows: The case US2019126010 was found to be duplicate of case US2019126012. Hence case US2019126012 would be deleted and all the information of this case will be added in case US2019126010 which is the case of record for this patient. The age at vaccination was not reported. In the 2nd week of May 2019, the patient received Shingrix on left arm. Less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced pain at the injection site, which one week later spread throughout the body. Less than a year after receiving Shingrix, the patient also experienced breathing problems, vision problems and heard a whistling sound in his ear. In the morning one day before the reporting date, the patient experienced pain in his left hand, left shoulder and upper back, neck and head. Less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient could not move his left hand and had pain in the left arm and shoulder. The patient stated that he experienced this pain off and on since the 1st day that he received the vaccine. The patient stated that he had also developed itching all over the body and pain in the back of the head. The patient stated that he experienced shortness of breath and that had resolved, however now each morning, he feels like there is something in his throat. The patient said that he reported his side effects to the pharmacy manager and she called Glaxosmithkline. The reporter was unable to locate a case history for that call as he could only provide a first name and attempted to call the pharmacy manager during the call with the patient but she was not available. The reporter documented what I could understand. It was extremely difficult to understand the patient due to a language barrier. The reporter cannot clarify any information reported from the patient and documented what he could understand.  The reporter requested to contact the pharmacy manager for follow up. VACCINE EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY; This prospective pregnancy case was reported by a healthcare professional and described the occurrence of vaccine exposure during pregnancy in a 33-year-old female subject who was vaccinated with tetanus toxoid, reduced diphtheria toxoid and acellular pertussis vaccine, adsorbed (Boostrix, GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis during pregnancy.   The subject's past medical history included one previous pregnancy resulting in a normal birth of a full-term infant with no defects.  The subject had not been using contraception prior to becoming pregnant.   On 7 September 2011 at 10:45 the subject received a booster dose of Boostrix (.5 unknown units, intramuscular, left arm), and experienced vaccine exposure during the third trimester of her pregnancy.  The conception was reported to be normal.  The subject was approximately 28 weeks gestation at the time of vaccination.  Date of last menstrual period was 22 February 2011 and estimated delivery date was 29 November 2011.  Prenatal testing including ultrasounds performed on 25 April 2011 and 12 July 2011, and maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein on 08 June 2011 had revealed no evidence of a defect.  Upon internal review done on 17th September 2019, the pregnancy outcome was updated to lost to follow-up.      Lab Comments: Lab Tests: Ultrasounds performed on 25 April 2011 and 12 July 2011 revealed no evidence of a defect. Maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein on 08 June 2011 revealed no evidence of a defect.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Live birth; No adverse event (There was no relevant maternal or paternal medical history.)

Suspected vaccination failure; Shingles; Warm shooting pains which spread up his back to the should blades; Nerve pain; Muscle pain; welts on neck; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a 63-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis and VARICELLA ZOSTER VIRUS VACCINE, LIVE, OKA STRAIN (ZOSTAVAX) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included chickenpox (the patient experienced chickenpox as a child and then again around age of 32 years).   On 11th April 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 23rd August 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, the patient received ZOSTAVAX at an unknown dose. In August 2019, between 1 and 2 years after receiving Shingrix and less than 2 years after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced welts. On an unknown date, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), shingles, pain, nerve pain and muscle pain. The patient was treated with antivirals nos, antivirals nos, antivirals nos, antivirals nos (Antiviral (Drug Name Unknown)). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, welts, nerve pain and muscle pain were unknown and the outcome of the shingles and pain were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, shingles, welts, pain, nerve pain and muscle pain to be related to Shingrix and Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received 1st and 2nd dose of Shingrix on an unknown arm (right or left unknown). The reporter did not sure if the injection was in the muscle or just under the skin (subcutaneous) as he did not look at the length of the needle. About a month before the date of reporting (August 2019), the patient noticed welts on his neck. He went to the physician because he thought he might have poison oak. The doctor diagnosed him with shingles. The welts were also on his right shoulder. He was prescribed unspecified antiviral tablets which he took for about a week and the shingles resolved. The patient stated that the shingles outbreak was brief and not bad perhaps because he caught it early. It had fully resolved. The patient also mentioned that occasionally he got warm shooting pains which spread up his back to the should blades. The pain was nerve or muscle pain and was very mild and it came occasionally. It was happening before the shingles outbreak. The patient stated that he had been exercising lately so he was not sure if it could be related to exercising but not had the shingles rash in that area. It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, shingles and welts to be related to Shingrix and Shingrix. It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain, nerve pain and muscle pain to be related to Zostavax as well. The reporter consented to follow up.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Chickenpox (the patient experienced chickenpox as a child and then again around age of 32 years)

Patient received her first Shingrix vaccine on 9/16/19 at about 230pm.  Immediately after administration (after ban aid application) the patient stated she felt dizzy.  She remained seated and was given water and continued to be observed by the RPH for about 10-15 minutes before the patient told the RPH she was feeling better a able to walk to the front of the pharmacy to pay and then drive home.    The next morning  (9/17/19) the patient called the pharmacy stating that about 2 hours after the vaccine, at home, she started experiencing severe pain in her left arm and shoulder.  The pain had her screaming, becoming short of breath and lead to uncontrollable shaking of her arm and head.  She was taken to the local ED where she was given 2 doses of pain medication.  She had many tests that ruled out a seizure, but she did have multiple x-rays that the MD ruled may have shown that the vaccine was administered too high in the arm.   The patient then discharged from the ED at 930pm on 9/16/19.   During her call to the pharmacy at 1030am on 9/17/19 she was still had a lot of pain in her arm and shoulder and was awaiting her spouse to return from the pharmacy with her pain meds.  She stated that the ED MD attributed her SOB and shaking all to the pain she had been feeling.  Her plan was to rest.  Her chart was documented with the reaction and it was advised that for now, she does not plan to receive the 2nd dose of the Shingirx vaccine.

VACCINE EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY; This prospective pregnancy case was reported by a healthcare professional and described the occurrence of vaccine exposure during pregnancy in a 25-year-old female subject who was vaccinated with tetanus toxoid, reduced diphtheria toxoid and acellular pertussis vaccine, adsorbed (Boostrix, GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis during pregnancy.   The subject's past medical history included two previous pregnancies resulting in normal births of two full-term infants with no defects.  Prior to becoming pregnant the subject had not been using contraception.  On 7 September 2011 at 12:00 the subject received a booster dose of Boostrix (o.5 unknown units, intramuscular, left arm), and experienced vaccine exposure during the third trimester of her pregnancy.  The conception was reported to be normal.  The subject was approximately 28 weeks gestation at the time of vaccination.  Date of last menstrual period was 25 January 2011 and estimated delivery date was 27 November 2011.  Prenatal testing including ultrasounds on 11 April 2011 and 20 June 2011, and maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein on 10 June 2011, had revealed no evidence of a defect.   Upon internal review done on 17th September 2019, the pregnancy outcome was updated to lost to follow-up.      Lab Comments: Lab Tests: Ultrasound tests on 11 April 2011 and 20 June 2011 revealed no evidence of a defect. Maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein on 10 June 2011 revealed no evidence of a defect.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Live birth; No adverse event (There was no relevant maternal or paternal medical history.)

On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in arm, nausea, headache, general body pain, influenza-like symptoms, feeling unwell and diarrhea were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain in arm, nausea, headache, general body pain, influenza-like symptoms, feeling unwell and diarrhea to be related to Shingrix. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient was flush and felt warm to the touch. She didn't register a fever that day but temperature was taken multiple times. She was very fussy (crying and didn't want to eat) around dinner time and I took her upstairs to get her ready for bed around 6:30pm. I gave her the bottle while I changed her diaper and put on pajamas. When I took the bottle away, she stared blankly and I picked her up. Her body went limp and her eyes rolled back. I immediately patted her back and yelled her name and she came back to consciousness within a couple of seconds. She cried for a little while and I gave her a pacifier to help soothe her. This all happened between 6:30 and 6:40pm.
LAB_DATA: I took the patient to the ER and they ran an EKG on her. They said it looked normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Mom reports in the early afternoon following his morning vaccines listed above, patient began complaining of headache, nausea and malaise so he went to his room to lay down.  She heard him making strange noises, so she went to check on him.   He was laying on his bed moaning with b/l arms flexing and extending at elbows and shoulders shrugging - she spoke to him and he was awake and able to respond, so she went to him and held him and his arms stopped moving.  She reports his arms were moving for ~1 minute while she was there but was unsure how long they'd been moving prior to her entering the room.  She asked him if he was moving his arms because his head hurt, and he denied moving his arms intentionally.  He complained it felt like someone was "kicking him in the head," and indicated his forehead.  She noted his temperature was 100.8 at this time.  She reports she gave him ibuprofen prior to the episode listed above, but timing is not quite clear.  Mom put a cool cloth on his forehead, his fever came down and he was able to sleep a bit throughout the night.  He continues to have b/l upper arm and shoulder twitching that is involuntary.  He still has headache this morning, but it is less severe.    Patient reports headache last night was 8/10, today is 4/10.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: unable to lift her arm/patient's difficulty in lifting lasted 3 days; red stripe that appeared 5 inches below and 5 inches above injection site; injection site was hot, swollen, there was pain; injection site was hot, swollen, there was pain; injection site was hot, swollen, there was pain; This spontaneous report was received from an office manager referring to a 38-year-old adult female patient. The patient's concurrent condition included rheumatoid arthritis and immunodeficiency. The patient's medical history and drug allergies were not reported. The patient's concomitant therapy included methotrexate. On 12-SEP-2019, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) via intramuscular route for immunodeficiency (lot/batch number and expiry date were reported as S009945 and 10-AUG-2020 respectively) (strength and dose were not reported). On 13-SEP-2019, the patient had complaints of being unable to lift her arm (arm where dose was administered) which lasted for 3 days as her range of motion was limited with swelling (movement disorder), there was a red stripe that appeared 5 inches below and 5 inches above injection site (injection site erythema), injection site was hot (injection site warmth), swollen (injection site swelling) and there was pain to touch (injection site pain). The patient was treated for the events with Benadryl, compresses and ibuprofen and sought medical attention. There was no overdose and product quality complaint reported. The adverse event was not cancer and the patient did not die. The outcome of the events were reported as recovering. The causality of the events with respect to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was not reported.

from the patient   I was offered the shingles vaccine on Thursday. I always knew I'd get one bc my mom got shingles. So, with no questions or more info, I got the shot at about 10 am on Thursday. I started to feel different that evening with tired muscles which usually means I'm getting sick. I felt agitated at bedtime about 12 hours later. about 14 hours after the shot,  I awoke out of a sound sleep with electric shock type feelings in my stomach (the feeling you get if you are looking down at something when someone slams on the breaks - the surge of anxiety you get all at once). When I stood up, I felt like I'd been hit by a train.  I guess you'd say flu-like symptoms. My arm was swollen and super sore too. I was sick for two days and super tired on the third. I felt exhausted again last night. I am telling you all this in case it is supposed to be reported (CDC?) or putting in my record or something. That was horrible and I'm am not looking forward to the second shot!! Should I even get it if it made me sick?

2 minutes after receiving a flu shot, patient told her father she was  dizzy, then fainted immediately.  Her father stated this had happened many times before, due to anxiety.  Her father,  tried to rouse her,and we applied cold packs and cloths to her head.  She briefly came around and spoke to her father, but continued to be pale and dizzy.  After about 5 minutes she fainted again.  She was responsive after a couple more minutes, and started to feel better.  Her father thought she would do best to go home but I asked them to stay for further monitoring, as she was not able to walk or support herself.  I took her blood pressure at approximately 15 and 25 minutes after the initial fainting, with readings of 116/75 P96 and 114/76 P87, respectively.  Normal breathing and absence of allergic signs such as hives, rash, and angioedema were noted, and she gradually became less pale and more responsive.  She left with her family with assistance, and her called me 1 our later to let us know that she was better, and walked for the vehicle to her home unassisted, and had no new symptoms.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Gave the patient a flu shot and she did really well. As I was giving the mother her flu shot, she said, "mom that wasn't bad" and then when the mother bled a little and the daughter saw and passed out. She passed out, fell and hit her head. She regained conscience right away, and the mother started asking her questions to make sure she didn't have a concussion. She was able to recall everything. I offered to call 911 but the mother said that wasn't necessary. Ice was provided and she sat for a bit while the mother and I talked. The daughter had never gone through this before but the mother has experienced this where she faints at the sight of blood. We asked patient if it was because it was the sight of blood that caused her to faint and she said yes. The mother carried her and she felt better. I reached out later in the day to see how patient was doing and the mother said she was resting and was going to give Tylenol for the bruise on her head. pneumonia; the vaccine did not prevent shingles; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. On or about 06-APR-2016, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles.         On an unknown date, "few months" of receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient developed and was diagnosed with pneumonia. The vaccine did not prevent shingles, but rather caused the patient to contract pneumonia. As a direct and proximate result of the defective Zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. The patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, pain and suffering and other damages. As a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The outcome of the event was considered to be not recovered.  Pneumonia was considered to be disabling.  Upon internal review pneumonia was considered to be medically significant.

confirmed VZV infection by PCR of skin lesions on 8/30; patient was diagnosed with leukemia; vesicular lesions; This spontaneous report was received from a physician via former company representative refers to a 18 year old patient. The patient's concurrent condition included leukaemia. Information on medical history, concomitant mediactions were not reported.  On 30-JUL-2019, the patient was vaccinated with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (VARIVAX) (strength, dose, frequency, anatomical location, route, lot # and expiry date not reported) for prophylaxis. On 02-AUG-2019, the patient experienced leukaemia. The patient started chemo including a 28-day course of prednisone. Subsequently, on an unknown date in August 2019, the patient experienced rash vesicular, which started out on the neck and was initially considered as a possible case of acne (vesicular lesions). On 30-AUG-2019, the patient experienced varicella infection (VZV infection) and it was confirmed by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) of skin lesions. It was also reported that it would be helpful to confirm that this was vaccine strain. The former company representative suggested the physician, if he would test the sample or would suggest another hospital physician. The reporter also stated that the patient was doing well after the course of prednisone. The rash had resided and there were no longer any lesions from which to obtain a sample. The only available sample was the one used for PCR testing. The outcome of rash vesicular was considered as not recovered. The outcome of leukaemia was considered to be recovering and the outcome of varicella was unknown. Causality assessment was not provided.  Upon internal review, the event leukaemia was determined to be medically significant.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had previously received Fluzone 0.25 in previous seasons without reaction. He was given Fluzone 0.5 IM on 9/5/19 and was initially noted to have some pain with refusal to bear weight on the left leg about 4 hours after the immunization was given. The following evening 9/6/19 about 29 hours after the immunization was given he was noted to have significant circumferential swelling of the left leg. There was no notable warmth or erythema concerning for cellulitis or type I sensitivity reaction, only extensive limb swelling in the same leg as the injection was given. He was able to move move and use leg well, and swelling was notably improved the following day.
OTHER_MEDS: None, however started on Amoxicillin orally within 24 hours of being given the vaccination.
CUR_ILL: Diagnosed with acute otitis media bilaterally on the day of immunization being given.
ALLERGIES: No known drug allergies.  Food allergies to milk, egg, flax seed managed by allergist. Cleared for flu vaccine by allergist.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Gardasil and menactra given in the right arm, and tolerated well.  Tdap given in the left arm and promptly after vaccine delivered, patient leans forward and his body tenses.  I am able to prevent him from falling and help him up onto the examination table, where he arouses with some mild confusion.  The incident lasted about 5-10 seconds.  He states he was really nervous about getting the vaccines today.  I examine him and find everything WNL.  Provide him with some water and graham crackers (from the school nurse), and he starts to feel better.  Mother states that has never happened before.  After some more rest, he feels well and mother opts to take him home.
HISTORY: He is underweight with BMI at 0 percentile

Not able to sleep; Trouble breathing; Throat closed up; Tired all day; Coughing; Feeling achy; This is a spontaneous case, initially received from other non-health professional via Communications (reference number: SEQ19-02681) on 13-Sep-2019, concerning a 65-year-old, female patient.   The patient's medical history included Augmentin (amoxicillin, clavulanic acid) for unknown indication.   On 12-Sep-2019, the patient was administered Fluad [Influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, MF59, dose, route of administration, anatomical location, batch number and expiration date: not reported] as protection against seasonal influenza.  On the same day, 12 hours after vaccination, the patient's throat closed up and she had trouble breathing. The patient was not able to sleep, had been tired all day, along with coughing and feeling achy. As reported, the patient had a reaction similar to this after taking Augmentin years ago, but at that time, she also had a rash, which she did not have now. Shingles; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation referring to a female patient of unknown age. The patient's pertinent medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications were not reported. On 13-APR-2017, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot #, expiration date, dosage and route of administration were not provided) for routine health maintenance and for  the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On 14-SEP-2017, the patient was diagnosed with shingles after experiencing extreme pain and an outbreak of blisters on her legs, arms and ribcage which resulted in medical treatment. This outbreak lasted for at least three weeks. On or about 02-NOV-2017, the patient was diagnosed with a second shingles outbreak. On 25-NOV-2017, the patient was diagnosed with a third outbreak of shingles after reporting to her physician with lesions on her side and a feeling like "something was biting her from inside". The patient continued to have reoccurring shingles outbreaks throughout the end of 2017 and throughout 2018 as a result of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), including extreme pain and numbness in her left leg which all resulted in medical treatment. Pain and tingling sensations in her skin, as a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), were permanent and continued at the time of the report. It was also specified that the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable disfiguring injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life and physical impairment. the event shingles was considered to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination.  Herpes zoster was considered to be disabling due to the severe, permanent and incurable injuries.

9/12/19 Fever of 102deg and stopped walking an standing 9/13/19 Fever of 100.7 with regular Tylenol, still not standing or walking and noticeable reduced movement of the legs , crying with passive movement of her legs. Took her in to PCP where she had absent reflexes and was sent home with instruction to use motrin. 9/14/19 Fever 100.6 with regular Tylenol, very fussy and now not crawling in addition to standing or walking. Went to ER where imaging ruled out any hip dysfunction or LE fractures. Absent reflexes. Performed an enema due to stool being seen on abdominal x-ray. Was sent home with instruction to return in 24 hours if not resolved. 9/15/19 Now unable to roll over, sit up independently and control her head. Went back to ER due to progression of weakness and she was admitted to the hospital. Absent reflexes. Lumbar puncture was negative. Presentation consistent with guillain barre syndrome and Physicians got approval to use IVIG treatment. 1st dose administered of IVIG.  9/16/19 No change in muscle tone or movement. No more fever. Spinal/brain MRI with and without contrast completed and was normal. Treated with 2nd dose of IVIG and started antibiotic for UTI as well.  9/17/19 Improvement in her movement with head control and kicking her legs. Beginning to be able to roll to her side. Continues use of antibiotic for UTI. 9/18/19 More improvement in movement, now able to roll and briefly bear weight on her legs with support. Good head control and pushing up from prone into crawl position. Discharged from hospital to home. 9/19/19 More improvement in movement, now able to crawl and pull to stand.
LAB_DATA: 9/14/19 X-ray imaging ruled out any hip or LE fractures. Normal hip ultrasound bilaterally. Absent reflexes. Blood draw showing elevated CRP and WBC. 9/15/19 Absent reflexes. Lumbar puncture was negative.  9/16/19  Spinal/brain MRI with and without contrast completed and was normal.

On Tuesday, 09/03/2019 I took my healthy 1 year old daughter for her 12-month visit where she received the recommended dose of Varicella. The injection was administered by her Pediatrician to the left upper thigh. By Wednesday, 09/04 evening my daughter became febrile with a fever that spike to its highest 104�F by Thursday 09/05/2019 which was associated with shivering and loss of appetite. The fever persisted despite of oral Tylenol and Motrin given to my daughter. Finally, her pediatrician administered a rectal suppository in the office on 09/05 which helped to reduce the fever, however, it did spike again that evening. The fever lasted until Saturday 09/07 and my daughter began to show signs of improvement by Sunday 09/08. Monday 09/09 my daughter developed what I thought were cold symptoms which included cough, congestion and runny nose; this lasted a week. On Sunday 09/15/2019 I noticed some inflammation at the site of her injection which I began to keep an eye on throughout the day; by Monday 3 vesicles were formed on her left thigh and one in the center of her chest. By Monday evening the vesicles continued to appear and the swelling at the injection site became more prominent. I took my daughter to an after hour Urgent Care on Tuesday 09/17 evening to express my concerns and all they could say was its viral. Keeping in mind that my daughter did not have nor has she developed any vesicles on her hands or feet, therefore, the prognosis of coxsackie would not apply. Additionally we co-sleep and I have not developed any symptoms throughout this entire time and coxsackie is extremely contagious. It is now September 20, 2019 and finally some of the vesicles on my daughter?s body are beginning to heal especially the ones at the site of injection. I will continue to monitor and keeping a diary along with photos to further assist with any information needed regarding this matter.
ALLERGIES: N.K.D.A with a history of  lactose intolerance

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received MMR, Varicella, and Influenza vaccines at Public Health Immunization Clinic. Patient tolerated vaccines well, returned to the waiting room to wait while sister's immunizations were drawn up, and per patient's mom and aunt, fainted.  Per patient's mother, patient was standing in front of her as she was seated in a chair, complained of a headache, and then started to fall forward. Mother caught patient before he fell and no injury sustained. Patient then had moments of lethargy, whining, and crying for three to four minutes. No difficulty breathing. Face pale according to vaccinating nurse.  Patient was laid supine on mom and aunt's laps for a couple minutes, when it was determined he had not eaten in 7 hours.  A small candy bar, a bottle of Boost drink, and a bottle of water given. No prior history of syncope. Patient's sister reacted in same manner on 9/17/19 (VAERS report also submitted) with two short seizures afterwards (this child with history of Epilepsy). Reassessment after candy and Boost started showed improvement in color, activity, and symptoms.  Patient and family remained in the waiting area for another 10 minutes without further incidence. Instructed mother and aunt that children to be vaccinated with PCP for a more controlled environment.
Patient said she was shopping later on that day and passed out. Didn't feel that way at all right after vaccine for earlier in the day. No signs of allergic rxn, simply fainted then was fine.
Give Meningoccal immunization on 09/17/2019. Immunization was not due until 11/12/2019 which is slightly under 2 months from now.  Last Dose 06/25/2015 - No adverse reactions

Starting the following day of the injections given, swelling and warmth began along with slight fever. Tylenol was given for fever and cool wash cloth was used for swelling. Next day Thursday the 19th of September 2019 around 8:30 am I noticed extreme swelling and blisters forming.  I called office and they said to bring him in. They saw him and prescribed antibiotics, steroids, pain reliever, and a cream for the site. Also drew a line surrounding the swollen site and said if swelling went outside of border to take baby to the ER or if a fever of 100.4 or higher was present. Made follow up visit for 1 week. Later in that same day around 6:00 pm the swelling had worsened and went outside of lines. Took baby to ER and and said to give double dose of antibiotics and to bring him back the following day to check up.  It is the 20th day of September while I write this and still early in the morning. The swelling has gone even farther outside of the line almost wrapping around the entire thigh but redness has slightly subsided.
CUR_ILL: Small cold a week prior to visit.
PRIOR_VAX: Unknown name of vaccine. Age 6-9 months at time of reaction

Pt received Shingrex vaccination on Monday, Sept. 16, 2019 at pharmacy.  (pt originally reported she received the vaccination on the 17th, pharmacy then pt confirmed it was Monday, Sept 16, 2019).  Pt called her doctor's office on Friday, Sept. 20, 2019 to report her symptoms.  Reports by noon on the day she received the vaccine noted left arm soreness, by mid afternoon developed chills, excessive thirst, nausea, fatigue, required sips of water to help her swallow.  Symptoms continued all night, next AM awoke with headache, chills continued with nausea, and excessive fatigue. Tylenol relieved the headache. Next day chills decreased, fatigue started to improve, arm soreness left. Next day developed sores and pain under her tongue, developed bumps on her tongue.  Symptoms continued to improve, except for tongue and mouth sores and spots.  Chills were gone on day 4, fatigues improving, no nausea and thirst improved.   Today, Friday 9-20-19 chills, fatigue gone, soreness remains in mouth and tongue.  Denies ever experiencing a rash, itching, difficulty breathing or chest pressure/pain, no facial swelling.   First Shingrex received was at pharmacy (same) on 7-9-19 and experienced no adverse reactions.

The vaccine was the second dose of Shingrix. The first was uneventful other than a very sort left arm. The second resulted again in a very sore left arm and a low grade fever the next day. The other symptoms came about three weeks later and now, on September 21, have not subsided: on the inner thighs and the back of the thighs. Sensitive to clothes rubbing, even skin on skin, and sensitive when sitting. Symptoms have variously been burning, irritation, and what feels like heightened nerve endings. There has never been a rash. I was first prescribed a topical steroid which I took for about a week, and then a dermatologist told me to stop it because I did not have signs of a rash. It was triamcinolone acetonide 0.1%. . After around two weeks, I saw a neurologist who prescribed gabapentin - 100 mg twice a day which I could increase to the same dosage three times I day. I started that yesterday.
LAB_DATA: None to date. Exams by an urgent care doctor, an internist, two dermatologists and a neurologist have so far been unable to diagnose the condition. The urgent care doctor thought I had shingles, but everyone else disagreed, and wanted me to take an antiviral medication. I have filled the RX but have never taken it. I am thinking now that I should.

The patient reported that, she received her 1st dose of Shingrix in the mid August 2019. The patient had expected fatigue reaction, but in addition she developed a shooting nerve pain from the corner of eye to just below her nose and just below nose she developed a red blister. She then quickly took acyclovir which had been prescribed for a cold sore and it went away. The patient enquired hat, whether she should take acyclovir prophylactically before receiving 2nd Shingrix dose. The patient further stated, this reaction was not listed anywhere and since Shingrix was not a live vaccine, she did not understand how she could have a case of shingles, since there was no denying that she had tingling, pain or blister. To answer patient's question, the call center representative provided information that, Shingrix does not contain any live virus, so it can not cause Shingles. Also there were no known interactions between Shingrix and acyclovir. The patient then asked, could Shingrix cause an outbreak of oral herpes in a new location, might be just from whacking the immune system but the call center representative denied it by explaining her that, shingles and herpes are two different infections caused by two different viruses. Shingles is caused by the varicella zoster virus (VZV), the same virus that causes chickenpox. Herpes is caused by the herpes simplex virus.

She sometimes couldn't sleep because of the arm pain; Swollen bicep muscle; The vaccine may have been given in the bicep muscle and not up higher where it normally should be; Soreness in the arm; malaise; swelling in the area where she received the shingrix shot\lump in arm; It was red and painful; It was red and painful; she couldn't hardly move her arm; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a 81-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included denosumab (Prolia) for osteoporosis.   Previously administered products included Prolia with an associated reaction of pain.   On 1st August 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 12th August 2019, the patient started Prolia (subcutaneous) at an unknown dose and frequency. On 1st August 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced pain in arm, malaise and vaccine administered at inappropriate site. In August 2019, the patient experienced extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, injection site erythema and injected limb mobility decreased. On an unknown date, the patient experienced difficulty sleeping and muscle swelling. On 2nd August 2019, the outcome of the pain in arm and malaise were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, injection site erythema and injected limb mobility decreased were recovering/resolving and the outcome of the difficulty sleeping, muscle swelling and vaccine administered at inappropriate site were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain in arm, malaise, extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, injection site erythema, injected limb mobility decreased, difficulty sleeping and muscle swelling to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter stated that the patient experienced soreness in the arm and malaise for about a day and then it resolved. On  12th October 2019, the patient went into receive her 14th dose of Prolia, which she did in the left arm also but in the subcutaneous tissue on the back upper side of her left arm.  The patient developed swelling in the area where she received the shingrix shot, it was red and painful.  The patient noted it was so swollen she looked like a football player.  it was down to the elbow. The patient returned to her Endocrinologist where she received the Prolia on 8/19, because that was the last shot and it was so far after the Shingrix shot. An MRI and ultrasound of her arm were done to rule out blood clot and ruptured muscle.  The patient was told Prolia shot wouldn't cause that reaction and she was referred to a bone doctor.  Blood tests were also performed and negative along with the Ultrasound and MRI.   The patient saw the bone doctor on 30th August 2019,  she states she could not hardly move her arm to dress herself and the pain was worse. The patient noted she sometimes could not sleep because of the arm pain. The patient also noted lump in the arm. The bone doctor showed her on the MRI that she had a very swollen bicep muscle. The patient was concerned when she saw the MRI film as she believes the vaccine may have been given in the bicep muscle and not up higher where it normally should be, which led to vaccine administered at inappropriate site. The patient believes it was given on the front of the arm, in the middle between her shoulder and elbow. The patient noted the Prolia was given to the back of the arm but appeared a little higher than normal.  The patient noted she had improved significantly,  she still had difficulty holding her arm up and out but the pain is about 95 percent better.   The patient stated the bone doctor has her doing arm exercises and recommended she receive the shingrix second shot in her right arm, which she stated she would not do. The patient states she would not be able to go that lone with her dominant arm in pain or with decreased mobility. The patient plans to discuss the second shot with her  Endocrinologist and her primary care physician. The reporter consented to follow up. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Neurodermatitis; Seasonal allergy; This case (DE-PEI-PEI2019005917) was received from a consumer via health authority (EMA) on 09-Sep-2019. It described a 19-year-old male consumer who developed neurodermatitis (PT: neurodermatitis) and pollinosis (PT: seasonal allergy) after administration of Typhoral L, Pocken and Telanol for prophylactic vaccination.  Case report: The consumer took a dose of Typhoral-L on 14-Jul-1976, along with Pocken on 18-Aug-1976 and Tetanol on 02-Jul-1976. Subsequently, he developed pollinosis and neurodermitis in 1976 & 1977, respectively. The consumer showed disabling/incapacitating.  Action taken with Typhoral L with respect to the event pollinosis was unknown, while with respect to the event neurodermatitis was not applicable while that with Pocken, and Tetanol with respect to the events pollinosis. The consumer had recovered with sequelae from the reported events.  Company's Comment: In this case, it was reported that a 19-year-old adult male consumer developed neurodermatitis and pollinosis after the administration of Typhoral L, Pocken, and Tetanol. There is lack of information regarding start date of events, course of events, medical history and concomitant medications. Hence, the causality is assessed as not assessable for the reported events with respect to intake of Typhoral-L.; Sender's Comments: Company's Comment: In this case, it was reported that a 19-year-old adult male consumer developed neurodermatitis and pollinosis after the administration of Typhoral L, Pocken, and Tetanol. There is lack of information regarding start date of events, course of events, medical history and concomitant medications. Hence, the causality is assessed as not assessable for the reported events with respect to intake of Typhoral-L.

post herpetic neuralgia following chronic pain after the shingles outbreak; erythematous macular rash noted over her right face with burning pain/ diagnosed with shingles; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On or around 20-MAY-2016, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot # and expiry date were not provided) for routine health maintenance and the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date in 2016 (reported as within two weeks after vaccination), she suffered from an erythematous macular rash noted over her right face with burning pain. The patient was ultimately diagnosed with shingles and later diagnosed with post herpetic neuralgia following chronic pain after the shingles outbreak. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination, the patient's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). She also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination, she suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.  The reporter considered the events to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The events were considered to be disabling.
