Itchy Rash; Burning/lips burning/Lips were burning/sides of mouth were burning; Mouth Blisters; feeling sunburned/ear burning; Rash across chest/on shoulders/on arm/on back/on face/on earlobe; lips rash; rash on external genitalia; genitalia burning; blisters on tip of tongue/blister on underneath tongue; Lips were peeling; side of mouth were cracking; difficulty in brushing; Redness on her arm; Swelling on arm; Sore Arm; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of erythema of extremities in a adult female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (thrice). Previously administered products included Beta-blocker. Concurrent medical conditions included drug allergy (allergy to an unspecified beta blocker).   On 20th August 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On 21st August 2019, 1 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced erythema of extremities, swelling arm and pain in arm. On an unknown date, the patient experienced itchy rash, oral discomfort, blistering of mouth, burning sensation skin, rash, rash lips, genital rash, genital burning, tongue blistering, peeling lips, cracked lips and activities of daily living impaired. The patient was treated with benadryl (nos) (Benadryl). On 3rd September 2019, the outcome of the erythema of extremities, swelling arm and pain in arm were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the itchy rash was recovering/resolving and the outcome of the oral discomfort and blistering of mouth were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the burning sensation skin, rash, rash lips, genital rash, genital burning, tongue blistering, peeling lips, cracked lips and activities of daily living impaired were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the erythema of extremities, swelling arm, pain in arm, itchy rash, oral discomfort, blistering of mouth, burning sensation skin, rash, rash lips, genital rash, genital burning, tongue blistering, peeling lips, cracked lips and activities of daily living impaired to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix in her right arm, and the following day having redness, swelling and soreness on her arm.  The redness described as being as wide as a softball as far as area, but not raised as high as a softball. Local reactions reported to have lasted approximately 2 weeks.  The patient had itchy rash developed that comes and then goes away following oral Benadryl 50mg that is taking throughout the day.  The rash has appeared across chest, shoulders, arm, back, lips, earlobes, external genitalia, and face.  The caller still has bouts of recurrent rash that was suppressed following oral Benadryl.  The caller reported lips, earlobes and genitalia as burning or feeling sunburned, and caller also reports blisters in mouth on the tip of tongue and underneath tongue.  The lips were burning and peeling and the sides of mouth were cracking and burning.  The caller describes difficulty in brushing teeth due to burning sensitivity in mouth from toothpaste.  The burning sensations and oral blisters resolved in approximately 1 week. The reporter consented to follow up. In the mix of events, the caller reports discovering an allergy to an unspecified beta blocker that has at the time of reporting been stopped and switched to a different therapy. The caller unsure if side effects are from Shingrix vaccine or something else.  The caller inquires if she should receive 2nd dose.Referred to health care professional.  The caller has appointment tomorrow with her dermatologist about ongoing rash. There is discrepancy between the outcome reported in the structured field of system (recovered) for redness, swelling and soreness on her arm and the outcome reported in the source document (recovered with sequel); outcome for itchy rash in the structured field of system (recovering) while in source document it is reported as fatal.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Drug allergy (allergy to an unspecified beta blocker); Shingles (thrice)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe pain; Swelling at the site; Bruising; Shoulder pain; Not back to normal activities; Extreme fatigue; No strength; dizziness; Foggy head; Couldn't sleep; diarrhea; freezing; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 5th September 2019 01:00, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 5th September 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced diarrhea, feeling cold, fatigue, weakness, dizziness, foggy feeling in head and sleeplessness. On 5th September 2019 05:00, the patient experienced pain in arm, injection site swelling, injection site bruising, shoulder pain and activities of daily living impaired. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in arm, injection site swelling, injection site bruising, shoulder pain, sleeplessness and activities of daily living impaired were unknown and the outcome of the diarrhea, fatigue and weakness were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the feeling cold was recovered/resolved and the outcome of the dizziness and foggy feeling in head were recovering/resolving.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain in arm, injection site swelling, injection site bruising, diarrhea, feeling cold, fatigue, weakness, shoulder pain, dizziness, foggy feeling in head, sleeplessness and activities of daily living impaired to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix and had severe pain and swelling at the site with bruising. She noted these began about 5pm and her vaccine received on at 1pm. She noted these also extended up into her shoulder area.  She does believe the vaccine was given in the muscle but noted she was only 4 feet 11 inches and 95 pounds.     She noted she did report these events to her physician via a message portal but has not been seen by her physician, who noted these did not require follow up.The patient states also on Thursday evening she had diarrhea, that has improved but not resolved. She was freezing but that resolved after 24 hours. She had extreme fatigue and no strength, which has gotten better but not resolved. She noted she had to cancel a vacation. She also had dizziness and what foggy head that continue but have improved.She noted she couldn't sleep due to the pain in her arm and shoulder. She was not back to normal activity but feels she is about 80 percent better.    The patient noted the continued issues are occurring longer than expected and was concerned about the long term effects would be.   The patient was referred to her physician and shared the information from post marketing adverse event reports from the prescribing Information.That document was also being emailed to the consumer. The reporter consented to follow up.

Suspected vaccination failure; Pertussis; Pneumonia; Sepsis; Encephalopathy; Cough; Respiratory Failure; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a 48-year-old patient who received DTPa (Reduced antigen) (dTpa vaccine) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included hiv infection.   On an unknown date, the patient received dTpa vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, more than a week after receiving dTpa vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria death, hospitalization and GSK medically significant), pertussis (serious criteria death, hospitalization and GSK medically significant), pneumonia (serious criteria death, hospitalization and GSK medically significant), sepsis (serious criteria death, hospitalization and GSK medically significant), encephalopathy (serious criteria death, hospitalization and GSK medically significant), cough (serious criteria death and hospitalization) and respiratory failure (serious criteria death and GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, pertussis, pneumonia, sepsis, encephalopathy, cough and respiratory failure were fatal. The reported cause of death was pertussis, pneumonia, sepsis, encephalopathy, respiratory failure, vaccination failure and cough.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, pertussis, pneumonia, sepsis, encephalopathy, cough and respiratory failure to be related to dTpa vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure, sever pertussis infection, pneumonia, sepsis, encephalopathy in an adult patient of 48-year-old of unspecified gender who was vaccinated with unspecified tetanus, diphtheria & acellular pertussis (Tdap) vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to result section reported in this literature article. The patient was the part of the Enhanced Pertussis Surveillance (EPS) as part of the Emerging Infections Program Network. The aim of the study was to characterize severe pertussis cases, defined as those that require hospitalization, and compare hospitalized and non-hospitalized pertussis patients, identify risk factors for hospitalization, and describe the clinical course and underlying health conditions of hospitalized pertussis patients. The patient had a concurrent history of human immunodeficiency virus infection. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication. On unspecified date, at least 14 days prior to cough onset, the patient had received unspecified tetanus, diphtheria & acellular pertussis (Tdap) vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. [In this study, 15942 cases of pertussis were reported in the surveillance area, patients aged more or equal to 12 years were considered up to date if they had received Tdap. For this analysis, only documented vaccine doses administered at least 14 days prior to cough onset. Fewer hospitalized patients were up to date on pertussis-containing vaccines]. On unspecified date in between 1st January 2011 and 31st December 2015, at least 14 days after vaccination, the patient had the onset of cough and was admitted. The patient had an infection which was laboratory confirmed by culture or polymerase chain reaction (PCR). During the admission, the patient had diagnosed with the pneumonia, sepsis (not further described), and encephalopathy. The patient had the normal white blood cell (WBC) of 8.71 � 109/L. The patient had a respiratory failure that required mechanical ventilation. On an unspecified date, the hospitalized pertussis patients died from their infection. It was unknown, whether the autopsy was performed or not. [In this study, pertussis cases were classified according to the Council of State and Territorial Epidemiologists case definition. For hospitalized pertussis patients, defined as those admitted to an inpatient care facility, observation unit, or emergency department for more or equal to 24 hours as a result of pertussis infection. Among these cases, 15 427 occurred in patients treated as an outpatient and 515 occurred in patients who were hospitalized; 107 hospitalized patients required admission to the intensive care unit (ICU). Overall, the most common hospital admission diagnoses included cough, "pertussis", respiratory distress and or failure, bronchiolitis or bronchitis, and pneumonia. Among all hospitalized patients (515), the median length of time from onset to hospitalization was 11 days, ranging from 7 days in infants aged less than 2 months to 17 days in persons aged equal or more than 65 years. The median length of hospital stay was 3 (1.7-6.9 days) and ICU stay was 4 (2-9 days). The hospitalized patients received a macrolide antibiotic within 14 days of symptom onset, and had an infection that was laboratory confirmed by culture or polymerase chain reaction (PCR). Traditional pertussis clinical symptoms were more commonly reported in hospitalized patients symptoms included paroxysmal cough, post-tussive vomiting, whoop, cyanosis and apnea. Among patients who were tested during their hospitalization, 31 of 350 had a maximum white blood cell (WBC) count that surpassed 30 � 109/L (previously associated with an increased risk of pertussis-related infant deaths and 54 of 271 had a viral codetection (diagnosed through PCR, direct fluorescent antibody testing, culture, or rapid antigen tests). Overall, 127 of hospitalized pertussis patients developed pneumonia, developed new-onset seizures, and developed encephalopathy]. This case was considered as suspected vaccination failure as the vaccination schedule and time to onset were unknown. This case was considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure and death. The author commented, "Pertussis vaccination according to Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP) recommendations is not only effective at preventing disease but has also been shown to reduce the clinical severity of pertussis illness. Although high amounts of missing vaccination information in adolescents and adults precluded our ability to fully assess this association in older age groups, a recent publication suggested that adolescents and adults vaccinated with Tdap have reduced incidence of post-tussive vomiting, a marker of more clinically significant illness. Thus, although vaccinated persons may still remain at risk for pertussis infection, these data highlight the role that pertussis vaccination plays in the prevention of severe and potentially life-threating infections, suggesting an added benefits of vaccination that goes beyond disease prevention. We are unable to determine whether certain underlying conditions are risk factors for severe pertussis or, rather, whether persons with these conditions are hospitalized at greater rates due to a perception of increased risk for severe disease". The author concluded, "Our analysis shows that severe pertussis infections that require hospitalization are not limited to infants; certain risk factors, such as key underlying medical conditions, may predispose an individual to more severe infections. Continued monitoring of pertussis hospitalizations through enhanced surveillance systems such as EPS will help better define populations at increased risk of severe disease in order to appropriately target and prioritize current and future pertussis prevention and control strategies. Individuals at the extreme ends of life may be the most vulnerable to severe pertussis infections, though hospitalization was reported across all age groups. Continued monitoring of severe pertussis infections will be important to help guide prevention, control, and treatment options". Guillain Barre syndrome; Fisher syndrome; Limb weakness; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of guillain barre syndrome in a elderly patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, less than 2 months after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced guillain barre syndrome (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), fisher syndrome (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and weakness of limbs. On an unknown date, the outcome of the guillain barre syndrome, fisher syndrome and weakness of limbs were unknown.   The reporter considered the guillain barre syndrome, fisher syndrome and weakness of limbs to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of guillain-barre syndrome (GBS) and fisher syndrome (FS) in a patient aged more or equal to 65-year-old of unspecified gender who was vaccinated with unspecified 2015-2016 seasonal of influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to result section reported in this literature article The patient was the part of the near real-time surveillance for GBS claims after influenza vaccination of insurance fee-for-service (FFS) beneficiaries using the updating sequential probability ratio test throughout the influenza seasons and SCRI analyses at the end of the 2015-2016 and 2016-2017 seasons. The aimed of this study was to evaluate this signal by conducting chart reviews in the 2015-2016 season followed by self-controlled risk interval (SCRI) analyses of chart-confirmed and imputed cases. [In this study, for the 2015-2016 season SCRI analysis, they used chart-confirmed GBS cases. In 2016-2017 season they conducted SCRI analyses of the claims-based GBS cases and attributed GBS cases (based on the positive predictive value (PPV) of the GBS diagnoses obtained by chart reviews in the previous season). Of the 95 chart-confirmed GBS cases, they noted a history of antecedent respiratory or gastrointestinal illness within six weeks prior to onset of GBS symptoms in 47 charts, one of which had a documented history of Campylobacter jejuni. They identified claims for influenza vaccines and vaccines administered concomitantly (pneumococcal, hepatitis B, and tetanus toxoid-containing vaccines) using Healthcare Common Procedure Coding System (HCPCS) and Current Procedural Terminology (CPT) codes. They conducted influenza infection adjustment using ��high" and ��low" influenza weeks, which were assigned as such using weekly oseltamivir prescription rates as well as use rates of rapid influenza tests (RIT) followed by an oseltamivir prescription within the subsequent two days]. On unspecified date, the patient had received unspecified 2015-2016 seasonal influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. [In this study, the vaccine type (high dose (HD) and standard dose (SD)), and presence of concomitant vaccination. The only HD vaccine administered in both seasons was the inactivated trivalent high dose vaccine (60 mg hemagglutinin per strain). The SD group included inactivated trivalent and quadrivalent (15 mg hemagglutinin per strain) vaccines A total of 13,366,005 insurance FFS influenza-vaccinated beneficiaries were observed for our SCRI analyses. Of these, 6,936,021 received the HD vaccine, 6,218,036 received the SD vaccines, and the remaining received other influenza vaccines (recombinant, intradermal, and cell-culture based) or only had general influenza vaccine codes but no specific codes for a vaccine type.]. On unspecified date between 2015 and 2016, in between the 1 and 42 days risk window, the patient had diagnosed with the guillain-barre syndrome (GBS) and fisher syndrome (FS) as per the Brighton case definition. [In this study, the primary and secondary risk windows were 1-42 and 8-21 days post-vaccination respectively. They defined exposure as a beneficiary's first influenza vaccination during the season, and outcome as the first occurrence of GBS in the inpatient setting during the post-vaccination window of interest. They used Brighton Collaboration's case definitions for GBS and Fisher Syndrome (FS), a variant of GBS, to classify these cases and considered cases classified as Brighton Level 1, 2, or 3 as ��chart-confirmed" GBS cases. For the 2015-2016 season, our claims-based near real-time surveillance using the Updating Sequential Probability Ratio Test (USPRT) first revealed a GBS signal in week 16 of surveillance (as of 29th November 2015) among HD vaccines aged more or equal than 65 years as a risk of GBS in the 0 to 42 day window and as a risk of GBS in the 7 to 21 day window. Of note, in the 2015-2016 season, the 0 to 42 day and 7 to 21 day risk windows were used for near real-time surveillance; however, they changed the risk windows to 1 to 42 and 8 to 21 days post-vaccination for the SCRI analyses and near real-time surveillance for subsequent seasons to better align with the existing literature. In the subsequent weeks they observed a GBS signal in week 26 (as of February 2, 2016) for all beneficiaries vaccinated with all seasonal vaccines as a risk of GBS cases in the 0 to 42 day window. The demographic characteristics of the influenza-vaccinated beneficiaries and the GBS cases in the 2 risk windows. They obtained 133 charts. They found 158 claims-based GBS cases in the 84 days post-vaccination that met our study criteria. All cases except one were identified with the ICD-10 code. Three cases were observed after the January 22, 2016 cut-off, and they requested medical charts for the remaining 155 cases. They obtained 133charts. Of these, they confirmed 95 by chart review as GBS cases. Our analysis showed a PPV of an inpatient diagnosis of GBS in ICD-10. By chart abstraction they found that seven cases identified as GBS by claims had FS noted in the charts. However, none of these seven cases met the criteria for FS and four did not meet the criteria for GBS. Of the remaining three cases, they excluded one due to the subject being noted as less than 65 years of age. They included the remaining two cases in the SCRI analysis. Both cases occurred in the 1 to 42 day risk window; one also occurred in the 8 to 21 day window. Even though these two remaining cases were diagnosed by the physicians as FS, they both had limb weakness in addition to FS features and were thus classified as GBS.].  This case has been considered as serious due to the hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not provided. The authors commented, "Our SCRI results did not show an excess GBS risk in the 1-42 day risk window either in the overall analysis or in any of the sub-analyses by vaccine type. For the secondary 8-21 day risk window, we found a statistically significant increased GBS for all seasonal vaccines. Our chart-confirmed analysis showed that the attributable risk in the secondary (8-21 day) risk window for all seasonal vaccines was slightly less than one excess GBS case per million vaccines, and that for the HD vaccine was slightly less than two excess cases of GBS per million vaccines. These findings are consistent with the risks noted on the package insert of influenza vaccines distributed in specific country. Our secondary analysis finding of a higher GBS risk among males and individuals aged more or equal to 75 years who received seasonal vaccines is consistent with existing literature. We considered the possibility that the difference may be related to egg-based versus recombinant influenza vaccine, which was included in our SD vaccine group". The author concluded, "we did not find an excess GBS risk in our primary analysis. The excess risk in some of our secondary analyses was close to what was expected; however, the slightly elevated GBS risk after all seasonal and HD vaccines, but not after standard dose vaccines is hypothesis-generating. This difference between HD and SD vaccines may be related to vaccine factors such as the amount of antigen or the antigen strains in various seasons or related to host factors. The risk of GBS after influenza disease is estimated to be much greater than the potential risk following influenza vaccine, ranging from four to almost 16 times higher, and the benefits of influenza vaccines in preventing morbidity and mortality heavily outweigh this risk. Influenza vaccines continue to be our best defense against influenza disease and the morbidity and mortality associated with it." This is 1 of the 4 valid cases reported in this literature article.

Concomitant therapies included eltrombopag olamine (PROMACTA), gabapentin  and pantoprazole (indications not reported).     "Sometime on 2016", the pt was vaccinated with a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), for singles, in her arm (unspecified) (route, lot/batch # and expiration date were not reported).     It was reported that the pt experienced chronic inflammatory demylenating polyneuropathy (chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy), Idiopathic Thrombocytopenic Purpurn (ITP) (immune thrombocytopenic purpura), and gastric bleed (gastric haemorrhage) after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) in 2016. Subsequently, the pt was hospitalized for about two weeks (unspecified date in 2016). The pt had a routine blood work on an unknown date, results not reported. She received immunoglobulin infusion as treatment on an unknown date.   The outcome of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy, gastric haemorrhage and immune thrombocytopenic purpura was reported as not resolved.  The causality assessment between chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy, gastric haemorrhage and immune thrombocytopenic purpura with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was not reported.   The reporter considered chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy, gastric haemorrhage and immune thrombocytopenic purpura as disabling and life threatening, however, it was also reported that no intervention was need to prevent serious criteria.   Upon internal review, chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy, gastric haemorrhage and immune thrombocytopenic purpura were determined to be medically significant events.

On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site leaking, injection site pain and injection site rash were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the accidental underdose was not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the wrong technique in device usage process was unknown. SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 1/2 after receiving the shots my daughter started to complain that she was experiencing traveling numbness.  First her arm, then her leg. A doctor friend said it was somewhat normal and that she should lay down for a bit.  After about another hour she started to feel somewhat normal again.  She did complain of her hand bothering her several times on several different days.  Two months later she was at the ER 3 times for seizures and then hospitalized for 2 weeks.  Her diagnoses was anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis.  She is still in recovery.  The doctors do not know why or how the encephalitis occurred.  several of the symptoms mimicked what occurred after the vaccines were given but on a much more intense scale.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Gardasil used for condyloma accuminata; This literature marketed report was received from the authors of a published literature article, titled as stated below, and refers to a 9-year-old male patient. On an unreported date, the previously healthy boy presented to dermatology with his mother for a lesion on his penis with a recent history of itching and bleeding. On exam, there was a 6x7 mm brown papule on the shaft of his penis surrounded by smaller papules. The area was biopsied and pathology reported condyloma accuminata positive for Human Papillomavirus (HPV) 6 and 11, and negative for HPV 16 and 18. Upon further questioning, the patient's mother reported that she was serum positive for HPV; however, she and the patient's siblings were not clinically affected. The mother was educated on routes of transmission of HPV and denied any knowledge of prior sexual abuse. Laboratory Sexually Transmitted Infection (STI) studies were ordered and the patient was returned to primary care for further care and quadrivalent human papillomavirus (types 6,11,16,18) recomb. vaccine (GARDASIL) vaccination.   A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.
CUR_ILL: Condyloma accuminata recurrent; Human papilloma virus serology test positive (mother)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I took ibuprofen 15 minutes after the vaccine to minimize any reaction. 4 hours later my eyes started to feel like I had dirt under the eyelids. I also started to get a headache. Shortly thereafter I started to get an irritated throat and swelling at the back of my tongue. Next my sinus became so swollen that I couldn't breathe through my nose and my frontal sinuses became swollen as well. Next my lungs became involved and I started to have asthma symptoms.  I called the emergency triage nurse line for my clinic and as told to take more ibuprofen, an antihistamine and use my albuterol. If symptoms continued to get worse, I was to go to the ER. about 4-5 hours after the symptoms started, they stabilized and I was able to go to sleep. I wolk up this morning with aching muscles a headache ringing ears and a slightly swollen throat. I'm taking tylenol and ibuprofen to control the symptoms.  This is the first time I've ever reacted tot e flu vaccine. This is also the first high dose vaccine I've had. I do get serioius asthma symptoms with a cold or flu.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Polycystic kidney; Anhydramnios (and oligohydramnios); (Anhydramnios and) oligohydramnios; Fetal exposure during pregnancy; Preterm birth; Infant passed away 10 minutes shy of being 24 hours old; This is an observational serious study case, initially received from other health professional on 20-Sep-2019, concerning a 24-hour-old female neonate subject. The mother was a 30-year-old subject (Ethnicity: Not reported) of body weight: 197 lbs, height: 65 inches and body mass index (BMI): 32.8, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy.  The mother's historical condition included neurofibromatosis. The mother's current conditions included yeast, HSV 2, anxiety and migraines. Concomitant medication included prenatal vitamins (unspecified vitamins), terconasole and Zoloft (sertraline hydrochloride).  The subject's mother obstetrical history noted that the mother had five previous pregnancies with 2 full term live birth, 2 preterm live birth and 1 elective abortion. The subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The mother did not have a prior history of use of illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject's mother had a prior history of using alcohol (reported as 2 or less). The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 25-Jun-2018 and the pregnancy was singleton. The estimated delivery date (EDD) and the corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were 01-Apr-2019.  On 21-Aug-2018, 04-Sep-2018 and 02-Oct-2018, the subject's mother underwent Ultrasound scan and no major congenital malformation noted.  On 16-Oct-2018, at gestation age of 16 weeks, the subject's mother was administered Flucelvax QIVc [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 252664, dose, expiration date, route of administration, and anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Fetal exposure during pregnancy'] for influenza immunisation.  On 18-Oct-2018, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound scan and quad screen and no major congenital malformation noted.  On 09-Jan-2019, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound scan and non stress test and polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  On 22-Jan-2019, the subject's mother underwent non stress test and polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  On 23-Jan-2019, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound scan and polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  On 25-Jan-2019, the subject's mother underwent non stress test and polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  On 29-Jan-2019, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound scan and polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  On 07-Feb-2019, the subject's mother underwent genetic testing and no major congenital malformation noted. Ultrasound scan was performed on the same day and the results showed polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  On 13-Feb-2019, the subject's mother underwent non stress test and polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  On 14-Feb-2019, 21-Feb-2019 and 01-Mar-2019, the subject's mother underwent biophysical profile and polycystic kidneys, oligohydramnios and anhydramnios noted.  At gestational age of 36.3 weeks, the mother delivered live birth, female neonate by Caesarean section (explicitly coded as �Premature baby'). The neonate's birth weight was 2780 g, head circumference and length were not reported. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 1 at one minute, 3 at five minutes and 5 at ten minutes.  Major congenital malformations (MCM) identified at birth were oligohydramnios, anhydramnios and polycystic kidneys. Other factors contributing to the MCM were unknown. As reported: "Baby passed away 10 minutes shy of being 24 hours old."(outcome: fatal). Information regarding autopsy was not reported.  This case is linked to 201904743, corresponding mother case. The subject's past medical history included varicose veins ligation. Concurrent medical conditions included portal hypertension (etiology was biliary atresia), biliary atresia and varicosity. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of fever and abdominal pain in a 9-year-old patient of unspecified gender who was vaccinated with unspecified Haemophilus influenzae type B, unspecified meningococcal vaccines and unspecified pneumococcal vaccine (PCV13 followed in 1 month by PPSV23 when feasible) (manufacturer unknown for all) for prophylaxis.  The patient was a part of cohort study that aimed to determine whether Partial Splenic Embolization (PSE) was safe and effective in the pediatric population.  The study was a retrospective review of a single-center experience for all patients ages 0 to 21 who underwent PSE for the management of portal hypertension (PHTN) between January 2010 and August 2017. The study presented the experience with the use of this modality in different pediatric populations with PHTN to better understand the rationale for safe and appropriate application of this treatment. [In this study, [In this study, recommended PSE to patients with bleeding tendencies that were not optimal candidates for an open surgical shunt or repeated endoscopies. This includes the following patient populations: Patients with baseline compromised respiratory function (ie, cystic fibrosis [CF]). 2. Patients with significant synthetic dysfunction that may progress to liver failure after shunting. 3. Patients with early signs of encephalopathy that could potentially worsen with increased portal systemic shunting. 4. Patients with abnormal right heart function that could develop cardiac decompensation or shunt failure. 5. Patients deemed to be marginal candidates for repeated anesthesia. 6. Patients with splenic vein thrombosis. 7. Patients with characteristics predicting poor wound healing or other surgical complications. 8. Patients with unfavorable anatomy, increased transhepatic resistance, or elevated right heart pressures to permit mesoportal shunting (Rex shunt)]. The patient had thrombocytopenia and/or recurrent variceal bleeding. The patient had portal hypertension, whose etiology was biliary atresia (BA), and the patient also noted to have evidence of varices before PSE which required endoscopic intervention. For this, the patient underwent endoscopic variceal ligation (EVL) before PSE. The patient had significant splenomegaly before PSE. The decision to proceed with PSE was determined by the primary hepatologist and surgeon after careful discussion with both patient and family members regarding alternative approaches. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided.   On an unspecified date, at least 2 weeks before PSE, the patient received unspecified Haemophilus influenzae type B, unspecified meningococcal vaccines and unspecified pneumococcal vaccine (PCV13 followed in 1 month by PPSV23 when feasible) (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown, batch number not provided for all), in order to reduce the risk of future infection by encapsulated organisms, should the procedure lead to a complication necessitating total splenectomy. The age of vaccination was not provided. It was reported that the patient received broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotic prophylaxis, typically with piperacillin/tazobactam, before the procedure to prevent infection of infarcted splenic tissue. This was continued for 5 to 7 days. On an unknown date, before PSE, the patient's platelet count was noted at 35�10E9/L (normal range not provided).   On an unspecified date between January 2010 and August 2017, at least 2 weeks after vaccination, the patient underwent PSE by interventional radiology under general anesthesia via percutaneous femoral artery approach under sterile conditions utilizing guidelines based on the Spigos technique to minimize complications. At the time of PSE, the patient was not actively bleeding. Diagnostic angiographies of the celiac axis and splenic arteries were obtained to determine the target splenic arterial branches, to identify accessory branches to other tissues from the splenic artery and to determine baseline splenic volume. Abdominal sonograms with doppler analysis of hepatic and splenic vessels were performed post procedure to assess vessel patency and the degree of intra-abdominal-free fluid. Arteriograms of partial splenic embolization (PSE), pre-embolization with capillary blush demonstrated splenomegaly and post-embolization with capillary blush revealed multiple defects before and after esophageal varices.   Information regarding patient's blood transfusions was not available. The patient was admitted to hospital after PSE for further observation and management. [In this study, patients received patient-controlled analgesia for pain control and to prevent splinting and associated pulmonary complications such as atelectasis and pneumonia]. The patient did not develop infection with encapsulated organisms. Post-PSE, the patient's platelet count was 154�10E9/L. the antibiotics were converted to an oral regimen before hospital discharge. [In this study, criteria for hospital discharge included adequate control of abdominal pain with oral medications, adequate oral intake/hydration, and absence of post procedure infection. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) showed splenomegaly and postembolization with necrotic areas surrounding the spleen. Three patients demonstrated complete resolution of varices. An additional 7 patients were noted to have a decrease in variceal grade].  On an unknown date, the patient was discharged fulfilling the criteria for hospital discharge that included (adequate control of abdominal pain with oral medications), adequate oral intake/hydration, and absence of post procedure infection. The patient was followed-up in the outpatient hepatology clinic. Hematologic indices including white blood cell (WBC) and platelet counts were monitored. Imaging was repeated as indicated. The patient developed fever and abdominal pain and the patient was re-hospitalized. [In this study, 7 patients required readmission after initial discharge 2 of these patients were discharged only 1 day after PSE and returned the following day with fevers and abdominal pain with an unremarkable diagnostic evaluation].  Surveillance endoscopy was also performed 3 months after PSE to evaluate for persistent varices. Splenic function appeared to be preserved during years of follow-up in patient without increased incidence of infection.  This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization.  The outcome of the event was not reported.  The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of fever and abdominal pain and Unspecified Haemophilus influenza type B vaccine, unspecified meningococcal vaccine and unspecified pneumococcal (PCV13 followed by PPSV23) vaccine. The author stated "The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends immunoprophylaxis against Streptococcus pneumoniae, H influenzae and Neisseria meningitidis in all splenectomized patients. Complications of PHTN such as hypersplenism, variceal hemorrhage, and ascites can lead to significant morbidity and mortality in children. Surgical interventions include shunting or splenectomy; however, overwhelming sepsis postsplenectomy is a pressing concern. PSE addresses portal hypertension regardless of etiology as definitive therapy. Most adverse effects following PSE are expected and can be managed conservatively. In our cohort we commonly observed fever, abdominal pain, and leukocytosis without evidence of infection. Pain was effectively controlled with intravenous and oral analgesics. Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs were avoided to minimize hemorrhage. In our experience, prophylactic antibiotics and limiting splenic reduction to no greater than 70% have avoided serious morbidity and mortality. In particular, there was no significant difference in the preprocedure platelet count between patients with and without recurrent thrombocytopenia. After PSE we noted a significant increase in platelets but to a lesser degree in patients who had recurrent hypersplenism. In our patients with esophageal varices, the combination of endoscopic ligation and PSE has been successful in controlling the progression of varices and decreasing the incidence of variceal hemorrhage."  The author concluded "our study supports that PSE is a safe, effective, semi-invasive alternative to splenectomy in pediatric patients with PHTN. The combination of EVL and PSE is effective treatment for esophageal and gastric varices (not amenable to simple band ligation). Reduced splenic volume and splenic venous return effectively decreased portal flow and pressure. PSE can be successfully performed in pre- and post-transplant transplant patients, and select cirrhotic and noncirrhotic pediatric patients. PSE appears to preserve functional spleen mass and avoids postprocedure accelerated liver disease or encephalopathy. In contrast to shunting, PSE can be effective even in the setting of elevated right-sided heart pressures. Further multicenter collaborative studies with larger and varied patient populations will need to be performed to substantiate our approach and better define patient populations that would benefit most from PSE, sequential PSE or combined interventions. Liver transplantation remains the ideal intervention for anyone with significant decompensated PHTN or advanced hepatic dysfunction".  This is 1 of the 9 valid cases reported in this article. I was given the shot at approximately 8:30 am. I left the clinic and was driving home. At approximately 8:45 am, I had to pull over because I felt very drowsy. As soon as I pulled over, I got very tingly and blacked out. I?m unsure how long I was unconscious. I woke up and I decided to try to make it home. I parked in the parking lot at my apartment building where I blacked out again, this time having severe shakes. I managed to take a Zofran as I felt like I was going to vomit. I called 911 because I kept falling in and out of unconsciousness. I managed to tell the dispatcher where I was at and what car I was in, but again, I fell unconscious. I woke up to paramedics banging on my car windows because my car door was locked. I unlocked it before starting to pass out again. My blood sugar and blood pressure was taken. My blood sugar was 96, and I cannot remember my blood pressure. I had a weak pulse so they had to use a stethoscope to take my pulse. I do not remember what my pulse was either. I cannot afford a hospital visit so I asked the paramedics to just take my to my bedroom, and help me lie down. I have been in bed since. During these black out events, I was tingling all over my body, I could hear - but it sounded like I was underwater, I had very dry mouth and I was very sick to my stomach. As of right now, it?s been 7 hours since receiving the vaccine and I have a strong headache, and feel generally unwell and lethargic. I am 26 weeks pregnant with an expected due date of December 26th, 2019. I have not noticed any issues with my baby. He is moving around normally.
LAB_DATA: Blood sugar test: 96  Blood pressure and heart rate were taken but I cannot remember the results.

The Patient had two previous doses in unspecified date in 2007 or 2008 and on an unspecified date in 2013 or 2014 with only minor pain and low grade fever.; The Patient had two previous doses in unspecified date in 2007 or 2008 and on an unspecified date in 2013 or 2014 with only minor pain and low grade fever.; she could not lift her left arm / the left arm felt weak / "no strength in that arm"; around 2 pm developed increasing pain; fever of 100 �F; general malaise; "She had a reaction to the PNEUMOVAX 23 shot"; she could not lift her left arm / the left arm felt weak / "no strength in that arm"; pain with lifting her arm-needed to use the right arm to hold the left arm / The pain is reported as extreme.; finger numbness; This spontaneous report was received from a 56-year-old female patient referring to herself.  The patient's concurrent conditions included asthma, drug hypersensitivity and food allergy. The patient's medical history included herpes zoster. Previous drug reactions/allergies included allergy to ibuprofen, soy and peanuts. Concomitant therapies included fluticasone furoate (+) vilanterol trifenatate (BREO), beclomethasone dipropionate (QNASL), olopatadine hydrochloride (PATANASE), albuterol sulfate (PROAIR) and vitamins (unspecified).  On unspecified dates in 2007 (reported as 2007 or 2008) and in 2013 (reported as 2013 or 2014), the patient was vaccinated with the first and second dose of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23), respectively; (strength, dose, frequency, lot # and expiration date were not reported) intramuscularly. On unspecified dates after those vaccinations, she experienced minor pain and low-grade fever. On 18-SEP-2019 in the morning, the patient was vaccinated with a third dose of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) (strength, dose, frequency, lot # and expiration date were not reported) in the left arm, intramuscularly, for prophylaxis (indication reported as asthma).  On the same date, the patient went to work and around 14:00, she developed a reaction to the pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) shot (vaccination complication), which included increasing pain (injection site pain) and finger numbness in the left hand (hypoaesthesia). She left work early and while changing, she found that she could not lift her left arm, her arm felt weak and without strength (injected limb mobility decreased and muscular weakness). Then, she contacted the physician and spoke with the Nurse Manager, who sent her to the minor emergency clinic. At the emergency clinic, she reported fever of 100 Farenheit degrees (F) (pyrexia), extreme pain with lifting her arm (she needed to use the right arm to hold the left arm) (pain in extremity) and general malaise (malaise). As treatment for the events, she was placed on acetaminophen (TYLENOL) and ice. It was reported that there were no flair-up of asthma symptoms, the patient was not hospitalized and there were no laboratories/studies performed yet. The outcome for the events of minor pain and low-grade fever was not reported. At the reporting time, the patient was not recovered from vaccination complication, injection site pain, hypoaesthesia, injected limb mobility decreased, muscular weakness, pyrexia (onset date: 18-SEP-2019), pain in extremity and malaise.   Relatedness between all the events and pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was not provided.
OTHER_MEDS: BREO; QNASL; PATANASE; PROAIR (albuterol sulfate); vitamins (unspecified)

Suspected vaccination failure; influenza A(H3N2); acute respiratory illness; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a adult patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), h3n2 influenza (serious criteria hospitalization) and respiratory disorder (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, h3n2 influenza and respiratory disorder were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, h3n2 influenza and respiratory disorder to be related to Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a patient aged between 22 and 63 years of unspecified gender, who was vaccinated with unspecified quadrivalent influenza vaccine (manufacturer GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis.   The patient was a part of the study that aimed was to compare antibody titers against both circulating influenza A (H3N2) strains and egg-adapted influenza A (H3N2) strains in acute specimens from individuals with and those without influenza virus infection in the 2017-2018 season. During the severe 2017-2018 influenza season, a study of the effectiveness of influenza vaccine among inpatients with acute respiratory illness as part of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) sponsored Hospitalized Adult Influenza Vaccine Effectiveness Network (HAIVEN) was performed. No information on patient's medical history, family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On unspecified date, during 2017-2018 influenza season, the patient received unspecified quadrivalent influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not provided. [In this study, there were 18 individuals who had been vaccinated, and the specific influenza vaccine they received could be confirmed for 15. All 15 individuals with confirmed vaccine product information received vaccines containing inactivated egg grown virus; 10 received quadrivalent standard dose vaccines (9 vaccines were produced by GlaxoSmithKline, and 1 was produced by Seqirus), 3 received trivalent high dose vaccines (produced by Sanofi Pasteur), 1 received trivalent adjuvanted vaccine (produced by Seqirus), and 1 received trivalent unadjuvanted vaccine (produced by Seqirus)]. On an unspecified date, during 2017-2018 influenza season, between 27 November 2017 and 31 January 2018, an unknown period after the vaccination, the patient developed acute respiratory illness and subsequently hospitalized. The patient was enrolled less than or equal to 10 days after illness onset during active influenza virus circulation. The patient's throat and nasal swab specimens were collected shortly for influenza virus identification by reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) analysis. The patient was found influenza A(H3N2) Positive The patient's antibody titers were also measured with neuraminidase-inhibition (NAI) and Microneutralization (MN) assays was determined. The microneutralization (MN) egg propagated A/HongKong/4801/2014 (HK-egg) antibody titer was found 20, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/HongKong/4801/2014 (HK) antibody titer was found 20, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Washington/16/2017 (WA) antibody titer was found 10, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Singapore/Infimh-16-0019/2016 (SG) antibody titer was 10, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Maryland/53/2017 (MD) antibody titer was found 10, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Wisconsin/327/2017 (WI) antibody titer was found 10, neuraminidase-inhibition (NAI) MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/HongKong/4801/2014 (HK) antibody titer was found 80 and NAI MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Singapore/Infimh-16-0019/2016 (SG) antibody titer was found 160 in patient. The genetic characterization of Influenza A(H3N2) virus strains circulating in patient sample was also determined (results not provided). This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being the time to onset was unknown. This case has been considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure and hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not reported. The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of influenza A (H3N2) infection and unspecified Quadrivalent influenza vaccine. However, the authors stated, "This analysis of specimens from adults hospitalized with influenza A(H3N2) virus infection during the 2017-2018 influenza season demonstrated an antibody response specific to egg-adapted strains that was significantly higher among vaccinated individuals. In our study sample, this suggests that the antibody responses to vaccination in this population are highly specific to the egg-adapted strain, with little cross-reactivity to the circulating virus. Additionally, antibody titers against cell grown influenza A/HongKong/4801/2014(H3N2) virus were similar to those in unvaccinated individuals. In this study sample, this suggests that the antibody responses to vaccination in this population are highly specific to the egg adapted strain, with little cross-reactivity to the circulating virus. In this study, antibody against the neuraminidase of influenza A/HongKong/4801/2014 virus and influenza A/Singapore/INFIMH-16-0019/2016 virus was not associated with protection against infection. Although neuraminidase content was not standardized in influenza vaccines, it was observed that anti neuraminidase antibody titers were higher among vaccinated individuals, suggesting that some of the existing anti neuraminidase antibody in this population resulted from vaccination. The serum specimens in this study were collected at a single time point early during acute illness." The authors concluded, "The conclusions were limited by the inclusion of a small number of specimens from a single hospital. Because the severity of the 2017-2018 epidemic was evident early in the season, it was prioritized rapid serologic testing of the specimens that were available to date during the first half of the season. These 2 factors may limit the broad generalizability of the results; however, the influenza viruses that circulated locally overall and during the analysis period were similar to those that predominated nationwide during the same season. The small sample size also precluded the ability to perform additional subanalyses, to assess whether results might vary within specific age groups or by history of prior vaccination. In one sense, the 2017-2018 influenza vaccine appears to have worked as intended: vaccinated individuals had high antibody titers against the influenza virus strain included in the vaccine. The study adds to the evidence that egg adaptations in the 2017-2018 influenza vaccine strain elicited antibodies to epitopes not conserved in circulating strains. The degree to which this contributed to the marked severity of the 2017- 2018 season remains to be determined. Several vaccine products have been introduced into the vaccine market that are produced in cells and do not have the same emergent egg adaptations seen in recent influenza A(H3N2) vaccine strains. At this time, evidence for the effectiveness of these vaccines relative to those produced in eggs is limited because few head to head trials have been performed. Early data suggest that cell based vaccines have somewhat improved protection in clinical trials and in the community. Unfortunately, these vaccines are still dependent on selecting viruses that are close antigenic matches to those that will circulate and are subject to the limitations of annual strain selection time lines. This underscores the need for the development of the next generation of influenza vaccines that provide better, broader, and longer lasting protection." This is 1 of the 4 valid cases reported in the same literature article. The patient's medical history not reported.  It was an actual medication error case due to vaccine administered at inappropriate site and Extra dose administered. It was unknown whether the patient experienced any adverse event post vaccination. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shortly after receiving her flu shot (~within 5 minutes of receiving it), a patient came back and reported that she was feeling flushed and asked if she appeared red.  She seemed normal in appearance, but then she started complaining of severe lower back pain.  At this point, I asked her if she would like us to call an ambulance to which she responded, "yes."  I asked my technician to call 911, while I continued to assess the patient. I went out of the pharmacy to see if I could aid the patient to a chair in the nearby waiting area (5 steps away), but she complained her back was in too much pain, and she remained hunched over a shopping cart for support. Patient did not report difficulty breathing, dizziness, or nausea. I grabbed a chair and put it directly behind the patient so that she could sit down.  After sitting, patient reported the pain in her back moved to her legs.  And after a few more minutes of waiting, patient began to report she was experiencing chest pain.  Shortly after this, the paramedics arrived and took the patient to the hospital.
HISTORY: Hypertension; AFib; Localization-related idiopathic epilepsy and epileptic syndromes with seizures of localized onset, not intractable, without status epiepticus;

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I have been having upper right arm pain for a while now, this has happened in the past, I cannot remember the exact year, but it was about  10 years ago, maybe. That pain lasted about 6 months and just went away on it's own. At the time I had mentioned it to my PCP but she said that she had never heard of arm pain after so many months  as a reaction to a flu shot. At that time, I could not even lift my arm to dress myself, it was very painful but like I said it went away. This time, I felt it again and thought oh no, before when I would tell people of my reaction to it before they looked at me like I was weird. This time I googled it and found that there is such a thing now.  This is where I got the information to this site. The deltoid muscle can get pinched and can be very painful. I knew I was not crazy. I am having pain now everyday, as the day goes on my arm just gets painful, there are times when I have to literally lift my arm up with my other arm to move it while I'm in bed. I have muscle relaxers that I was given by my PCP for my lower back pain that I use when the pain is so bad on my arm  and then I can get some sleep.  I have read articles on it and have found that a MRI can be helpful in determining how bad it is. I have not gone to my Dr yet regarding this and it's just because I do not want to take the time to do all the visits that will probably be involved and also the cost of the MRI. I have medical insurance but I'm sure there will be a deductible that I have to meet.
LAB_DATA: I have not had any done yet.  But I will be scheduling soon to see my PCP.
OTHER_MEDS: Paroxetine HCL 20 mg tablet Larissa- 28 tablet Bupropin HCL XL 300 mg Pantoprazole SOD DR 40 mg Cyclobenzaprine 10 MG prn
PRIOR_VAX: A flu shot many years ago.

Concurrent medical conditions included portal hypertension (whose etiology was portal vein thrombosis), portal vein thrombosis (PVT) and varicosity. This case corresponds to supplemental table 1 (patient 13) reported in this literature article.  The patient was a youngest patient of a cohort study that aimed to determine whether Partial Splenic Embolization (PSE) was safe and effective in the pediatric population.  The study was a retrospective review of a single-center experience for all patients ages 0 to 21 who underwent PSE for the management of portal hypertension (PHTN) between January 2010 and August 2017 at New York. The study presented the experience with the use of this modality in different pediatric populations with PHTN to better understand the rationale for safe and appropriate application of this treatment. [In this study, [In this study, recommended PSE to patients with bleeding tendencies that were not optimal candidates for an open surgical shunt or repeated endoscopies. This includes the following patient populations: Patients with baseline compromised respiratory function (ie, cystic fibrosis [CF]). 2. Patients with significant synthetic dysfunction that may progress to liver failure after shunting. 3. Patients with early signs of encephalopathy that could potentially worsen with increased portal systemic shunting. 4. Patients with abnormal right heart function that could develop cardiac decompensation or shunt failure. 5. Patients deemed to be marginal candidates for repeated anesthesia. 6. Patients with splenic vein thrombosis. 7. Patients with characteristics predicting poor wound healing or other surgical complications. 8. Patients with unfavorable anatomy, increased transhepatic resistance, or elevated right heart pressures to permit mesoportal shunting (Rex shunt)]. The patient had thrombocytopenia and/or recurrent variceal bleeding. The patient had portal hypertension, whose etiology was portal vein thrombosis (PVT)(no underlying liver disease) and the patient had a bleeding. The patient also had variceal hemorrhage and the patient also noted to have varices before PSE. For the management of variceal hemorrhage, the patient underwent sclerotherapy rather than endoscopic variceal ligation before PSE. The patient had significant splenomegaly before PSE. The decision to proceed with PSE was determined by the primary hepatologist and surgeon after careful discussion with both patient and family members regarding alternative approaches. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided.   On an unspecified date, at least 2 weeks before PSE, the patient received unspecified Haemophilus influenzae type B, unspecified meningococcal vaccines and unspecified pneumococcal vaccine (PCV13 followed in 1 month by PPSV23 when feasible) (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown, batch number not provided for all), in order to reduce the risk of future infection by encapsulated organisms, should the procedure lead to a complication necessitating total splenectomy. The age of vaccination was not provided. It was reported that the patient received broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotic prophylaxis, typically with piperacillin/tazobactam, before the procedure to prevent infection of infarcted splenic tissue. This was continued for 5 to 7 days. On an unknown date, before PSE, the patient's platelet count was noted at 15�10E9/L (normal range not provided).   On an unspecified date between January 2010 and August 2017, at least 2 weeks after vaccination, the patient underwent PSE by interventional radiology under general anesthesia via percutaneous femoral artery approach under sterile conditions utilizing guidelines based on the Spigos technique to minimize complications. At the time of PSE, the patient was not actively bleeding. Diagnostic angiographies of the celiac axis and splenic arteries were obtained to determine the target splenic arterial branches, to identify accessory branches to other tissues from the splenic artery and to determine baseline splenic volume. Abdominal sonograms with doppler analysis of hepatic and splenic vessels were performed post procedure to assess vessel patency and the degree of intra-abdominal-free fluid. Arteriograms of partial splenic embolization (PSE), pre-embolization with capillary blush demonstrated splenomegaly and post-embolization with capillary blush revealed multiple defects before and after esophageal varices.   Information regarding patient's blood transfusions was not available. The patient was admitted to hospital after PSE for further observation and management. [In this study, patients received patient-controlled analgesia for pain control and to prevent splinting and associated pulmonary complications such as atelectasis and pneumonia]. The patient was noted to have recurrent variceal hemorrhage after PSE and started bleeding and subsequently underwent EVL intervention. The patient did not develop infection with encapsulated organisms. Post-PSE, the patient's platelet count was 188�10E9/L. The antibiotics were converted to an oral regimen before hospital discharge. [In this study, criteria for hospital discharge included adequate control of abdominal pain with oral medications, adequate oral intake/hydration, and absence of post procedure infection. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) showed splenomegaly and postembolization with necrotic areas surrounding the spleen. Three patients demonstrated complete resolution of varices. An additional 7 patients were noted to have a decrease in variceal grade].  On an unknown date, the patient was discharged fulfilling the criteria for hospital discharge that included (adequate control of abdominal pain with oral medications), adequate oral intake/hydration, and absence of post procedure infection. The patient was not re-hospitalized. The patient was followed-up in the outpatient hepatology clinic. Hematologic indices including white blood cell (WBC) and platelet counts were monitored. Imaging was repeated as indicated. Surveillance endoscopy was also performed 3 months after PSE to evaluate for persistent varices. Additionally, the patient underwent surgical shunt after post PSE and reason of surgical shunt was due to recurrent variceal hemorrhage. The time range from PSE to surgical shunt was 7.56 -27.72 months. Splenic function appeared to be preserved during years of follow-up in patient without increased incidence of infection.  This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization.   The outcome of the event was not reported.  The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of recurrent variceal hemorrhage and Unspecified Haemophilus influenza type B vaccine, unspecified meningococcal vaccine and unspecified pneumococcal (PCV13 followed by PPSV23) vaccine. The author stated "The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends immunoprophylaxis against Streptococcus pneumoniae, H influenzae and Neisseria meningitidis in all splenectomized patients. Complications of PHTN such as hypersplenism, variceal hemorrhage, and ascites can lead to significant morbidity and mortality in children. Surgical interventions include shunting or splenectomy; however, overwhelming sepsis postsplenectomy is a pressing concern. PSE addresses portal hypertension regardless of etiology as definitive therapy. Most adverse effects following PSE are expected and can be managed conservatively. In our cohort we commonly observed fever, abdominal pain, and leukocytosis without evidence of infection. Pain was effectively controlled with intravenous and oral analgesics. Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs were avoided to minimize hemorrhage. In our experience, prophylactic antibiotics and limiting splenic reduction to no greater than 70% have avoided serious morbidity and mortality. In particular, there was no significant difference in the preprocedure platelet count between patients with and without recurrent thrombocytopenia. After PSE we noted a significant increase in platelets but to a lesser degree in patients who had recurrent hypersplenism. In our patients with esophageal varices, the combination of endoscopic ligation and PSE has been successful in controlling the progression of varices and decreasing the incidence of variceal hemorrhage."  The author concluded "our study supports that PSE is a safe, effective, semi-invasive alternative to splenectomy in pediatric patients with PHTN. The combination of EVL and PSE is effective treatment for esophageal and gastric varices (not amenable to simple band ligation). Reduced splenic volume and splenic venous return effectively decreased portal flow and pressure. PSE can be successfully performed in pre- and post-transplant transplant patients, and select cirrhotic and noncirrhotic pediatric patients. PSE appears to preserve functional spleen mass and avoids postprocedure accelerated liver disease or encephalopathy. In contrast to shunting, PSE can be effective even in the setting of elevated right-sided heart pressures. Further multicenter collaborative studies with larger and varied patient populations will need to be performed to substantiate our approach and better define patient populations that would benefit most from PSE, sequential PSE or combined interventions. Liver transplantation remains the ideal intervention for anyone with significant decompensated PHTN or advanced hepatic dysfunction".  This is 1 of the 9 valid cases reported in this article. Additionally, the patient underwent surgical shunt after post PSE and reason of surgical shunt was due to recurrent variceal hemorrhage. The time range from PSE to surgical shunt was 7.56 -27.72 months. Splenic function appeared to be preserved during years of follow-up in patient without increased incidence of infection.

The author stated "The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends immunoprophylaxis against Streptococcus pneumoniae, H influenzae and Neisseria meningitidis in all splenectomized patients. Complications of PHTN such as hypersplenism, variceal hemorrhage, and ascites can lead to significant morbidity and mortality in children. Surgical interventions include shunting or splenectomy; however, overwhelming sepsis postsplenectomy is a pressing concern. PSE addresses portal hypertension regardless of etiology as definitive therapy. Most adverse effects following PSE are expected and can be managed conservatively. In our cohort we commonly observed fever, abdominal pain, and leukocytosis without evidence of infection. Pain was effectively controlled with intravenous and oral analgesics. Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs were avoided to minimize hemorrhage. In our experience, prophylactic antibiotics and limiting splenic reduction to no greater than 70% have avoided serious morbidity and mortality. In particular, there was no significant difference in the preprocedure platelet count between patients with and without recurrent thrombocytopenia. After PSE we noted a significant increase in platelets but to a lesser degree in patients who had recurrent hypersplenism. In our patients with esophageal varices, the combination of endoscopic ligation and PSE has been successful in controlling the progression of varices and decreasing the incidence of variceal hemorrhage."  The author concluded "our study supports that PSE is a safe, effective, semi-invasive alternative to splenectomy in pediatric patients with PHTN. The combination of EVL and PSE is effective treatment for esophageal and gastric varices (not amenable to simple band ligation). Reduced splenic volume and splenic venous return effectively decreased portal flow and pressure. PSE can be successfully performed in pre- and post-transplant transplant patients, and select cirrhotic and noncirrhotic pediatric patients. PSE appears to preserve functional spleen mass and avoids postprocedure accelerated liver disease or encephalopathy. In contrast to shunting, PSE can be effective even in the setting of elevated right-sided heart pressures. Further multicenter collaborative studies with larger and varied patient populations will need to be performed to substantiate our approach and better define patient populations that would benefit most from PSE, sequential PSE or combined interventions. Liver transplantation remains the ideal intervention for anyone with significant decompensated PHTN or advanced hepatic dysfunction".  This is 1 of the 9 valid cases reported in this article. On Sunday morning, area of redness was approx 5 inches and bruised area in the center was larger. Pt was seen at UC and was thought to have an injection site reaction as well as an infection and was started on Keflex. Mom continued with zyrtec, tylenol for comfort and applied ice and hydrocortisone. Pt took 2 doses of keflex on Sunday. Area looked alot better on Monday morning. Today in office, pt is much improved. Area appears normal - no swelling, redness, pain. Pt remained afebrile throughout weekend. This is pt's 4th year to get the flu vaccine. "

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Next day at 7: 30am woke up like usual and ate breakfast.  Around 8am, took shower and got chills that is out of norm.  Started to get dress, went down, started to vomit, and could not get up.  Tried to crawl but could not get footing�legs felt like spaghetti.  Patient was able to get up and felt supper shaky; laid on bed gradually got better.  Patient started to sweat and it took about 24 hours to stop shaking.  Patient has never had an experience like that so was very surprised. She ate the same dinner as the night before to make sure that it was not food poisoning and was not.  Patient has received vaccines in the past with no problem besides a sore arm.  Patient has taken same medicine for years; there was no change. Patient lives by herself.  Today went for a walk as usual but did not walk as many hours as usual.   Patient did not call doctor because it was the weekend.  Patient has follow-up with doctor on Thursday in preparation for surgery to replace pacemaker. Patient is almost back to normal.

Started with severe constipation in a breastfed baby. Sever enough he would have fevers until passing it with assistance (stimulation, suppository, etc). From then on he got worse with every injection. Diagnosed with GERD and eventually suggested to put him on Zyrtec for allergies. Had severe protective vomiting several times per day and some weight loss. Eczema. Has been in the ER mulitple times due to breathing issues, has now (5yrs) been diagnosed with mild to severe persistent asthma.
LAB_DATA: At 2yrs allergy testing was done and came back severely positive for almost everything tested.  Was given an Eppi Pen. Went on to see a Gastro and she stated he had too many allergies, that he likely has Mast Cell Activation Disease/Disorder. Specialist ran blood work but does not believe he hast MSA. Limiting toxin exposures in our home and environment helped. Still didnt eat much, was eating mostly eggs until his 18m shots and then stopped eating them. When older I asked why, he said his mouth itched when he ate them. He had "spiders in his ears". Had chronic ear infections until getting tubes at 2yrs. Easily sick, strep multiple times, croup, etc.  He is on Allegra 2x/day as Zyretec gave him night terrors. He is on a steroid for his asthma 2x/day and a rescue inhaler/nebulizer. To this day was have no difinatave answers as to why his body has so many issues/allergies. We just have to deal with the symptoms. After discovering Vax Injury to be a thing, that is the only real explication to his issues as all are side effects to being vaccinated.
HISTORY: Asthma, constant histamine reactions sometimes the cause is unknown due to the number of sensitivities both known and unknown. He has to be on Allegra full time to keep reactions to a minimal level

SYMPTOM_TEXT: When the skin discoloration first began it was also accompanied by red target-like rings on the discoloration marks which led my husband and I to believe that he had gotten ring worm some how. They didn't seem to itch our son though, and we put Miconazole from the local store on it every day. It didn't seem to help though. He didn't run a fever or fall ill from it. We didn't take him to his doc appointment sooner due to those things and his next appointment was 03/18/2019. When we got to his appointment, I asked about what the ash and discoloration was. Dr. said it was eczema, not ring worm and that's why Miconazole didn't work. I asked how he could pick up eczema because that doesn't run on either side of our families. He was not sure. I looked within the vaccine insert under post market-experience on page 17 and found that his last visit and vaccine DTap/IPV/hib fit the time frame perfect.   Eczema is a particular type of inflammatory reaction of the skin in which there is erythema (reddening), edema (swelling), papulles (bumps), and crusting of the skin followed  finally, by lichenification (thickening) and scaling of the skin. Erythema occurs with any skin injury, infection, or inflammation.   Erythema multiforme is most often caused by Herpes Simplex Virus. He received the Varicella vaccine 09/24/2018.
LAB_DATA: none. Dr. just had told us it was eczema, not ring worm. The red rings have since gone about May, but the skin discoloration has remained as well as rough patches of skin.

The patient told him it did not itch, it hurts, and had something like this a couple years ago, which took about 3 or 4 weeks or more to heal, though did not go to the doctor for it years ago.  On the reporting date, the patient was diagnosed with Shingles. The patient was put on Valacyclovir HCl 1gm tablet, every 8 hours, for 7 days. The patient know that it is not supposed to get a Shingrix shot when you have Shingles. But the patient did not even know that the patient had Shingles. The patient asked that would being on the Valtrex (Valacyclovir), reduce the effectiveness of my second Shingrix shot.
