Suspected vaccination failure; influenza A(H3N2); acute respiratory illness; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a adult patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), h3n2 influenza (serious criteria hospitalization) and respiratory disorder (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, h3n2 influenza and respiratory disorder were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, h3n2 influenza and respiratory disorder to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a patient aged between 22 and 63 years of unspecified gender, who was vaccinated with unspecified influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to supplementary table 2 (subject 7) in this literature article. The patient was a part of the study that aimed was to compare antibody titers against both circulating influenza A (H3N2) strains and egg-adapted influenza A (H3N2) strains in acute specimens from individuals with and those without influenza virus infection in the 2017-2018 season. During the severe 2017-2018 influenza season, a study of the effectiveness of influenza vaccine among inpatients with acute respiratory illness as part of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)-sponsored program was performed. No information on patient's medical history, family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On unspecified date, during 2017-2018 influenza season, the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not provided. [In this study, there were 18 individuals who had been vaccinated, and the specific influenza vaccine they received could be confirmed for 15. All 15 individuals with confirmed vaccine product information received vaccines containing inactivated egg-grown virus; 10 received quadrivalent standard-dose vaccines (9 vaccines were produced by GlaxoSmithKline, and 1 was produced by Seqirus), 3 received trivalent high dose vaccines (produced by Sanofi Pasteur), 1 received trivalent adjuvanted vaccine (produced by Seqirus), and 1 received trivalent unadjuvanted vaccine (produced by Seqirus)]. On an unspecified date, during 2017-2018 influenza season, between 27 November 2017 and 31 January 2018, an unknown period after the vaccination, the patient developed acute respiratory illness and subsequently hospitalized. The patient was enrolled less than or equal to 10 days after illness onset during active influenza virus circulation. The patient's throat and nasal swab specimens were collected shortly for influenza virus identification by reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) analysis. The patient was found influenza A(H3N2) Positive. The patient's antibody titers were also measured with neuraminidase-inhibition (NAI) and Microneutralization (MN) assays was determined. However, the authors stated, "This analysis of specimens from adults hospitalized with influenza A(H3N2) virus infection during the 2017-2018 influenza season demonstrated an antibody response specific to egg-adapted strains that was significantly higher among vaccinated individuals. Patient was found to be lying on ground with purse under his head and mother by his side. Per mother, as he left our clinic, he walked outdoors and verbalized that it was blurry and bright to see and passed out immediately. When nurse arrives, patient was found alert, oriented to place, person and time. Initial vital signs while supine at 1145 am, B/P 110/74, AHR 59, blood chemstix 85, pulse oximetry 99% on room air. He was closely monitored for the next 15 minutes outdoors then transferred back to the pediatric treatment room at noon via wheelchair. The primary care provider was notified of incident immediately. It was noted that he had received his meningococcal vaccine prior to leaving his appointment and had not had anything to eat or drink before his visit today.  He was monitored until 1230 pm as vital signs remained stable. He was also given apple juice, crackers and 24 ounces of water while being monitored. Dr. (PCP) evaluated him and  was cleared to be discharged home. Nurse accompanies him by walking him outside as mother had car pulled up and escorted to car. He denied any further symptoms upon discharge.

The night of the vaccination patient threw up and ran a fever of 103.4. The vomitting continued through the next 2 days along with extreme lethargy and the inability to walk. For the next week patient would not/could not hold her head upright, she was sleeping for 20hours a day and when she was awake she stared into space. She refuse to eat. She could not walk or climb which she had been doing for the last 4 months at that point. I took patient to the hospital about a week and a half after vaccination due to episodes of hypothermia, cyanosis, and the extreme lethargy. The lethargy lifted after 2 weeks she began holding her head up again and slowly walking again. We began noticing personality trait differences as well. Increased appetite and mood swings which have not gone away

I had several weeks of thyroid gland pain, even though an ultrasound was normal.   I have had numerous labs, imaging, doctor and specialist appointments plus the one ER visit for pleurisy.  I tested positive for the Epstein Barr Virus (negative Mono) and even though I've been on Prednisone for the past 5 weeks, my inflammation markers are still high and it only seems to be suppressing my symptoms for a bit until they increase the dose again.  There seems to be no hope in sight.

As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), pt symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using it. Pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition.  As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution, and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence the pt suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury.    The reporter considered the events to be related to zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX).  The reporter considered the events to be disabling. Upon internal review, stroke, hearing loss were determined to be medically significant events.

Suspected vaccination failure; influenza A(H3N2); acute respiratory illness; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a adult patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), h3n2 influenza (serious criteria hospitalization) and respiratory disorder (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, h3n2 influenza and respiratory disorder were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, h3n2 influenza and respiratory disorder to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a patient aged between 22 and 63 years of unspecified gender, who was vaccinated with unspecified influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.  The patient was a part of the study that aimed was to compare antibody titers against both circulating influenza A (H3N2) strains and egg-adapted influenza A (H3N2) strains in acute specimens from individuals with and those without influenza virus infection in the 2017-2018 season. During the severe 2017-2018 influenza season, a study of the effectiveness of influenza vaccine among inpatients with acute respiratory illness as part of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)-sponsored Hospitalized Adult Influenza Vaccine Effectiveness Network (HAIVEN) was performed. No information on patient's medical history, family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On unspecified date, during 2017-2018 influenza season, the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not provided. [In this study, there were 18 individuals who had been vaccinated, and the specific influenza vaccine they received could be confirmed for 15. All 15 individuals with confirmed vaccine product information received vaccines containing inactivated egg-grown virus; 10 received quadrivalent standard-dose vaccines (9 vaccines were produced by GlaxoSmithKline, and 1 was produced by Seqirus), 3 received trivalent high dose vaccines (produced by Sanofi Pasteur), 1 received trivalent adjuvanted vaccine (produced by Seqirus), and 1 received trivalent unadjuvanted vaccine (produced by Seqirus)]. On an unspecified date, during 2017-2018 influenza season, between 27 November 2017 and 31 January 2018, an unknown period after the vaccination, the patient developed acute respiratory illness and subsequently hospitalized. The patient was enrolled less than or equal to 10 days after illness onset during active influenza virus circulation. The patient's throat and nasal swab specimens were collected shortly for influenza virus identification by reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) analysis. The patient was found influenza A(H3N2) Positive. The patient's antibody titers were also measured with neuraminidase-inhibition (NAI) and Microneutralization (MN) assays was determined. The microneutralization (MN) egg propagated A/HongKong/4801/2014 (HK-egg) antibody titer was found 160, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/HongKong/4801/2014 (HK) antibody titer was found 20, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Washington/16/2017 (WA) antibody titer was found 10, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Singapore/Infimh-16-0019/2016 (SG) antibody titer was 10, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Maryland/53/2017 (MD) antibody titer was found 10, MN MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Wisconsin/327/2017 (WI) antibody titer was found 10, neuraminidase-inhibition (NAI) MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/HongKong/4801/2014 (HK) antibody titer was found 10 and NAI MDCK-SIAT1 propagated A/Singapore/Infimh-16-0019/2016 (SG) antibody titer was found 10 in patient. The genetic characterization of Influenza A(H3N2) virus strains circulating in patient sample was also determined (results not provided). This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being the time to onset was unknown. This case has been considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure and hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not reported. The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of influenza A (H3N2) infection and unspecified influenza vaccine. However, the authors stated, "This analysis of specimens from adults hospitalized with influenza A(H3N2) virus infection during the 2017-2018 influenza season demonstrated an antibody response specific to egg-adapted strains that was significantly higher among vaccinated individuals. In our study sample, this suggests that the antibody responses to vaccination in this population are highly specific to the egg-adapted strain, with little cross-reactivity to the circulating virus.Additionally, antibody titers against cell-grown influenza A/HongKong/4801/2014(H3N2) virus were similar to those in unvaccinated individuals. In this study sample, this suggests that the antibody responses to vaccination in this population are highly specific to the egg-adapted strain, with little cross-reactivity to the circulating virus. In this study, antibody against the neuraminidase of influenza A/HongKong/4801/2014 virus and influenza A/Singapore/INFIMH-16-0019/2016 virus was not associated with protection against infection. Although neuraminidase content was not standardized in influenza vaccines, it was observed that anti-neuraminidase antibody titers were higher among vaccinated individuals, suggesting that some of the existing anti-neuraminidase antibody in this population resulted from vaccination. The serum specimens in this study were collected at a single time point early during acute illness." The authors concluded, "The conclusions were limited by the inclusion of a small number of specimens from a single hospital. Because the severity of the 2017-2018 epidemic was evident early in the season, it was prioritized rapid serologic testing of the specimens that were available to date during the first half of the season. These 2 factors may limit the broad generalizability of the results; however, the influenza viruses that circulated locally overall and during the analysis period were similar to those that predominated nationwide during the same season. The small sample size also precluded the ability to perform additional subanalyses, to assess whether results might vary within specific age groups or by history of prior vaccination. In one sense, the 2017-2018 influenza vaccine appears to have worked as intended: vaccinated individuals had high antibody titers against the influenza virus strain included in the vaccine. The study adds to the evidence that egg adaptations in the 2017-2018 influenza vaccine strain elicited antibodies to epitopes not conserved in circulating strains. The degree to which this contributed to the marked severity of the 2017- 2018 season remains to be determined. Several vaccine products have been introduced into the vaccine market that are produced in cells and do not have the same emergent egg adaptations seen in recent influenza A(H3N2) vaccine strains. At this time, evidence for the effectiveness of these vaccines relative to those produced in eggs is limited because few head-to-head trials have been performed. Early data suggest that cell-based vaccines have somewhat improved protection in clinical trials and in the community. Unfortunately, these vaccines are still dependent on selecting viruses that are close antigenic matches to those that will circulate and are subject to the limitations of annual strain selection time lines. This underscores the need for the development of the next-generation of influenza vaccines that provide better, broader, and longer-lasting protection." This is 1 of the 4 valid cases reported in the same literature article. On the 13th, I felt lethargic and "out of it" all day, more specifically -  weak and dizzy when up and walking around.  I felt very warm all day, and because of the other symptoms, I didn't think to take my temperature until later that afternoon. I didn't have a  proper thermometer, so I took my temperature under my arm with a scientific field thermometer - it registered approximately 104.5 degrees - between 104-105 degrees Fahrenheit. This was the best measurement I could get as the thermometer is graduated every 2 degrees (i.e., I was reading between 104-106). My regular "medical" thermometer had a dead battery.  I didn't seek treatment, but took 2-200mg tablets of ibuprofen every 4 hours  (4pm, 8pm, then again at 8am the next day).  The second day (9/14), I took my temperature again and it had come down to a little over 100 degrees. I took the last ibuprofen dose of 400mg at that time.

extensive thrombosis; normal transhepatic pressures with massive debilitating splenomegaly; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of thrombosis in a 6-year-old patient who received Haemophilus influenzae type b vaccine for prophylaxis.  Co-suspect products included PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE (PCV13) for prophylaxis, PPSV23 PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE for prophylaxis, piperacillin for prophylaxis and tazobactam for prophylaxis.   The subject's past medical history included varicose veins ligation and splenomegaly. Concurrent medical conditions included portal hypertension (etiology was autoimmune hepatitis ), autoimmune hepatitis, hemorrhage, thrombocytosis,genetic predisposition to myelodysplastic-like syndrome and varicosity.   On an unknown date, the patient received Haemophilus influenzae type b vaccine at an unknown dose, PCV13 at an unknown dose, PPSV23 PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE at an unknown dose, piperacillin (intravenous) at an unknown dose and frequency and tazobactam (intravenous) at an unknown dose and frequency. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of thrombosis in a 6-year-old female who was vaccinated with unspecified Haemophilus influenzae type B, unspecified meningococcal vaccines and unspecified pneumococcal vaccine (PCV13 followed in 1 month by PPSV23 when feasible) (manufacturer unknown for all) for prophylaxis.   The patient was a part of cohort study that aimed to determine whether Partial Splenic Embolization (PSE) was safe and effective in the pediatric population.  The study was a retrospective review of a single-center experience for all patients ages 0 to 21 who underwent PSE for the management of portal hypertension (PHTN) between January 2010 and August 2017. The study presented the experience with the use of this modality in different pediatric populations with PHTN to better understand the rationale for safe and appropriate application of this treatment. [In this study, [In this study, recommended PSE to patients with bleeding tendencies that were not optimal candidates for an open surgical shunt or repeated endoscopies. This includes the following patient populations: Patients with baseline compromised respiratory function (ie, cystic fibrosis [CF]). 2. Patients with significant synthetic dysfunction that may progress to liver failure after shunting. 3. Patients with early signs of encephalopathy that could potentially worsen with increased portal systemic shunting. 4. Patients with abnormal right heart function that could develop cardiac decompensation or shunt failure. 5. Patients deemed to be marginal candidates for repeated anesthesia. 6. Patients with splenic vein thrombosis. 7. Patients with characteristics predicting poor wound healing or other surgical complications. 8. Patients with unfavorable anatomy, increased transhepatic resistance, or elevated right heart pressures to permit mesoportal shunting (Rex shunt)]. The patient had thrombocytopenia and/or recurrent variceal bleeding.   The patient had portal hypertension, whose etiology was autoimmune hepatitis (AI). The patient also noted to have evidence of varices before PSE. For this, the patient underwent endoscopic variceal ligation (EVL) before PSE. The patient had significant splenomegaly before PSE. This patient was found to have a genetic predisposition to myelodysplastic-like syndrome and thrombocytosis. it was reported that Myelodysplastic-like syndrome has been associated with both thrombotic and hemorrhagic complications. The decision to proceed with PSE was determined by the primary hepatologist and surgeon after careful discussion with both patient and family members regarding alternative approaches. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided.   On an unspecified date, at least 2 weeks before PSE, the patient received unspecified Haemophilus influenzae type B, unspecified meningococcal vaccines and unspecified pneumococcal vaccine (PCV13 followed in 1 month by PPSV23 when feasible) (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown, batch number not provided for all), in order to reduce the risk of future infection by encapsulated organisms, should the procedure lead to a complication necessitating total splenectomy. The age of vaccination was not provided. It was reported that the patient received broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotic prophylaxis, typically with piperacillin/tazobactam, before the procedure to prevent infection of infarcted splenic tissue. This was continued for 5 to 7 days. On an unknown date, before PSE, the patient's platelet count was noted at 153�10E9/L and white blood cells count (WBC) was 1.4�10E9/L (normal range not provided).   On an unspecified date between January 2010 and August 2017, at least 2 weeks after vaccination, the patient underwent PSE by interventional radiology under general anesthesia via percutaneous femoral artery approach under sterile conditions utilizing guidelines based on the Spigos technique to minimize complications. At the time of PSE, the patient was not actively bleeding. Diagnostic angiographies of the celiac axis and splenic arteries were obtained to determine the target splenic arterial branches, to identify accessory branches to other tissues from the splenic artery and to determine baseline splenic volume. Abdominal sonograms with doppler analysis of hepatic and splenic vessels were performed post procedure to assess vessel patency and the degree of intra-abdominal-free fluid. Arteriograms of partial splenic embolization (PSE), pre-embolization with capillary blush demonstrated splenomegaly and post-embolization with capillary blush revealed multiple defects before and after esophageal varices.   Information regarding patient's blood transfusions was not available. The patient was admitted to hospital after PSE for further observation and management. [In this study, patients received patient-controlled analgesia for pain control and to prevent splinting and associated pulmonary complications such as atelectasis and pneumonia]. The patient underwent EVL intervention post PSE. The patient did not develop infection with encapsulated organisms. Post-PSE, the patient's platelet count was 1335�10E9/L. the antibiotics were converted to an oral regimen before hospital discharge. [In this study, criteria for hospital discharge included adequate control of abdominal pain with oral medications, adequate oral intake/hydration, and absence of post procedure infection. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) showed splenomegaly and postembolization with necrotic areas surrounding the spleen. Three patients demonstrated complete resolution of varices. An additional 7 patients were noted to have a decrease in variceal grade].  On an unknown date, the patient was discharged fulfilling the criteria for hospital discharge that included (adequate control of abdominal pain with oral medications), adequate oral intake/hydration, and absence of post procedure infection. The patient was followed-up in the outpatient hepatology clinic. Hematologic indices including white blood cell (WBC) and platelet counts were monitored. Imaging was repeated as indicated. The patient developed extensive thrombosis and re-admitted to hospital. The extensive thrombosis of her splenic vein, portal vein, and inferior vena-cava (IVC) at the level of the renal veins necessitating thrombectomy and urgent splenectomy 9 days after PSE. This patient had normal transhepatic pressures with massive debilitating splenomegaly. The procedure was performed for compassionate reasons and an estimated 80% of the spleen was infarcted in a single procedure. Platelet levels peaked at an astonishing 2484�E109/L in this patient after PSE necessitating chronic antiplatelet therapy.  [In this study, 7 patients required readmission after initial discharge 2 of these patients were discharged only 1 day after PSE and returned the following day with fevers and abdominal pain with an unremarkable diagnostic evaluation]. Surveillance endoscopy was also performed 3 months after PSE to evaluate for persistent varices. Splenic function appeared to be preserved during years of follow-up in patient without increased incidence of infection.  This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization/serious per reporter. [In this study, Thrombosis included splenic vein, portal vein, and inferior vena cava at the level of the renal veins reported by the Institute.  The outcome of the event was not reported.  The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of thrombosis and Unspecified Haemophilus influenza type B vaccine, unspecified meningococcal vaccine and unspecified pneumococcal (PCV13 followed by PPSV23) vaccine. The author stated "The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends immunoprophylaxis against Streptococcus pneumoniae, H influenzae and Neisseria meningitidis in all splenectomized patients. Complications of PHTN such as hypersplenism, variceal hemorrhage, and ascites can lead to significant morbidity and mortality in children. Surgical interventions include shunting or splenectomy; however, overwhelming sepsis postsplenectomy is a pressing concern. PSE addresses portal hypertension regardless of etiology as definitive therapy. Most adverse effects following PSE are expected and can be managed conservatively. In our cohort we commonly observed fever, abdominal pain, and leukocytosis without evidence of infection. Pain was effectively controlled with intravenous and oral analgesics. Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs were avoided to minimize hemorrhage. In our experience, prophylactic antibiotics and limiting splenic reduction to no greater than 70% have avoided serious morbidity and mortality. In particular, there was no significant difference in the preprocedure platelet count between patients with and without recurrent thrombocytopenia. After PSE we noted a significant increase in platelets but to a lesser degree in patients who had recurrent hypersplenism. In our patients with esophageal varices, the combination of endoscopic ligation and PSE has been successful in controlling the progression of varices and decreasing the incidence of variceal hemorrhage."  The author concluded "our study supports that PSE is a safe, effective, semi-invasive alternative to splenectomy in pediatric patients with PHTN. The combination of EVL and PSE is effective treatment for esophageal and gastric varices (not amenable to simple band ligation). Reduced splenic volume and splenic venous return effectively decreased portal flow and pressure. PSE can be successfully performed in pre- and post-transplant transplant patients, and select cirrhotic and noncirrhotic pediatric patients. PSE appears to preserve functional spleen mass and avoids postprocedure accelerated liver disease or encephalopathy. In contrast to shunting, PSE can be effective even in the setting of elevated right-sided heart pressures. Further multicenter collaborative studies with larger and varied patient populations will need to be performed to substantiate our approach and better define patient populations that would benefit most from PSE, sequential PSE or combined interventions. Liver transplantation remains the ideal intervention for anyone with significant decompensated PHTN or advanced hepatic dysfunction".  This is 1 of the 9 valid cases reported in this article. Delivered neonate at 36.3 week of gestation; Candidiasis; Urinary tract infection; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 06-Aug-2019, concerning a 32-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight: 199 lbs, height: 60 inches and body mass index (BMI): 38.9, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had 5 previous pregnancies which included 4 full term, live births and 1 spontaneous abortion. No birth defects were reported. Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The subject did not have a prior history of use of tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject's medical history included history of deep vein thrombosis. The subject's concomitant medications included Prenatal Vitamins (mineral NOS, vitamin NOS) as a supplement and Lovenox (enoxaparin sodium) for deep vein thrombosis.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 27-Aug-2018, estimated delivery date (EDD) was 03-Jun-2019 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was 23-Jun-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 29-Oct-2018, at gestation age of 9 weeks, the subject was administered Flucelvax QIVc [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, at a dose of 0.5 ml, batch number: 252664, expiration date, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as vaccine exposure during pregnancy) for influenza immunisation.  On 07-Nov-2018, the subject developed urinary tract infection (UTI) and candidiasis. The subject received 0.4% terconazole, administered via vaginal route, as a corrective treatment for candidiasis, and Macrobid (nitrofurantoin) at a dose of 100mg, administered via oral route, two times per day, as a corrective treatment for UTI.   On 08-Nov-2018, the subject recovered from the event of �candidiasis', and treatment with terconazole was discontinued.  On 14-Nov-2018, the subject recovered from the event of �urinary tract infection', and the treatment with Macrobid was discontinued.  On 28-May-2019, at gestational age of 36.3 weeks, the subject vaginally delivered male neonate (explicitly coded as �Premature delivery'). The neonate's birth weight was 3090 g, head circumference was 34.3 cm and length was 48.3 cm. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) score at one minute was 7 and at five minutes was 5.  APGAR score was not reported for 10 minutes. No major congenital malformation was identified at birth. There were no pregnancy complications noted.  The case is linked to 201904408, the corresponding child case.  Follow up received by other health care professional on 17-Sep-2019: The information on ongoing use of Lovenox and APGAR score at one minute and at five minutes were provided. Action taken for Lovenox was updated. The narrative was amended accordingly.  Company comment: A 32-year-old female pregnant subject experienced candidiasis, urinary tract infection and premature delivery after receipt of Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. Chronology seems plausible for the events of candidiasis and urinary tract infection while for premature delivery remains unsuggestive. UTIs are common during pregnancy, because the growing uterus makes pressure on the bladder and urinary tract. Candida infections are also frequent during pregnancy. According to one study, about 20 percent of women have Candida yeast in their vagina normally. That number goes up to 30 percent during pregnancy. Although causality was highly confounded, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related for all 3 events. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.; Reporter's Comments: A 32-year-old female pregnant subject experienced candidiasis, urinary tract infection and premature delivery after receipt of Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Premature delivery; Yeast; Anemia; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 18-Sep-2019, concerning a 29-year-old, adult female pregnant subject of body weight: 144 lbs, height: 64 inches and body mass index (BMI): 24.7 [ethnicity: not reported] enrolled in a study.  The subject's obstetrical history included seven previous pregnancies (five full term live births, one preterm live birth and one spontaneous abortion). The subject did not have history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and did not have maternal and paternal history with MCM. The subject did not consume tobacco, alcohol and illicit-drugs.  The subject's historical condition included bacterial vaginosis. The subject's historical medication included Metrogel (metronidazole). The subject's concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamin (unspecified vitamins).   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 25-Jun-2018. The subject's estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated delivery date (CEDD) were 01-Apr-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 01-Aug-2018, the subject performed cystic fibrosis mutation analysis and spinal muscular atrophy (mother+carrier) and no MCM was noted.  On 07-Aug-2018 and 13-Aug-2018, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 15-Oct-2018, approximately at gestational age of 16 weeks, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV NVD (Flucelvax QIVc) (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 252664, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration: not reported) (explicitly coded as Vaccine exposure during pregnancy) for Influenza immunisation.  On 15-Oct-2018, the subject performed Quad screen and ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 12-Dec-2018, 1 month and 27 days after vaccination, the subject developed anemia. The subject started corrective treatment with ferrous sulfate, at dose of one tablet, twice a day, orally.  On 22-Dec-2018, the subject recovered from anemia.  On 09-Jan-2019 and 31-Jan-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 14-Feb-2019, 3 months and 30 days after vaccination, the subject developed yeast. The subject started corrective corrective treatment with Metrogel (metronidazole), 0.75% gel, twice a day, vaginally.   On 21-Feb-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 24-Feb-2019, the subject recovered from yeast.  On 09-Mar-2019, at gestational age of 36.7 weeks, the subject vaginally delivered male neonate. No pregnancy complications were noted. The neonate's birth weight was 2977 g, head circumference was 33 cm and length was 52.1 cm. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) score at one minute was 9, at five minutes was 9 and no data was reported for APGAR score at ten minutes. No major congenital malformation was identified at birth.  This case is linked to 201904705, the corresponding child case.  Company comment:The patient was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV NVD (Flucelvax QIVc) at approximately 16 weeks of gestational age (explicitly considered as vaccine exposure during pregnancy).  The patient experienced anaemia and fungal infection, approximately two and four months after vaccination, respectively. Chronology seems plausible. At 36.7-week gestational age, the subject gave birth to a male infant (reported as preterm delivery). The decision to administer a vaccine during pregnancy is related to medical decision making by the mother and her physician and is not related to any property of the medication. The event of vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related considering the intended use of the vaccine. By early morning (9/24), her hives had spread all the way down her legs, and the hives were raised and  severely spread all across her back and stomach. We have been continuing  to take the prescribed medicine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Injections given and patient asked to lie down for 5-7 minutes since receiving  Gardisil vaccine.  Patient in room with sibling. Sibling reported that after about 5 minutes patient got up from supine position, stood, became weak and fainted.  Sibling called for help. Patient was pale, clammy and semi- alert.  Placed back on bed in supine position and attended to by physician.  After about 25 minutes skin color pinked up and she was alert and felt well.  She got up to leave and in the waiting room became weak, dizzy and almost passed out again.  Patient was pale again and alert. She felt dizzy.  Placed in supine position on bed with knees up. Blood glucose level checked and at 99. B/P was at 72/40.  Given oral fluids and pretzels to eat.  Patient observed about 45 minutes and B/P was at 98/69.  No longer pale, alert and oriented and dizziness improving.  Patient rechecked by physician  and released to home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 30 minutes of receiving the Boostrix Tdap shot, I suffered a severe allergic reaction. My whole body became heavy, and I was unable to move or get out of bed. I felt a wave of extreme fatigue and weakness wash over me and was in a mental fog. My mental intake and comprehension, as well as my response time was greatly slowed. I was able to finally get out of bed about an hour after the reaction, but stayed in a mental fog for weeks, if not months after that. The fatigue is overwhelming and has not gone away.
LAB_DATA: 3 separate doctor visits to address fatigue and mental symptoms. Diagnosis and treatment ongoing.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediately upon injection I felt like I had received an electric shock.   A few hours later I began shivering severely and uncontrollably.   This lasted for hours.    Later I developed a severe headache.   I vomited and felt weak and dizzy.   I still feel ill.  I have never had a reaction to any vaccine like this.   I was very frightened until I googled Shingrix reactions and realized my problems were common.

After receiving my TDAP vaccine, I experienced the expected soreness in my left arm at the injection site. But in the early morning of the 3rd day I began feeling extreme pain, which only increased daily to the point where my husband insisted on taking me to the ER.  The pain feels as though my arm is being ripped out of it's socket. It is a constant pain that is only increasing over time. My left arm is completely useless. It is not paralyzed or anything, but is immobile unless I am willing to endure extreme, excruciating pain. The ER sent me home with instructions to follow up with my clinic when they opened that morning (I checked into the ER shortly before 04:00am on the morning of September 25, 2019). My clinic suggested Motrin for 48 hours and to see them if after 48 hours the pain did not decrease. The pain increased again overnight and my clinic was able to see me today, September 26th, around 11am. They suggested 72 hours of Motrin as needed, and told me if the pain is still there on Monday they will send me to a neurologist. Therefore, we are assuming there has been nerve damage.  There was never any swelling, redness, or signs of fever. I am 28 weeks pregnant, with 2 living boys whom have both been fully vaccinated with no issues. My due date is Dec 17, 2019.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 05/18/19 I received the first Shingrix shot without experiencing side effects.  On 07/17/19 I received the second Shingrix shot at 9:00 a.m. at the same Pharmacy and continued with my usual daily routine. At bed time (about 10:00 p.m.) I suddenly started to shiver uncontrolably and felt ice-cold for several minutes. When the shivers finally subsided, I fell asleep. The next morning (07/18/19) I felt slightly nauseated and very sweaty but forced myself to get up and feed the cat. When I was in the process of setting his bowl on the floor, I lost consciousness and collapsed on the concrete floor. My partner heard the shattering of the food bowl and found me. When I came to he helped me back to bed and called the ER at Hospital. The doctor on duty, urged my partner to bring me to the ER, since I had experienced syncope and collapse. By the time we reached the hospital, I was feeling well again (aside from a couple of bruises from the fall). Because the tests run by the ER staff showed no abnormalities, they concluded that the episode I had experienced was attributable to the Shingrix shot.  It turned out to be a very expensive shot.

Dizzy / Dizziness; Nauseous; Vomit; Fell in bathroom a few times; Feeling hot; Muscle aches; Sore arm/feet hurt; Severe flu like symptoms; Headache; Chills; Feeling off center; vertido; hyperventilating; not able to catch her breath; feel thristy; breathing more deeply and through her mouth; This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a 67-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. In September 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 12th September 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced pain in arm, influenza-like symptoms, headache, chills, muscle pain and feeling hot. On 13th September 2019, the patient experienced dizziness, nausea, vomiting and fall. In September 2019, the patient experienced feeling abnormal, vertigo, hyperventilation, shortness of breath, thirst and mouth breathing. The patient was treated with ranitidine, antiinflammatory/antirheumatic products (Anti-Inflammatory), non-drug therapy (Heating Pad (Nos)) and non-drug therapy (Ice Pack (No Medication)). Rechallenge with Shingrix was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in arm, chills, nausea, vomiting, muscle pain, fall, feeling hot, feeling abnormal, vertigo, hyperventilation and shortness of breath were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the influenza-like symptoms, thirst and mouth breathing were unknown and the outcome of the headache and dizziness were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain in arm, influenza-like symptoms, headache, chills, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, muscle pain, fall, feeling hot, feeling abnormal, vertigo, hyperventilation, shortness of breath, thirst and mouth breathing to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient had injections in her right arm.  The patient received Shingrix and had sore arm and experienced severe flu like symptoms. All the symptoms she experienced are listed in this report under adverse events.  The patient felt so dizzy that she fell in her bathroom a few times. The dizziness caused her to be nauseous and vomit. She has been taking Ranitidine and anti-inflammatories and they have helped with the nausea and muscle aches. All symptoms have resolved except for headache, dizziness and nausea which are still present on and off. She described it as still feeling off center. She used a heating pad and ice packs for the muscle aches. She said her feet also hurt but they always hurt. The reporter stated that the dizziness has gotten better and was more like vertigo at the time of reporting. She states she has been drinking alot and feels thirsty since receiving Shingrix. It could be that she was breathing more deeply and through her mouth, hyperventilating, not able to catch her breath when she was vomiting. The reporter consented to follow up.

Further, as a tragic consequence of the Company's wrongful conduct, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of the Company's conduct, the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the 2nd dose of the shingrix vaccine on Saturday 6/15/19 mid-day. By Sunday 6/16/19, he developed a fever of over 100 degrees. He took some acetaminophen and went to see his doctor Monday morning who instructed him to continuing taking acetaminophen as necessary. His fever persisted and by Wednesday evening, his temperature had gone over 102 degrees. On Thursday morning, he went to see the doctor and was asked to go to the Emergency department next door at hospital. He was given many tests and was immediately admitted due to suspicious images in upper lung. He was put in isolation since they did not know the cause of the problem. By Friday, he was admitted to the ICU and by Friday afternoon, he was not able to breathe on his own and a respirator was put in. He was given different antibiotics and various anesthesia and was in an unconscious state for the next 8 plus days. By the time the respirator was removed, he was told he had "acute respiratory distress syndrome". His lungs were not functioning and had dark images throughout. He was discharged on 7/16/19 and has been regaining breathing and physical strength. Pulmonologist says it will probably take 1 year to recover completely.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient returned to pharmacy day after immunization to report redness, warmth and itchiness below injection site on left arm. She stated she had taken diphenhydramine tablet yesterday when itching began (in afternoon a few hours after vaccination). After further questioning of patient, she asked if having an allergy to alpha-gal could contribute to her reaction. When I pulled her immunization sheet, she had not listed an allergy. I said it could be a factor in the reaction and told her that I would be reporting the reaction and advised her to watch the reaction site for any changes and to continue diphenhydramine for now. I also counseled her that if the reaction changed or got worse to see medical treatment immediately.
ALLERGIES: Codeine, Morphine, Galactose (Alpha-gal) - disclosed only when pt came back to report reaction.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Sore arm, general body ache, slight fever (99.3), accelerated heartbeat, grogginess

Patient called the pharmacy approximately 7 hours after vaccine administration to report itchiness at injection site. When questioned, she said the area did feel warm to the touch and described the area as slightly "swollen". She did not report any breathing issues or swelling of the tongue. I suggested she take a Benadryl tablet (diphenhydramine) , which she confirmed she had available at home. I instructed her if the reaction changed or got more severe to see medical attention immediately. I also informed her that I would be reporting this as an adverse reaction and incident report.  Patient had received a Fluzone High Dose vaccination on 9/13/19 and a Prevnar 13 vaccination on 9/8/2018 with no reactions to either injection.
OTHER_MEDS: Not known - pt has diabetes, fills rx's elsewhere

Finger flange of the syringe broke which made a deep cut on the left pointer finger.; Finger flange of the syringe broke which made a deep cut on the left pointer finger.; the finger flange of the syringe broke/ PQC: Yes; The patient "was using a PNEUMOV AX 23 syringe and while injecting PNEUMOVAX 23 on 9/15/2019, the finger flange of the syringe broke which made a deep cut on the left pointer finger; This spontaneous report as received from a 40 year-old male pharmacy technician who is also the patient.   The patient did not have concurrent or historical conditions, drug reactions, allergies, or concomitant medications.    On 15-SEP-2019, the patient was was using a pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) (lot # S012244 with expiry date of 09-FEB-2021) syringe and while injecting the vaccine, the finger flange (at the end towards plunger not needle) of the syringe broke (syringe issue) which made a deep cut on the left pointer finger (skin laceration). The finger was treated by washing the site and applying a bandage. Then, another syringe of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was administered without difficulty. On 16-SEP-2019, the patient was recovered from the events. There was a product quality complaint involved, but the product would not be retrieved as syringe was used. Additionally, it was reported that the syringe tip cap was attached properly prior to use, the syringe tray intact and undamaged, the cellophane cover of the syringe tray intact and completely sealed on receipt and the syringe carton was not damaged prior to use.   The causality assessment between skin laceration, product quality complaint and syringe issue with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was not provided.

trouble hearing out of left ear; complete loss of vision for short periods of time; trouble walking; extremely dizzy; vertigo; Initial information received on 20-Sep-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case received from a nurse.  This case involves a 82 years old female patient who experienced trouble hearing out of left ear (hypoacusis), complete loss of vision for short periods of time (blindness), trouble walking (gait disturbance), extremely dizzy (dizziness) and vertigo (vertigo), while she received vaccine INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE [FLUZONE HIGH DOSE].  The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  On 12-Sep-2019 at 2:09 pm, the patient received a 0.5 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE lot UJ221AB and Exp. Date 01-Apr-2020 via intramuscular route in the left deltoid.  On 13-Sep-2019 at night around 3 am, the patient developed a serious trouble hearing out of left ear (hypoacusis), complete loss of vision for short periods of time (blindness), trouble walking (gait disturbance), extremely dizzy (dizziness) 12 hours 51 minutes following the administration of INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE. patient was diagnosed with vertigo. The patient was hospitalized on the same day these events occurred and discharged on 14-Sep-2019 (hospitalization duration 1 day). She was told to go to emergency room.  Other relevant tests not reported.    Final diagnosis was vertigo, hypoacusis, blindness, gait disturbance and dizziness.  It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  The patient was recovering from all the events.  List of documents held by sender: none.; Sender's Comments: This case involves a 82 years old female patient who developed vertigo, hypoacusis, blindness, gait disturbance and dizziness after vaccination with FLUZONE HIGH DOSE. Time to onset was compatible. However, patient's medical condition at the time of vaccination and lab tests ruling out alternate etiologies were not reported. Based upon the reported information, the role of vaccine cannot be assessed.

Causality assessment was not reported by the reporter.  This is one of two reports received from the same reporter.

Seizure like episode; Migraine; Vomiting; Nausea; Flu-like symptoms; Information received on 14SEP2019 from a consumer via a website.  A 35 year old female experienced seizures like episode (PT: Seizure like phenomena), flu-like symptoms (PT: Influenza like illness), nausea (PT: Nausea), vomiting (PT: Vomiting), migraine (PT: Migraine), following the administration of BioThrax.  The consumer claimed to have suffered progressively worse symptoms after anthrax vaccinations in December 2017, April 2018 and August 2018. It was reported that after the first vaccine, she experienced flu-like symptoms including headaches, sweats and coughing. After the second shot, she experienced nausea, vomiting and migraines, in addition to her prior symptoms. She also received emergency room treatment for migraines during this period.  The progressively worsening reactions to the first two vaccines led the consumer to withdraw her informed consent to the third administration of the vaccine, and she repeatedly requested a waiver from vaccination from the doctor, her patient advocate, and her chain of command. Although she received a week-long delay in vaccine, she did not obtain a waiver.  After the compulsory administration of the third anthrax vaccine, she developed nausea within a day. More symptoms developed over the course of weeks resulting in multiple overnight stints at the hospital. Medical staff instructed her and her husband, to wait out the reaction at home and avoid seeking treatment, as reported by the consumer. But when she became non-responsive during episodes of seizure-like shaking, her husband paid out-of-pocket for emergency room treatment. The seizure-like episodes continued for at least three weeks after the administration of the vaccine.   Outcome of the reported events was unknown at the time of report.   Company Comments: The described events of seizure-like episode, flu-like symptoms, nausea, vomiting and migraine have been reported with reasonable time relation to intake of Biothrax, with flu-like symptoms having recurred with repeated administration.  No medical history nor diagnostic evaluations were reported in the article, therefore causality cannot be ruled out.  That being said,  the causality assessment is considered to be probably related to the administration of vaccine.; Sender's Comments: Company Comments: The described events of seizure-like episode, flu-like symptoms, nausea, vomiting and migraine have been reported with reasonable time relation to intake of Biothrax, with flu-like symptoms having recurred with repeated administration. SYMPTOM_TEXT: After checking out and leaving the doctor's office after a routine well-child exam, we got in our car. Right after my son closed the door and fastened his seat belt, he reclined his seat slightly. I jokingly asked if he was already feeling lethargic. We were warned that he might be lethargic for about 3 days. He did not respond. His eyes rolled back and his upper body began shaking. His head was shaking as well. I began yelling at him and grabbed his arm, but he didn't respond to me. The movement lasted approximately 30 seconds, but could be slightly more or less. (It seemed like forever.) I was about to get out of the car and run for help inside the doctor's office when his body relaxed, and his eyes closed completely. He then opened his eyes and looked at me. He did not know what had just happened and thought he had just fallen asleep. He was slightly  disoriented,  alert, but slightly lethargic. He was extremely pale, diaphoretic and his pulse was approximately in the 40s. It had been 84 in the doctor's office. He was able to stand and walk and we went back into the doctor's office. I explained what had just happened.  They took his temperature and led us into a room for him to lie down. The doctor came out and looked at him. He explained that he just passed out and that it is common after shots and blood draws. It was a blood pressure thing and he needed to rest. No exam was done and no vital signs taken. I took his pulse and it was 70. He was told to rest there for a bit. After 15 minutes, he felt stronger and we left the doctor's office.
HISTORY: None besides acne. Acne not treated by anything other than over-the-counter cleansers and creams.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient passed out after leaning over to tie her shoelace; This spontaneous report was received from a physician via company representative, referring to a 11-year-old female patient. The patient's medical history, concurrent condition, drug allergies/reactions and concomitant medications were unknown. On 13-AUG-2019, the patient was vaccinated with hpv rL1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) (strength, dose, schedule, anatomical location, lot# and expiry date was unknown) via intramuscular route for vaccination. On the same day the patient was also vaccinated with diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified), tetanus toxoid (manufacturer unknown) and meningococcal ACYW conj vaccine (dip toxoid) (MENACTRA) (strengths, doses, schedules, anatomical locations, route of administrations, lot#s and expiry dates not reported) for prophylaxis. On the same day (13-AUG-2019), the patient passed out after leaning over to tie her shoelace (loss of consciousness). The patient sought medical attention. The patient did not receive any treatment or undergo any lab diagnostics/studies for the event. The physician observed the patient for about an hour and after the patient recovered completely she was sent home on the same day. There was no associated product quality complaint. Cancer and overdose were not involved. The reporter did not provide the causality assessment between the suspect therapies and the reported events.  Upon internal review, the event loss of consciousness was determined to be medically significant.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: He developed febrile seizures / hospitalized many times at unspecified times due to seizures; Developed epilepsy at age of 4; This spontaneous report was received from a consumer (patient's mother) regarding a currently 5 years old male patient. Information on patient's current conditions, drug allergies/reactions were not reported.Concomitant medications included divalproex sodium (DEPAKOTE). On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with first dose of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (MMR), 1 regular injection, for prophylaxis (dose, route, lot# and expiry date was not reported).The consumer reported that the patient had received MMR (not  M-M-R II) vaccine around 12 to18 months of age. On an unknown date (reported as within 24 hours of vaccination), the patient developed febrile seizures (febrile convulsion). The consumer reported that her son had been hospitalized many times at unspecified hospitals at unspecified times due to seizures. On an unknown date (reported as at the age of 4), the patient developed epilepsy (also reported as pertinent medical history).The patient sought medical attention. The consumer stated that she was not anti-vaccine. She was against putting her son's life in danger. She also stated that she highly doubted her son would have had epilepsy if he had not gotten that first shot of MMR. The consumer stated that her son was up to date on all vaccines except MMR because he tolerated monovalent vaccines. The consumer wanted to speak to the person who made the decision to stop making MMR as a monovalent vaccine. There was no product quality complaint (PQC) was involved. The outcome of the event febrile seizures was reported as not recovered, however for epilepsy it was unknown.Causality of the events were not reported.   Upon internal review, the event febrile seizures and epilepsy were determined to be medically significant.

pneumonia; COPD exacerbation; herpes zoster; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a female patient of unknown age. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not provided. Her concurrent condition included chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). In or around 28-MAY-2017, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dosage, route, lot number and expiration date were not reported) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster).  Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (date unknown in 2017), the patient suffered from COPD exacerbation and pneumonia, which required hospitalization. Additionally, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (date unknown in 2017), the patient also suffered from lesions and was diagnosed with herpes zoster.  As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the product. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of the company wrongful conduct, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of the company's conduct, the patient had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was reported as not recovered. The events were considered to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).   The events herpes zoster, COPD exacerbation and pneumonia were considered to be disabling. Upon internal review, the event pneumonia was determined to be medically significant.
CUR_ILL: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease; Routine health maintenance

Starting about 9 pm on 9-19, I had extreme diarrhea. Then in the next hour or so, I started having really bad aches and chills. About 10:30 I threw up a lot, everything in my stomach from dinner and all that I had to drink. I was up all night throwing up and having diarrhea. I started having a fever of 102 around 3 AM on 9-20. From 9 PM on 9-19 to about 11 PM on 9-20, I threw up 12 times and had diarrhea about 8 or so times. I was not able to keep down any liquids or food and my body was aching so bad that I could not move. Because of not being able to keep down any fluids (and having a fever and sweating a lot) and also breastfeeding, I felt like I was seriously dehydrated and that I should see a doctor. I called my 24/7 nurse hotline around 8 PM on 9-20 through my insurance company, and the nurse instructed me to go into the ER within the next hour, as I was probably severely dehydrated. I told myself if I threw up in the next 2 hours, that I would go in. I was able at that point to hold down a little bit of water and didn't end up going in, although I probably should have. I felt slightly better on 9-21, but still very weak and dehydrated.
PRIOR_VAX: Almost every year I get the flu shot, I get a similar type of reaction - aches, chills, fever, throwing up.

Syncope and collapse (ICD10-R55). 17 y/o male who received vaccines being HPV the last one given of 3 on DOS. Pt felt light headache, body was stiff and collapsed. He was somewhat disoriented, pale and clammy, he was assisted to the bed laying down with legs held high. BP 113-43, HR variation 30s-50s at 3:45 PM; pt oriented and conscious at this time. Repeat BP at 4:00 PM 121/67 HR 55. EKG showed NSR with rate variation. His O2sats were in the 80s, w/supplemental Oxygen 8 lpm, sats up to 100%. O2 decreased to 6 lpm with sat still at 100%. Pt had 2 other HPV vaccines with no reaction. Pt continued alert and oriented, HOB raised at 45 degrees. BP at 4:12PM 123/64, HR=51 O2sat=100%. O2 removed at 4:16 PM O2 sats holding at 99% on RA. BP at 4:19 pm 108/77 with HR=64(sitting). BP standing at 4:22 PM = 109/47 with HR=63. Pt continues A/O X3. No neuro deficits; taking for a walk with no complaints; taken back to room BP at 4:25 PM = 101/35 HR=60. Neuro-exam = No deficits. Pt denies headache, dizziness, chest pain, sod, doe, vision changes, paresthesias. BP checked again = 106-56, HR=61. Pt referred to Dr, Pediatric Cardiologist. Pt currently not clear for sports, no PE or strenuous activities until cardiac evaluation. Strict ER precautions d/w patient and his fatherin any significant headaches, dizziness, disorientation, lethargy, difficult breathing, chest pain. 09/26/19=F/U on vaccine reaction. Pt denies any symptoms since 09/25/19; has an appointment with Ped. Cardiologist, Dr next week.

I continued to treat this at home up until Saturday when I noticed a small rash on my right arm.  The following Sunday morning the rash had spread and was raised, and scattered. However, the swelling had gone down. The rash was very warm to the touch and holding heat. Later in the day, the rash spread even more. The DR was then able to determine it was not a hematoma, or allergic reaction. I also sent my DR the results and she asked if the injection site was cleaned. The pharmacist that administered the vaccine did not swab prior that I can recall.

I, am writing this report in the voice of the patient, as dictated to me by her. She was 32 weeks pregnant when she had the Dtap vaccine. The paperwork she was given regarding the vaccine just indicated Dtap vaccine, with no additional information regarding manufacturer, etc. She got very sick. Her symptoms did not improve over time. She felt exhausted and toxic. She had chills and hot flashes. Her baby died at 3 1/2 weeks later.    Tuesday 8/27/2019:   I went to my normal, scheduled prenatal visit for my 32 week check-up. I was healthy, feeling good and strong. My OB Dr suggested I have the Dtap vaccine. He told me about the side effects. I told him I didn?t want it, that I don?t like taking any medicines or drugs and was worried about the side effects on my baby. I said that I did not have it for my two other pregnancies and everything went well, no problem. He told me it was necessary, not only to protect my baby but to protect the other babies in the hospital when I gave birth. He said all the other moms were getting it. So I said okay. They gave me the vaccine.   Wednesday 8/28/19:  The next day, Wednesday, I woke up feeling really sick. I felt like I had a fever, but I didn?t, though I was having hot flashes. My arm was very sore. I couldn?t raise it. It hurt too much to sleep on. I felt exhausted. I had a sore throat and runny nose. The injection site on my arm was very painful, and felt numb. Couldn?t sleep on it. painful inside. The sickness never got better. It didn?t go away. I just took things day by day, thinking I would feel better soon.   Thursday 9/12/19:  I went in for my next prenatal appointment, my 34 week check-up. I told the doctor about my symptoms since they gave me the vaccine injection. He said it was normal and maybe I had a cold or flu. My body still felt very weird, tired, sick, weak, hot flashes, chills. It never went away. We scheduled a routine ultra sound for Sept 18th. At 20 weeks pregnant, the routine ultrasound had shown a possible low lying placenta.   Wednesday 9/18/19:  I had the ultrasound. It showed no problem. The placenta was in the right position and everything was normal. Everything was good. I heard the baby?s heartbeat. It was strong and good. No problems. But I was still feeling sick.   Sunday 9/22/19:  The baby wasn?t moving. I felt something was wrong. I went to the emergency that was close to my house. They did an ultrasound and found that there was no heartbeat. They said the baby was dead. They told me to go home and rest. I was almost 36 weeks. They said to call my doctor and schedule an appointment with him at Hospital for the next day.   Monday 9/23/19: I checked into Hospital. I saw Dr. He induced labor in the afternoon.          Tuesday:  I gave birth near 5 pm, a baby girl. She weighed 5 lbs 4 oz. No cord wrapped around her neck. No bleeding. Everything seemed very normal. She looked perfect, no abnormalities and a good size for 36 weeks. They put her on my chest. She stayed with me until I left the next day afternoon   They asked if I wanted an autopsy. They said it would be helpful to understand what happened and why the baby died. I agreed. The baby is now at Hospital undergoing the autopsy.  Wednesday 9/25/19: I checked out of hospital and went home.    Follow up postpartum appointment:  Mon Sept 30   My due date was:  Oct 22, 2019
LAB_DATA: Ultrasound 9/22/2019: determined the baby was dead

Her eyes rolled back in her head, and she went rigid in the chair. Both the family member and I rushed over to her. She was breathing the whole time, but her skin and lips were very pale. I was having a massive fever (grade unknown), and I was unable to respond to my fiance when she came into the room. I wanted to ask for tylenol, or a doctor, but even though I could hear her, I wasn't able to  say anything.  This feeling lasted for about 10 hours, which was almost 24 hours after the injection. On 9/5/19, I went back to work. I still felt miserable, but was able to move about. I felt like I had the flu however. From 9/5-9/9/9 I experienced memory issues. My fiance was showing me a photo with something red and something yellow on it, and I couldn't recall the names for the colors. The next morning she was ill and remained ill for 10 days with fever, occipital headache, vomiting, and dizziness. She had only a mild residual occipital HA when she received Rabies vaccine #2 July 26th.  Within about 36 hrs she was ill as before with headache, vertigo, palpitations, chest heaviness, and sweating. About 14 days post the earlier vaccinations and 3 days following Rabies #2, while seated, she passed out.  LOC lasted less than 5 minutes.  In the ER her HR was 248. She was Dx'd with SVT and treated with Adenosine. Since, the headache, chest pressure, and vertigo persisted. Cardiology cleared her and Rx with Diltiazem. Two days later with onset of chest pressure she suffered another acute LOC while seated lasting about 1 minute. Since then, she has had bouts of tachycardia, sweating, dizziness generally in the morning with arising.  She has had one bout of dyspnea, tachycardia, and chest pain which awoke her from sleep.  She no longer exercises as symptoms worsen. She awakes unrefreshed, feeling generally fatigued.  She feels anxious/tremulous most all the time and feels her concentration is impaired.  She was Dx'd with an adjustment disorder with anxiety for which she took hydroxyzine. She denies further vomiting, or history of dysuria, incontinence, constipation, diarrhea, postprandial syncope, flushing, neurogenic pain, or heat/cold intolerance.  Tentative Diagnosis: Dysautonomia.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: YEL-AVD (Yellow Fever associated viscerotropic disease) Patient states he was in his normal state of health of 23 Aug 2019 when he received 3 vaccines as part of his immunization requirements to include AVA #1, Typhoid and YF-Vax. He tolerated the vaccines well without any immediate adverse reactions. Within a few hours, he developed bilateral shoulder soreness that lasted about 3 days before resolving. He then did fine until Monday, 2 Sep when he awoke with some subtle left sided chest discomfort. Patient describes the chest discomfort began as a tugging/pulling sensation in his left chest. The pain progressed the following day and began to have associated dyspnea which was worse when lying down or when taking a deep breath. His symptoms continued to worsen and he sought care in the ED on 6 Sep 19. There he was noted to have a (+) D-dimer and CTPA done which did not reveal a PE but did show a small -moderate sized left-sided pleural effusion. In addition, he was noted to have an elevated creatinine and liver associated enzymes. He was hemodynamically stable, oxygenationg at 98% on RA and afebrile in the ED. He also endorses some chills and night sweats that developed during this time. He notes having daily headaches, as well. He further describes his chest pain as a constant dull pain 4 out of 10 in intensity but with acute excaerbations of a sharp pain (9 out of 10) with deep inspiration or lying down. Upon presentation today, he states his symptoms are all resolved other than rare episodes of substernal chest discomfort that occur at rest and resolve within a couple minutes, which he notes as distinctly different than his original pain and dyspnea.He denies any associated nausea, vomiting or diarrhea associated with his symptoms, but did endorse some LH associated with his dyspnea. He denies any recent travel and has never been outside the country. No high risk sexual encounters, etc. He denies a history of atopy/allergies. He received all routine childhood vaccines without any adverse reactions. Patient denies any other known adverse events following immunizations. Patient states he tolerates ingestion of eggs and gelatin and denies any known adverse reactions to latex, neomycin, polymixin, streptomycin, thimerosal, yeast, or formaldehyde.  Patient with clinical history and laboratory findings most consistent with Yellow fever vaccine associated viscerotropic disease (YEL-AVD). This is a rare Adverse Event Following Immunizations (AEFI) that was first described in 2001. It is reported to occur in 0.3 per 100,000 vaccines and is exclusively seen in patients receiving the YF-Vax for the first time, typically occurring within 1-8 days following vaccination but has been reported as far out as 18 days (patient's symptoms began at 10 days out from vaccination). YEL-AVD mimics naturally acquired yellow fever disease with the vaccine virus proliferating and disseminating throughout the patient's tissues. YEL-AVD is defined as acute multiple organ system dysfunction that occurs following vaccinization; it can range from relatively mild multi-system disease to severe multiple organ system failure and death. Initial symptoms of YEL-AVD are nonspecific including fever, headache, malaise, arthralgias, myalgias, nausea, vomiting and diarrhea; as it progresses it can include thrombocytopenia, elevation of transaminases, bilirubin and creatinine; less frequent manifestations include rhabdomyolysis and DIC. YEL-AVD is fatal in more than 60% of reported cases. Unfortunately, patient has no baseline CMPs/BMPs to compare his elevated LAEs and creatinine to. However, his LAEs are already trending down. The patient had multi-system organ involvement to include pleural effusion with dyspnea, elevated liver associated enzymes and acute kidney injury, elevated fibrin degradation products, as well as headaches. I suspect that patient will meet Brighton Collaboration case definition for viscerotrophic disease (level 2 of diagnostic certainty) with elevated Fibrin Degradation Products (elevated D-dimer) as well as a creatinine >/= 1.5 times his baseline value. (baseline value pending but suspect as patient convalesces his creatinine will decrease to less than 1 which will then meet this criteria). Interestingly, several cases of YEL-AVD have involved a history of autoimmune disease or diseases with potential autoimmune etiology. The literature includes 3 patients with SLE, 2 with Addison's disease, 1 with Crohn's disease, 1 with PMR and hypothyroidism, 1 with UC and 1 with myasthenia gravis. This patient has known mild eosinophilia with recent striae and weight gain, as well as some white and blue color changes to his digits. As suggested by his pulmonologist it is prudent to rule out Addison's disease as well as CVD given the literature and patient's history. No history of immunodeficiency, but given YEL-AVD can be associated with immunodeficiency will rule out common immunodeficiency with screening flow cytometry and quantitative Immunoglobulin levels; of note, patient denies a history of thymectomy or myasthenia gravis. Patient should not receive YF-Vax in the future but would not have an indication for such anyways. Patient may receive AVA and Typhoid as needed in the future but would consider dosing them in isolation from other vaccines. Serum sent to CDC for PRNT testing which may also provide some additional diagnostic certainty (already in discussions with Dr.).Patient currently feels his is back to his pre-immunization baseline.

The patient experienced Shingles. The reporter told that, the patient had other comorbidities like lupus and was on frequent courses of prednisone. The reporter did not think it was related to Nucala since was in presence of other factors, but did discontinue Nucala. It was unknown if the reporter considered the systemic lupus erythematosus and shingles to be related to prednisone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient wanted to get 2 vaccines on the same arm on 8/19.  He was due for 2nd Shingrix vaccine and also was due for an annual flu shot.  The two injection sites were separated by about 1 inch apart.  The patient came to the pharmacy complaining of sore arm that has been lasting for longer than 2 weeks.  Per patient, he cannot lift his right arm freely due to severe pain.  Morning seems to be worse than the evening.  We are suspecting that getting 2 vaccines on the same arm probably burdened his immunity.  The patient has never had unusual reactions to any vaccines.  The patient has been taking Tylenol for pain with a minimal pain relief.  The patient would seek medical help soon, but her wife is sick, so he will wait until her wife gets better first.

On the same day that I received the injections, in the afternoon, around 3 p.m., started to get very cold,  started shivering and my teeth were chattering.  I assumed it was from the air conditioning.  Later at dinner, around 5:30, in a different location, I two cups of hot tea to try and warm myself, with no luck.  After returning home I went to bed around 9 pm, still feeling extremely cold and shivering.  I slept poorly.  I felt very achy.  I awoke around 5 a.m. feeling very hot.  My husband took my temperature and it was 101.8 degrees.  He gave me two extra strength acetaminophen, which helped bring my fever down and relieved some of my aches.  However, all day that day (Sunday, Sept. 29, 2019) I was extremely tired and fatigued and the aches returned, but not the fever.  Today, Monday, Sept. 30, 2019, I have no fever or aches, but am extremely fatigued.
OTHER_MEDS: Atenolol, Lisinopril, Multaq, Xarelto, Cetirizine, Acetaminophin, Folate, multivitamin
ALLERGIES: morphine, erythromycin, Bactrim, cashew nuts, pistachios, chick peas

In the left submandibular area there is another approximately 4 mm level IB lymph node at the center of a 1.6 x 2.4 cm area of fat stranding. There is adjacent overlying asymmetric thickening of the left platysma. A few additional mildly prominent left cervical chain lymph nodes are also present, none of which are pathologically enlarged.  There are no pathologically enlarged right cervical lymph nodes or areas of surrounding fat stranding.  The nasopharynx and oropharynx are unremarkable. There is a cystic focus along the anterior right aspect of the epiglottis which measures 7 x 4 mm in greatest axial dimension likely representing a vallecular cyst as it encroaches into the right vallecula. The airway remains patent.  There is mild multifocal calcific atherosclerosis.  1.3 cm lipoma overlying the superior medial left trapezius.  Lung apices are clear. Status post left temporoparietal craniotomy with an area of encephalomalacia the left temporal lobe. No air-fluid levels in the paranasal sinuses or mastoid air cells. Moderate degenerative changes of the cervical spine. Small hypodense nodules in the thyroid.  IMPRESSION:  Areas of fat stranding centered around two lymph nodes deep to the left sternocleidomastoid mastoid and in the left submandibular region as described in the findings. Findings likely reflect an inflammatory or infectious etiology given adjacent enlargement of the musculature and fat stranding. However, malignancy, possibly lymphoma or metastatic disease, cannot be excluded and follow-up imaging is recommended after treatment to ensure resolution.
