Coronal and sagittal reformatted images were generated. INTRAVENOUS CONTRAST ADMINISTRATION (mL Omnipaque 350): 100 DOSE REPORT (Total DLP mGy*cm): 879  FINDINGS:  There is a region of fat stranding that measures approximately 2.9 x 1.5 cm centered about a left IIB lymph node which measures approximately 4 mm. In the left submandibular area there is another approximately 4 mm level IB lymph node at the center of a 1.6 x 2.4 cm area of fat stranding. There is adjacent overlying asymmetric thickening of the left platysma. A few additional mildly prominent left cervical chain lymph nodes are also present, none of which are pathologically enlarged.  There are no pathologically enlarged right cervical lymph nodes or areas of surrounding fat stranding.  The nasopharynx and oropharynx are unremarkable. There is a cystic focus along the anterior right aspect of the epiglottis which measures 7 x 4 mm in greatest axial dimension likely representing a vallecular cyst as it encroaches into the right vallecula. The airway remains patent.  There is mild multifocal calcific atherosclerosis.  1.3 cm lipoma overlying the superior medial left trapezius.  Lung apices are clear. Status post left temporoparietal craniotomy with an area of encephalomalacia the left temporal lobe. No air-fluid levels in the paranasal sinuses or mastoid air cells. Moderate degenerative changes of the cervical spine. Small hypodense nodules in the thyroid.  IMPRESSION:  Areas of fat stranding centered around two lymph nodes deep to the left sternocleidomastoid mastoid and in the left submandibular region as described in the findings. Findings likely reflect an inflammatory or infectious etiology given adjacent enlargement of the musculature and fat stranding. However, malignancy, possibly lymphoma or metastatic disease, cannot be excluded and follow-up imaging is recommended after treatment to ensure resolution. First of all, I just went in to get my shingles vaccine at the request of my doctor. The pharmacist asked if I've had my flu vaccine, which I hadn't so I said no. She recommended I get both vaccines at the same time. She said it's better for your immune system if you get them both at once. Within an hour, I had the "common symptoms" from the Shingrix literature...redness and swelling at the injection site, muscle pain, tiredness, headache, shivering, fever and upset stomach. On day three after the injection, I developed a shingles blister on the back of my neck. I called my doctor. She had me come in to verify it was shingles, which it was. Over the next 4 days I developed 8 more shingles blisters and a coldsore on my lip. My Dr. gave me a prescription for Valtrex but said not to take it unless I got significantly worse as it would make the vaccines less effective. At day 7, I started taking 1000 mg Lysine due to the coldsore. The other blisters dried up and scabbed over by day 9.  Today is day 17 and the blisters and coldsore are all gone except the one on the back of my neck. It still has a scab. I've since heard from several nurse friends that the pharmacist shouldn't have recommended I get bot the Shingrix and the Flu vaccines at the same time.

On 09/27/19 my son was complaining of his leg hurting, limping and wouldn't really walk much.  Saturday morning (09/28/19) his entire right thigh was swollen from his knee cap to his hip.  He took a nap that afternoon and woke up around 3PM, when he woke up his face was swollen, his hands/feet were swollen, his thigh was still swollen and there were hives on his leg, abdomen and face.  He was complaining about his hands/feet hurting.  He wouldn't walk or put shoes on due to pain.  I gave him 5mls of children's Benadryl and took him to the urgent care clinic.  By the time we got there the redness/swelling of his face had gone down but the hives, swollen thigh and hand/foot pain was still present.  He was evaluated by a physician assistant I believe.  We were instructed to do Benadryl/ranitidine and giving  a dosing schedule.  We were also given the option to try zyrtec during the day rather than Benadryl.  He has been taking the allergy medications since and the hives are gone, he is acting better and walking normal again but his thigh is still swollen at this time.

No information about the pt's pertinent medical history, concomitant medications and drug reactions or allergies was provided.  In or around October 2016, the pt was inoculated with a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (strength, route, frequency, lot/batch # and expiration date were not reported). Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt suffered shingles (herpes zoster). As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using it. The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution, and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence the pt suffered serious, progressive, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The reporter considered the event to be related to zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX). The reporter considered the event to be disabling.

Shortly after receiving Defendants' Zostavax vaccine, Plaintiff suffered shingles and retinal damage.; Shortly after receiving Defendants' Zostavax vaccine, Plaintiff suffered shingles and retinal damage.; Information has been received from a lawyer and the patient (pt) regarding a case in litigation involving a female patient (pt) of unknown age. No information about the pt's pertinent medical history, concomitant medications and drug reactions or allergies was provided.     In or around May 2012, the pt was inoculated with a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (strength, route, frequency, lot/batch # and expiration date were not reported). Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt suffered shingles (herpes zoster) and retinal damage (retinal injury). As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using it. The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution, and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury.   The reporter considered the events to be related to zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX).  The reporter considered the events to be disabling.  Upon internal review, retinal injury was determined to be a medically significant event.

Patient came to the clinic today, with his father, to get a Td.  His father wanted him to get a Td because he poked himself with a tack. Patient was administered the Td vaccination in the left deltoid muscle, he reported he was feeling fine after vaccine and was talkative. Father and son then left clinic room. Approximately 10-15 minutes later the father came to desk and reported that his son just had a seizure.  RN was at the desk when father reported incident and went into the Immunization room and told RN, emergency supplies and oxygen canister were gathered by both RNs and returned to waiting room.  By that time father had brought son (patient) back into the waiting room from parking lot and patient was sitting in a chair.  RN asked how he was feeling and he stated ?fine? there was no visible signs of injury.  RN suggested he lay down in the clinic room and he verbalized okay and that he also could walk there on his own.  Patient was steady when he walked to the clinic and lay down on the exam table, RN elevated his legs.  A third RN was in the clinic room with oxygen canister and gave him 8L oxygen via mask.  Throughout patient was alert and talking to RNs.  BP was 102/62, pulse 60.  Father explained to RNs that they walked to the car and as son was getting into the car he had a ?seizure.?  911 was called and arrived within approximately 10 minutes, patient talked with EMS crewmember for approximately 10 minutes and then walked to gurney and got on.  Patient then was transported to the hospital for further evaluation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: arm soreness; swelling at injection site; white dot at injection site; can't lift arm; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced pain in arm, injection site swelling, injection site hypopigmentation and injected limb mobility decreased. Rechallenge with Shingrix was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in arm, injection site swelling, injection site hypopigmentation and injected limb mobility decreased were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain in arm, injection site swelling, injection site hypopigmentation and injected limb mobility decreased to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient demographic details were not reported. 5 weeks ago from the date of reporting, the patient received 2nd dose of Shingrix. The patient experienced soreness in arm, on which the inajection has been received, since from the day of vaccination. At the time of reporting, the events were unresolved, and the patient stated that she can not lift her arm above shoulder. The patient did not consent to follow up. This case was 1 of 3 linked cases.

Stroke; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of stroke in a 80-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Shingix (1st dose received on 20th April 2019).   On 20th July 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 23rd August 2019, 34 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced stroke (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the stroke was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the stroke to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information was reported as follows: The patient wanted to know, could a 3rd dose of Shingrix would safe on blood thinner.

Shingles / mild outbreak; Small area about the size of a dime with one tiny blister the size of a straight pin head; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of shingles in a patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (had chronic outbreaks for over 20 years).   On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, less than 2 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced shingles and blister. On an unknown date, the outcome of the shingles and blister were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the shingles and blister to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information was reported as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. Two months before the time of reporting, the patient received a dose of Shingrix. The patient was pretty confident this was a mild outbreak, there was just one small area about the size of a dime with one tiny blister the size of a straight pin head. The patient wanted to know, had broke out with Shingles between a Shingrix Vaccination. The patient was not comfortable to giving out the information online. The GSK pharmacist provided the information that, during clinical trials, evaluation of the efficacy of Shingrix started 1 month after the 2nd dose. Therefore, the efficacy of the vaccine was unknown if the second dose was not received. Also, the GSK clinical trials (ZOE50 and ZOE70) excluded patients who had a history of previous herpes zoster (shingles). The patient guessed that, the patient would contact the physician.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Shingles (had chronic outbreaks for over 20 years)

Hepatitis; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of hepatitis in a patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included non-small cell lung cancer.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced hepatitis (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the hepatitis was unknown.   The reporter considered the hepatitis to be related to Flu vaccine.  This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of hepatitis in a patient of unspecified age and gender who was vaccinated with unspecified influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.  The patient was a part of single-center retrospective analysis that was conducted for patients with advanced non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC) who received prolonged cell death 1 (PD-1) or prolonged cell death ligand 1 (PD-L1) inhibitor monotherapy between March 2015 and December 2018 to interrogate if influenza vaccination in patients with NSCLC receiving immune checkpoint inhibitors (ICPI) therapy had an increased incidence of immune-related adverse events (irAEs) compared to non-vaccinated patients. Comparisons of adverse event incidence between flu vaccinated and control patients were tested using chi-square statistics. The patient had history of non-small cell lung carcinoma (NSCLC). No information on patient's family history was provided.   On an unspecified date, between March 2015 and December 2018, the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosages unknown, batch number not provided). [In this study, influenza immunization records from both institutional and state-wide registries were obtained from 2014 -2019. 19 received quadrivalent influenza vaccine, 13 received trivalent influenza vaccine and 1 was undetermined]. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient also received prolonged cell death 1 (PD-1) or prolonged cell death ligand 1 (PD-L1) inhibitor monotherapy (ICPI). [In this study, 33 were vaccinated during ICPI therapy].   On an unspecified date, an unknown period after vaccination, the patient had hepatitis. It was considered as irAE.  [In this study, 22 vaccinated patients had an irAE versus 53 patients who were not vaccinated during ICPI therapy. 8 vaccinated patients had an irAE leading to discontinuation of therapy].  Treatment was unknown.  The outcome of the event was not reported.  The authors commented and concluded "Our study suggests that irAEs are not significantly increased with vaccination for influenza during ICPI therapy. However, there is a slight trend toward increased incidence of irAE warranting ICPI discontinuation for which further investigation is needed. Limitations of this study include a small sample size and inability to grade irAE retrospectively."

within 2 hours of shot, my right arm hurt (possibly left- Not sure) and then immediately within an hour I started to feel like my head was shooting small bursts of pain. It felt similar to really bad flu. I asked nurse if I should have any questions and she said "your arm will hurt". I knew the arm pain was due to shot, I did not know where the other symptoms came from or why. From that day forward, my teeth became extremely sensitive to touch and eating food became a painful event. I did not call the doctor, because I had no idea this was related. On June 29th I went to urgent care as my tongue swelled up so bad I couldn't open my mouth except to swallow small amounts of food and water. The urgent care said to go to ER as this could be life threatening. ER said it was an infection of the salivary gland involving the lymph nodes. I was given a prescription for Keflex(?) and told to follow up with the doctor. I spent the next 10 days sick and in pain. I finally returned to work on July 8th. On August 10th I returned to Urgent Care and said I felt horrible. Everything from my neck up hurt and it kept moving around. The doctor said he had never seen this before and didn't know what to do. He gave me a prednisone shot and sent me home.   I finally made an appointment with my primary for August 30th. She referred me to an infectious disease specialist and to a neurologist. I am still waiting until November 27th to see the neurologist. I saw Dr on Tuesday, September 10th. I explained the symptoms again and what I had been through. He diagnosed me with Trigeminal Neuralgia Zoster. He also gave me a prescription for Valtrex. I took if for two weeks and my face swelled up under both lower right and left chins. He referred me to a pain management specialist and told me to stop taking the Valtrex.   I cannot seem to get into see anybody without waiting months and in the mean time I am in tremendous, actually horrific pain and I cannot take pain meds.  My body rejects them. I understand that Trigeminal Neuralgia has no cure. I got this because of the shingles shot, and absolutely no one listened to me when I mentioned when my personal hell started. But apparently, it is true... some people have extremely adverse reations to vaccines, and I am one of them. I feel as it I am on my own and basically with no help or resources. How dare they put out a product with no warning or testing.
ALLERGIES: no tolerance for pain meds, codeine, and most drugs

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came into the pharmacy with his father to get the meningitis vaccine as requested by his high school and the HPV vaccine as requested by his mother who is a nurse. When patient stood up after the vaccinations he said he felt dizzy so he sat back down.  A pharmacy technician was called to help lay the patient on the floor .  The RPH talked with the patient as the technician held his feet up off the ground.  His pulse and blood pressures were taken results as follows, 5:27 101/51 & 43,  5:28 108/47 & 44, & 5:31 97/52 & 52. after about 10 minutes the patient said he felt better and sat upright in the chair.  His father went to get him a snack and a drink.  When the father returned the patient felt better still they walked around/stayed in the store before going home.  An hour later the patient's mother came to the pharmacy to get an administration record to give to the school as proof of getting the Menactra and to tell us that the patient was feeling fine.  She also wanted to get the return dates for the remaining Gardisil 9 shots.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shortly after receiving Defendants' Zostavax vaccine, Plaintiff suffered chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy.; Information has been received from a lawyer and the patient (pt) regarding a case in litigation involving a male patient (pt) of unknown age. No information about the pt's pertinent medical history, concomitant medications and drug reactions or allergies was provided. In or around 2015, the pt was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (strength, route, frequency, lot/batch # and expiration date were not reported).  On an unknown date, reported as "shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX)", the pt suffered chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy.  As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), pt symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using it. Pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution, and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The reporter considered the event to be related to zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX). Chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy as disabling event, due to the pt's permanent and incurable injuries. Upon internal review, chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy was determined to be a medically significant event.

Fetal exposure during pregnancy; Preterm birth; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 18-Sep-2019, concerning a male, neonate subject, whose mother was 25-year-old, pregnant female subject of body weight 106 lbs, height 62 inches and body mass index 19.4, enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy.  The mother's medical history included urinary tract infection. Concomitant medications included Vitafol One (ascorbic acid, betacarotene, colecalciferol, cupric oxide, cyanocobalamin, folic acid, magnesium oxide, nicotinamide, omega-3 fatty acids, polysaccharide-iron complex, potassium iodide, pyridoxine hydrochloride, riboflavin, thiamine mononitrate, tocopheryl acetate, zinc oxide) for healthy pregnancy and Macrobid (clarithromycin) for urinary tract infection.   The subject's mother had no previous pregnancies. The mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. Also, the subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 18-Aug-2018, and the expected delivery date was 25-May-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 06-Oct-2018, the subject's mother was administered Flucelvax QIVc [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 252232, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, expiration date and anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.  On, at gestational age of 36.9 week, the mother delivered live birth, male neonate [explicitly coded as �Premature baby'] through vaginal method. The neonate's birth weight was 2765 grams, head circumference was 31 cm and body length was 50 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 9 (one minute), 9 (five minutes) and 9 (ten minutes). There was no pregnancy complication noted and no major congenital malformation identified at birth.   At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the event �Birth premature' was not reported.  This case is linked to 201902925 (corresponding mother case).  Company comment: Reportedly, a male neonate subject was delivered as premature baby after foetal exposure during pregnancy, after maternal receipt of Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD at gestation age of 7 weeks. Chronology is plausible. The mother's concomitant treatment with clarithromycin confounds causality. However, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.; Reporter's Comments: Reportedly, a male neonate subject was delivered as premature baby after foetal exposure during pregnancy, after maternal receipt of Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD at gestation age of 7 weeks. Chronology is plausible. The mother's concomitant treatment with clarithromycin confounds causality. However, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.

Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Preterm birth; This is a serious observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 18-Sep-2019, concerning a male subject which mother was enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy.  The subject's mother had seven previous pregnancies, five previous full-term live birth, one previous preterm live birth and one previous spontaneous abortion. The subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The subject's mother had no history of offspring with MCM. The subject's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's mother's last menstrual period (LMP) was on 25-Jun-2018. Estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected EDD was reported as 01-Apr-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The pregnancy status of the was collected, and no MCMs were noted.   The subject's mother historical condition included bacterial vaginitis (from 07-Aug-2018 to 17-Aug-2018) and historical drug included Metrogel (metronidazole) for bacterial vaginitis. Concomitant medications included prenatal vitamins (minerals not specified (nos), vitamins nos) for pregnancy.   On 01-Aug-2018, the subject's mother underwent spinal muscular atrophy screen and cystic fibrosis mutation analysis and no MCMs were noted.   On 07-Aug-2018, 13-Aug-2018 and 27-Aug-2018, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound and no MCMs were noted.  On 15-Oct-2018, at approximately 16 weeks of gestation, the mother was administered Flucelvax QIV [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, cell cultured derived, batch number: 252664, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, anatomical location and expiry date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. On the same day, the mother underwent ultrasound and Quad Screen and no MCMs were noted.  On 12-Dec-2018, the subject's mother developed anaemia and was treated with ferrous sulfate one tablet, twice daily, orally. I want to report that I had a serious adverse event produced by the Shingrix vaccine. I have never had an allergic response to a vaccine. After the injection on Monday August 26th, I felt little discompfort at the site of injection but dry cough appeared after 3-days. Monocytes were 10.5% with 1.08*10^9. All other cell types and levels were within normal range. They treated me with paracetamol IV and polaramine im. I also visited an ENT due to the ear blockade.  She told me it will take sometime to clear up (ears were ok but my hearing was decreased).Today, October 2nd, I am still with ear drum blockade but no headache or pain. FYI I had chicken pox when I was a child and was vaccinated with Zostavax approximately 3 years ago.

Starting from about  9:30 or 10:30 pm on Tues night,  I had about 5 bouts of liquid stools and cramping over an hr or so.   I went to bed and woke up and threw up at about 1:00pm.   I was awake until at least 4 feeling very thirsty, a bit dizzy, light headed and in general sick.  I was extremely thirsty and got up on the hour and drank 8 to 10 oz of water until about 4 am or so.    I slept then for a while and woke up again around 7 am or so, by then my stomach and cramps were ok but then I had a little ringing in the left hear and had a low grade head ache.    I called the Dr. around the time the office opened and spoke with the nurse and ate a breakfast cookie.    We decided that I was much better than during the night but that I should get gatorade or coconut milk to replace electrolytes.  Over the next couple of hours I drank 2 cans of coconut milk ,stayed in bed feeling like I had the flu and slept pretty much all day until I got up and had rice when my husband had dinner.    The next day, I felt like I had a mild flu and was up and out of bed all day.  I took my temperature with a mercury oral themometer just once and it read 101.2 at about 7 am.   Usually I would be 98 or a little below.   The following day I felt a bit better yet.     It is now a week out on Wed.   Except for my stomach and intestines getting back to normal, I feel fine.  Except, I went out to dinner last night, had a substantial meal and had one liquid stool and one throwing up episode.  Because , I feel like I should be fine, I saw my Dr. today who ran some blood work to make sure that nothing else is brewing along with this "reaction."  Temperature at the Dr. office was 98. The first shot, I had mild flu like symptoms for a couple of days but this was far worse.    My arm did hurt and had a little bump at the site but was not red over any of the three days.

HISTORY: I take replacement hormones and a thyroid supplement
ALLERGIES: seasonal and possible digestive allergy to molds and dusts and possibly cockroaches or pets.  No recent testing but historically I have had some allergies.  None rated as  severe.

The patient stated that the arm does not itch. The patient also reports that she is not experiencing any breathing problems, and no other systemic reactions reported. The patient showed me her arm, and I observed the arm to be very bright red and swollen from the top of the arm up near the shoulder down to the elbow. It was a fairly large area affected on the outside of the right arm. Due to the severity of the reaction, I advised the patient to seek medical care. Recommended the patient see a physician to rule out reactions suchas cellulitis/infection versus an allergic reaction. The reaction is severe enough that it should not be treated OTC. The patient was going into her doctor office about this today per my recommendation to follow up with physician about this. I looked up the patient's recent immunization history in our computer: on 9/30/2019, this pharmacy gave the patient 3 immunizations ... Fluzone Quad and Pneumovax 23 were administered in the right arm, and Shingrix was administered in the left arm. The patient did not experience any reactions in the left arm where the Shingrix was administered. This IMZ reaction in the right arm would be from either the Fluzone Quad and/or the Pneumovax 23. The relatedness between the event and meningococcal acyw conj vaccine (crm197) (MENVEO) was suspected. The relatedness between the event and other suspect therapies was not provided. One of the hospital employees received a dose of Fluarix and caller states that the vaccine was not injected into the deltoid muscle. 5 months old female patient who received DTaP-IPV diluent separately and did not receive ACT-HIB powder portion of pentacel, no AE; Initial information received on 12-Sep-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a nurse.  This case is linked to cases 2019SA257163 and 2019SA261801 (same reporter).   This case involves a 5 months old female patient who received DTaP-IPV diluent separately and did not receive ACT-HIB powder portion of vaccine DIPHTHERIA/TETANUS/5 HYBRID AC PERTUSSIS/IPV(MRC5)/HIB(PRP/T) VACCINE [Pentacel] (lot: UJ060AA, expiry vdate: 04-Oct-2020, the outer carton is lot: UJ060AAA, expiry date: 04-Oct-2020) via unknown route in the left thigh, on 27-Aug-2019.  The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  Concomitant vaccinations included ROTAVIRUS VACCINE (ROTAVIRUS VACCINE) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE CONJ 13V (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13). At 31 weeks and 1 day, the patient was born via cesarean delivery. The patient was diagnosed with birth weight low, premature birth and live birth. On an unknown date, the outcome of the cardiovascular insufficiency, birth weight low, premature birth, live birth, monoamniotic twin pregnancy and maternal exposure during pregnancy were unknown. Pt was given multiple vaccines as part of her WCC; she began to have reaction sxs this morning 9/25/19 , which started as what FOC describes as a "bug bite," but then progressed to include a large area of spreadig redness, significant swelling, and itching. Pt does not c/o pain, and has not had fevers or discharge from the area, though she has seemed a bit tired. No n/v, anorexia, malaise, paresthesia, or weakness of the leg. # Vaccines adverse reaction  (T50.Z95A): Consistent with a localized (though moderately/severe) reaction; not concerning for infection or anaphylaxis. Start with topical steroids; recommended close f/u friday which MOC will call to schedule. May consider oral steroids if not improving dt the degree of swelling. Will report to VAERS, close monitoring discussed. Plan printed and provided to patient: PRESCRIBE: triamcinolone 0.1% topical cream, Apply to affected area 2 times a day, # 100, RF: 0. (Transmitted by PA-C) The injection given in the left thigh was Kinrix, which includes DTap and Polio- these are both vaccines that she's had 3 ad 4 times prior respectively, so I am suspecting this is a localized reaction to carrier substances present in the specific Kinrix formulation of the vaccine, rather than a reaction to the specific polio or dtap components. She is finished with both of these series, and won't require another Dtap- (though she will eventually need a Tdap). Recommend a topical steroid cream as prescribed, with close monitoring for worsening problems, such as swelling of lips, tongue, or face, trouble breathing, coughing, or wheezing- which would warrant urgent follow up or ER visit. Otherwise we will report this reaction to the manufacturer and agency.
OTHER_MEDS: triamcinolone 0.1% topical cream, Apply to affected area 2 times a day

Additional case details were reported as follows: The patient had an unknown manufacturers flu vaccine in her left arm and on Wednesday the day before reporting she had her second dose of Shingrix in her right arm.  The patient stated she immediately felt bad after receiving the Shingrix vaccine.  On Thursday, before day of reporting, after 2 days of vaccination the patient covered in hives at the site and from head to toe.  She could not move her arm. She noted the rash was a red pin prick appearance on Friday, before day of reporting.  On Sunday, before day of reporting, the patient went to urgent care and was given methylprednisone prescription. Her tongue was no longer heave, the pin prick rash was the same and still all over her body, head to toe.  The patient was still tired but contributed that to taking round the clock Benadryl as prescribed from Urgent care. She was on a total of 5 days of methylprednisone. muscle aches; nerve pain; sore arm/ left arm very tender; could not sleep; feeling stiff and sore all over; fatigue; sore all over; nausea; joint pain; flu; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of muscle pain in a 77-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included fluconazole (Fluzone (Fluconazole)) for product used for unknown indication.   The patient's past medical history included head and neck cancer and stroke. Concurrent medical conditions included blindness, automobile accident (- soft tissue injuries, broken sernum, Nov 2018, still recovering from injuries), thyroid disorder, vestibular disorder (caused by head and neck cancer treatment), gastroesophageal reflux disease, soft tissue injury (still recovering from injuries) and fractured sternum (still recovering from injuries). Concomitant products included omeprazole, paracetamol (Tylenol), thyroid hormones (Thyroid Hormone) and medication unknown (Blood Pressure Medication).   On 18th September 2019 16:30, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 18th September 2019, the patient started Fluzone (Fluconazole) at an unknown dose and frequency. In September 2019, 9 hrs 30 min after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced muscle pain, nerve pain, pain in arm, insomnia, stiffness, fatigue, general body pain, nausea, joint pain and influenza. On an unknown date, the outcome of the muscle pain, nerve pain, pain in arm, nausea, joint pain and influenza were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the insomnia, stiffness, fatigue and general body pain were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the muscle pain, nerve pain, pain in arm, insomnia, stiffness, fatigue, general body pain, nausea, joint pain and influenza to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: On 18th September 2019, The reporter stated that the patient got the first dose of Shingrix, as well as Fluzone, , around 4:30 PM. Prior to getting the vaccines the patient had physical therapy for previous car crash injuries and also did some shopping. The patient went to bed around 8:30 PM exhausted from a busy day. On 19th September 2019, at 2 am around, the patient woke up with severe muscle pains, her left arm very tender, and the sheet moving against her body causing nerve pain. The patient felt like she did right after her car accident. The patient got up feeling stiff and sore all over and took some Tylenol.  The patient could not sleep the rest of the night. That morning she had two previously scheduled appointments with her physician and ophthalmologist. The patient got home from her appointments around 2 PM and was so fatigued she fell asleep as soon as she got home. The patient woke up about 4 PM and drank a lot of water. The patient spent the rest of the day treating herself like she had the flu. The symptoms resolved after about 24 hours. During this period she had these symptoms she had a little bit of nausea, which was solved by eating food. The patient thinks she was hungry and also had flashes of joint pain like her knees were getting electric shots. The patient noted that she was often stiff and sore after physical therapy, so she was not sure how much of the symptoms were due to the vaccine versus her previous activities. She does not think any of it was caused by Fluzone. She has never had problems with flu vaccines in the past.
OTHER_MEDS: Omeprazole; Tylenol; THYROID HORMONE; BLOOD PRESSURE MEDICATION; Fluconazole
CUR_ILL: Automobile accident (- soft tissue injuries, broken sernum, Nov 2018, still recovering from injuries); Blindness; Fractured sternum (still recovering from injuries); Gastroesophageal reflux disease; Soft tissue injury (still recovering from injuries); Thyroid disorder; Vestibular disorder (caused by head and neck cancer treatment)
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Head and neck cancer; Stroke

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day following the vaccination he developed yellow blotches on both medial lower legs which to him looked like hives.  The next day he developed generalized pruritus and clusters of water blisters in streaks on arms and legs and beneath his nose. The following day it dawned on him that these tiny blisters were identical to what he had seen in the past on his genitalia during outbreaks of herpes.  So he began the same regimen of treatment which had been effective for his herpes outbreaks.  Within eight hours of the first dose of 2 grams of valacyclovir the pruritus had resolved.  Twelve hours later he took the second dose and soon thereafter the water blisters began crusting over.  Just to be sure he repeated the course the following day.  The rash and all of his symptoms quickly resolved and he has remained asymptomatic since.  He first reported this to me today when he was in my office for an unrelated matter.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D 1000 IU daily Vitamin B 12 1000 mcg IM weekly

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 4 OCT 2019, PT discovered that she has been in positive on urine pregnancy test after she received the smallpox on 24 SEP 2019.
Large local reaction started about 6 hours after the vaccines were administered.  Urticaria developed two days later.  Patient was seen in the Emergency Department for this reaction.
LAB_DATA: CBC with leukocytosis (WBC > 16,000).  Other labs were unremarkable.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: First sign that appeared was soreness in the arm. This started approximately 2 hours after vaccination. By hour 4 after vaccination, the arm was so stiff that it was hard to move. At hour 6, the injection site was inspected for the first time. There was a bright red welt with an approximate 1 inch diameter; the welt was giving off a large amount of heat. The following morning, the welt had grown to approximately 2.5 inches in diameter. The arm was still extremely sore and difficult to move without pain. The soreness and pain went down as time went on. Today, five days after the vaccine, the welt is finally gone, but there is still residual muscle soreness.
OTHER_MEDS: Omeprazole 20mg Tablet, Loratidine 10mg Tablet, Vitamin D3 2000U Capsule

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Swelling at site of injection. Redness, Skin is hard. Skin is hot. Fever, nausea and pain at site of injection. These symptoms occurred within 24 hours and today is day three after the injections. Symptoms remain. I did contact the doctor on the day after injections to let him know about the reactions. He said next year they will give them in separate sites as these were given in the same site. And perhaps on different days.
OTHER_MEDS: Estrodial,  Medroxyprogersterone, Centrum multiple vitamin, calcium, magnesium.
CUR_ILL: GI upset. Vomiting/ diarrhea. Two weeks prior to vaccinations.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Started with body aches, fever, lethargy, exhaustion developed cough lasted for 5 days.  Cough still lingers now on day 6.  Haven?t felt this bad in a very long time.  Felt it important to report this.  2nd dose.  No real reaction after first except a little soreness. Crazy. Why this reaction?

Patient presented to clinic with cellulitis at vaccination site. The site at which the patient was immunized is lower than the recommended distance from the acromion process. Approximate 10cm lesion at time of appointment. Patient denied shortness of breath or difficulty breathing, no generalized rashes present, negative for axial lymphadenopathy. Lesion was erythemic and hot to touch, tender to palpation. Physician Assistant prescribed Keflex for treatment. Patient advised to follow up with the clinic if his symptoms do not improve.
Muscle soreness, chills, fever, stiffness,  insomnia. Took Tylenol. Symptoms abated after 24 hours.
Patient reports to muscle discomfort and limited movement 3 weeks after vaccine

On this same date, during the vaccine administration two vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) syringes out of a carton of ten broke.   The first syringe broke at the finger flanges while using it, but there was no initial crack on the syringe. The finger flanges broke up after the administration of the shot (product quality issue). The second syringe broke at the luer lock while the medical assistant was sliding the safety tip off of the needle. It was stated that it broke after administration while attempting to put the safety mechanism on after administration. No patient was involved.   The outcome of product quality issue, accidental exposure to product, needle issue and syringe issue was unknown.     The reporter did not provide a causal relationship between the events and the Pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23).

Anaphylaxis; a missed contraindication for Tdap; Anaphylaxis; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of anaphylaxis in a patient who received Hepatitis A vaccine for prophylaxis.  Co-suspect products included DTPa (Reduced antigen) (Tdap Vaccine) for prophylaxis, Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis, Men ACWY-CRM NVS (Meningococcal ACWY Vaccine (potential Menveo)) for prophylaxis, DTPa (Reduced antigen) (Tdap Vaccine) for prophylaxis, ADENOVIRUS VACCINE for prophylaxis and POLIOMYELITIS VACCINE (IPV VACCINE) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Hepatitis A vaccine at an unknown dose, Tdap Vaccine at an unknown dose, Flu vaccine at an unknown dose, Meningococcal ACWY Vaccine (potential Menveo) at an unknown dose, Tdap Vaccine at an unknown dose, ADENOVIRUS VACCINE at an unknown dose and IPV VACCINE at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Hepatitis A vaccine and Tdap Vaccine and not applicable after receiving Flu vaccine, Meningococcal ACWY Vaccine (potential Menveo) and Tdap Vaccine, the patient experienced anaphylaxis (serious criteria GSK medically significant), anaphylaxis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and contraindicated drug administered. On an unknown date, the outcome of the anaphylaxis, anaphylaxis and contraindicated drug administered were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the anaphylaxis to be related to Hepatitis A vaccine and Tdap Vaccine. The reporter considered the anaphylaxis to be possibly related to Flu vaccine, Meningococcal ACWY Vaccine (potential Menveo) and Tdap Vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of anaphylaxis in a patient of unspecified age and gender who was vaccinated with unspecified inactivated poliovirus (IPV), unspecified inactivated influenza (IIV), unspecified meningococcal conjugate (MCV4) and unspecified tetanus, diphtheria & acellular pertussis vaccine (Tdap) vaccines and unspecified adenovirus (manufacturer unknown for all vaccines) for prophylaxis.  The patient was the part of the observational study that aimed to investigate adverse event (AE) reports following the adenovirus vaccine submitted to the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS). They searched the VAERS database for reports among persons who received adenovirus vaccine during 1st October 2011 through 31st July 2018 including participants in a military observational study. [In this study, they identified those reports filled from 24th October 2011 to 5th October 2012, an FDA-mandated, post marketing military observational study was conducted using the database. This study compared 100,000 recruits exposed to the adenovirus vaccine with a historical unexposed cohort and identified statistical signals for psoriasis, anaphylaxis and other hypersensitivity reactions as emergent AEs possibly related to vaccination. During the study period, VAERS received a total of 100 reports following adenovirus vaccine; among all reports, the earliest vaccination date with the adenovirus vaccine the study identified was November 9, 2011]. The patient was from the military observational study. The patient had a past history of anaphylaxis following Tdap and hepatitis A vaccines (i.e., a missed contraindication for Tdap). No information on patient's family history or concomitant condition was provided. On unspecified date, the patient had received unspecified inactivated poliovirus (IPV), unspecified inactivated influenza (IIV), unspecified meningococcal conjugate (MCV4) and unspecified tetanus, diphtheria & acellular pertussis vaccine (Tdap) vaccines and unspecified adenovirus (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided for all). The age of vaccination was not provided.  On an unspecified date between 1st October 2011 through 31st July 2018, unknown period after vaccination, the patient presented to the hospital with the episode of anaphylaxis. [In this study, The main diagnosis for each report was categorized into a MedDRA System Organ Class (SOC) grouping. Reports suggestive of anaphylaxis or GBS were further classified using the Brighton Collaboration criteria or a physician's diagnosis. Reports are classified as serious based on the Code of Regulations if one of the following is reported: death, life-threatening illness, hospitalization or prolongation of hospitalization, permanent disability, or congenital anomaly]. This case has been considered as serious due to the hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. [In this study, each of the patients was treated with epinephrine, antihistamine and corticosteroid therapy]. The outcome of event was not reported.  The author commented, "We identified eight reports of anaphylaxis following adenovirus vaccine classified as serious and on review of medical records all were identified as participants in the military observational study. In two patients the anaphylaxis was considered as possibly related to vaccines. In addition, 95 percent of the adenovirus vaccine reports documented co-administration of other vaccines and 50 percent reported co-administration of penicillin G (or other antibiotic if allergic to penicillin) according to standard protocol in this military population. The investigators of the earlier military observational study also commented that concurrent vaccine exposures in the recruit population was an important limiting factor for attributing the statistical signaling outcomes including psoriasis, anaphylaxis and other hypersensitivity reactions as possibly related to the vaccine". The author concluded "The reporting rate for serious AEs was higher than with other vaccines administered in the comparison military recruit population (39 percent vs 18 percent however, we identified no unexpected or concerning pattern of adenovirus vaccine AEs. Co-administration of vaccines and IM Pen G was commonly reported in this military population. These exposures may have contributed to the GBS and anaphylaxis outcomes observed with the adenovirus vaccine. Future adenovirus vaccine safety studies in a population without these co-administrations would be helpful in clarifying the vaccine's safety profile". This is 1 of the 19 valid cases reported in this literature article.

Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Preterm birth; Low birth weight; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 27-Sep-2019, concerning a male, neonate subject, whose mother was 25-year-old, pregnant female subject of body weight 193 lbs, height 66 inches and body mass index 31.1, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The mother's historical medical condition included bacterial vaginosis. The mother's current medical conditions included bacterial vaginosis, nausea, vomiting, Herpes simplex, hypertension, trichomoniasis, anemia, elevated alpha-fetoprotein and uterine dehiscence. The mother's historical medications included Metrogel (metronidazole). The mother's concomitant medications included: Metrogel (metronidazole) for bacterial vaginosis, Flagyl (metronidazole) for trichomoniasis, Procardia (nifedipine) for hypertension, Venofer (saccharated iron oxide) for anaemia and Prenatal vitamins (minerals NOS, vitamins NOS) for pregnancy.   The subject's mother had six previous pregnancies. Five pregnancies ended with full term live birth and one ended with pre-term live birth. The mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. Also, the subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations. The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 29-Jun-2018. Estimated delivery date and corrected estimated delivery date were 05-Apr-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 03-Oct-2018, the subject's mother was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (Flucelvax QIVc) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, batch number: 252664, route of administration, expiration date and anatomical location: not reported] [explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy'] for influenza immunisation.  At gestational age of 32.9 week, the mother delivered live birth, male neonate [explicitly coded as �Birth premature'] through Caesarean method. The neonate's birth weight was 2140 grams [explicitly coded as �Low birth weight baby'], head circumference and body length were not provided. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). There were pregnancy complications noted which included hypertension, uterine dehiscence and preterm labor. There was no major congenital malformation identified at birth.   At the time of initial reporting, the outcomes of the events were not reported.  This case is linked to 201904853 (corresponding mother case).  Company Comment: Reportedly, the male neonate subject was delivered as premature and low birth weight baby after foetal exposure during pregnancy with the suspect product Flucelvax QIVc. Chronology is plausible. Mother's medical history of herpes simplex, hypertension, trichomoniasis and anaemia may have contributed to development of the events. Causality was confounded by use of multiple concomitant drugs. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company conventions. Body aches; Significant Malaise; Stay in bed for 48 hours; This case was reported by a physician via sales rep and described the occurrence of general body pain in a 56-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   In November 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. In November 2018, immediately after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced general body pain, malaise and bedridden. On an unknown date, the outcome of the general body pain, malaise and bedridden were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the general body pain, malaise and bedridden to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient was the reporter's husband. Soon after receiving dose of Shingrix, the patient experienced significant malaise and body aches causing him to have to stay in bed for 48 hours. The reporter stated that, all symptoms were resolved after 48 hours. The sales representative indicated that, the reporter provided this information to her during a Congress she was attending and was unable to provide any additional details. For tolerance to the 2nd dose of Shingrix, refer case US2019AMR175952. This was 1 of the 4 cases, reported by the same reporter.

A 55-year-old male patient received pneumococcal 13- valent conjugate vaccine (diphtheria crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13), intramuscular in the left deltoid on 16Jul2019 08:30 at 0.5 ml, single for immunization. Medical history included ongoing hypertension, substance abuse, arthralgia, hyperlipidemia and tobacco use. Concomitant medication included atorvastatin calcium (LIPITOR) for hyperlipidaemia, losartan potassium (COZAAR) for hypertension and ranitidine hydrochloride (ZANTAC); all ongoing. Concomitant vaccines includes hepatitis a vaccine (HEPATITIS A; lot number: N39BM, expiry date: 31Jan2022) intramuscular in the right deltoid, diphtheria vaccine toxoid, pertussis vaccine acellular, tetanus vaccine toxoid (TDAP; lot number: X5R7Y, expiry date: 14Nov2020) intramuscular in the left deltoid and hepatitis b vaccine (lot number: L9539, expiry date: 07Dec2021) intramuscular in the right deltoid; all administered on 16Jul2019 for immunization. On 16Jul2019, the patient received the vaccine exposed to temperature excursion on unspecified date. The vaccine was labeled with 'do not use' however was still given to the patient. Information on the batch number has been requested.  Follow-up (23Aug2019): This follow-up is being submitted to notify that the batch number is not available despite the followup attempts made. Follow-up attempts have been completed and no further information is expected.  Follow-up (05Sep2019): This is a follow-up report combining information from duplicate reports 2019306934 and 2019310592. The current and all subsequent information will be reported under manufacturer report number 2019310592. This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other health professional. A patient of unspecified age and gender received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13) via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date at single dose for immunization. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The caller reported that once the sterile seal had been broken, the vaccine should be used or discarded at the end of the workday. Caller stated there might have been a patient who received the vaccine beyond the end of the workday.  Follow-up (23Aug2019): This follow-up is being submitted to notify that the batch number is not available despite the followup attempts made. Vaccine single dose syringe has needle applied to syringe during clinic the day i.e. 15Jul2019 before and should have been wasted, however a staff member used it anyway on 16Jul2019. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Uterine dehiscence; Premature delivery; Hypertension; Trichomonas; Bacterial vaginosis; Nausea; Vomiting; Elevated AFP; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 27-Sep-2019, concerning a 25-year-old, female pregnant subject of body weight: 193 lbs, height: 66 inches and body mass index (BMI): 31.1 (Ethnicity: not reported) enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's past medical history included bacterial vaginosis and the subject's historical drug included Metrogel (metronidazole) for bacterial vaginosis. The subject's current condition included Herpes simplex virus II and anemia. The subject's concomitant medications included: Prenatal vitamins (mineral nos, vitamins nos) for pregnancy and Venofer (saccharated iron oxide) for anemia.  The subject's obstetrical history included six previous pregnancies with five full-term live births and one preterm live births. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no relevant maternal and paternal medical history. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 29-Jun-2018. The subject's estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were 05-Apr-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 22-Aug-2018, the subject underwent cystic fibrosis mutation analysis and spinal muscular atrophy test and no MCMs were noted.  On 05-Sep-2018 and 20-Sep-2018, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCMs were noted.  On 03-Oct-2018, at gestational age at 13 weeks, the subject was administered Flucelvax QIVc [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 252664, dose: 0,5 ml, anatomical location, route of administration and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. On the same day, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 22-Oct-2018, 19 days after vaccination, the subject underwent maternal serum alpha fetoprotein (MSAFP)/Serum markers test and the result was 3.33 (no units were provided) and it was reported as elevated alpha 1 foetoprotein (AFP). On the same date, the subject underwent ultrasound and Qnatal test and no MCM was noted.  On 15-Nov-2018, 1 month and 12 days after vaccination, the subject experienced nausea and vomiting.   On 18-Dec-2018, 2 months and 15 days after vaccination, the subject developed bacterial vaginosis.  From 18-Dec-2018 to 28-Dec-2018, the subject was treated with Metrogel gel for bacterial vaginosis, dose reported as 0.75 %, two times a daily (BID), vaginally.   On 28-Dec-2018, the subject recovered from the event of bacterial vaginosis.  On 15-Jan-2019, the subject underwent Non-stress test and no MCM was noted.  On 28-Jan-2019, 3 months and 25 days after vaccination, the subject developed hypertension and trichomonas.  From 28-Jan-2019 to 08-Feb-2019, the subject was treated with Procardia capsule (prasugrel hydrochloride) for hypertension, at one dose, every six hours (Q6h), orally and with Flagyl (metronidazole) for trichomonas, at dose of 375 mg, BID, orally.  On 05-Feb-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 07-Feb-2019, the subject underwent Non-stress test and no MCM was noted.  On 08-Feb-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and Non-stress test and no MCMs were noted. On the same date, the subject recovered from the event of trichomonas.  On 11-Feb-2019, the subject underwent Non-stress test and no MCM was noted.  On 14-Feb-2019, at gestational age of 32.9 weeks, the mother delivered live birth, male neonate by caesarean method of delivery. The neonate's birth weight was 2140 g, his head circumference and length: were not reported. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). At the time of delivery, pregnancy complication uterine dehiscence was noted, but details were not specified. There was no MCMs identified at birth. On the same date, the subject recovered from the event nausea and vomiting.  At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the events uterine dehiscence, premature delivery and alpha 1 fetoprotein increased was not reported, while the event of hypertension was not resolved.  This case is linked to 201904856, the corresponding child case.  Company Comment: The subject experienced uterine dehiscence, premature delivery, alpha 1 fetoprotein increased, hypertension, trichomoniasis, bacterial vaginosis, nausea and vomiting after vaccination with the suspect product Flucelvax QIVc. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy.   Chronology is plausible. Medical history of bacterial vaginosis, Herpes simplex virus II, anaemia and pregnant state may have contributed to development of the events. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company conventions. For all other events, causal role of the suspect product cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related.; Reporter's Comments: The subject experienced uterine dehiscence, premature delivery, alpha 1 fetoprotein increased, hypertension, trichomoniasis, bacterial vaginosis, nausea and vomiting after vaccination with the suspect product Flucelvax QIVc. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy.   Chronology is plausible. Medical history of bacterial vaginosis, Herpes simplex virus II, anaemia and pregnant state may have contributed to development of the events. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company conventions. For all other events, causal role of the suspect product cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Eclampsia at 34 weeks; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received on 27-Sep-2019, concerning a 24-year-old, pregnant, female subject [Ethnicity: Not reported] of body weight 158 lbs, height 64 inches and body mass index (BMI) 27.1, enrolled, a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had two previous pregnancies including one previous full-term live birth and one preterm live birth pregnancy. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject's current conditions included anxiety, depression and hypertension. Concomitant medications included prenatal vitamins (minerals NOS, vitamins NOS) for pregnancy and Zoloft (sertraline hydrochloride) for anxiety.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 10-Nov-2018, the estimated date of delivery (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery was 17-Aug-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 12-Mar-2019, the subject underwent spinal muscular atrophy, cystic fibrosis mutation analysis and hemoglobin electrophoresis and no MCM was noted.  On 19-Mar-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and quad screen, and no MCM was noted.  On 15-May-2019, at approximately 26 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 252664, dose: 0.5 mL, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.   On an unreported date, at 34 weeks of gestation, the subject experienced eclampsia, reported as pregnancy complication.  On 13-Aug-2019, at gestational age of 39.4 weeks, the subject delivered a live birth, male neonate via caesarean section. The neonate's birth weight was 3250 grams, head circumference was 35.6 cm and length was 50.8 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). There was no APGAR score data for 10 minutes reported. No MCM was identified at birth.   At the time of initial reporting, the outcome for the event of 'eclampsia' was not reported.  Company Comment: The subject experienced eclampsia after vaccination with the suspect product Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. Chronology is plausible. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of hypertension and pregnant state may have contributed to development of the event. Causality was confounded by use of concomitant medication, Zoloft (sertraline hydrochloride). Causal relationship between the suspect product and exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related. The subject was treated with benzylpenicillin (Penicillin). The reporter considered the vaccination failure, influenza, retropharyngeal abscess, peritonsillar abscess, streptococcal infection and bacterial infection to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a 13.9-year-old male patient, who was vaccinated with unspecified 2017-2018 seasonal influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to case-5 from table 1 reported in this literature article. The patient was a part of retrospective review that was performed for pediatric patients hospitalized with bacterial head or neck infections following influenza infection between October 2017 and March 2018.The patient had received influenza vaccine previously in 2006, 2007, 2009, 2012, 2014 and 2015. No information on patient's medical history, family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date in 2017, the patient received unspecified 2017-2018 seasonal influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The patient had also received 4 doses of unspecified 7-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV7). The age of vaccinations was not provided.  On an unspecified date, an unknown period after the seasonal influenza vaccination, the patient developed influenza virus infection that was subsequently diagnosed with positive rapid influenza diagnostic test. The type of influenza virus was unknown. On an unspecified date between October 2017 and March 2018, at the age of 13.9 years, 6 days after the influenza diagnosis, the patient was hospitalised for retropharyngeal abscess (RPA) and peritonsillar abscess (bacterial head or neck infections which were associated with influenza infection).  The incision and drainage was performed. The causative pathogen for head or neck infection was found to be Streptococcus pyogenes. The patient was also found positive with polymicrobial infection with Prevotella. The duration of hospitalization was between 5 and 35 days. The treatment was started with penicillin (definitive treatment). The duration of treatment was 3 weeks. The patient had completed penicillin treatment successfully and had favorable outcome. This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being the time to onset was unknown. This case has been considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure/hospitalisation. The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of influenza virus infection, and unspecified seasonal influenza vaccine. However the authors stated, "Seasonal influenza infection is associated with secondary bacterial complications involving the upper and lower respiratory tract. However, the association of influenza infection with secondary severe or complicated head and neck infections is not appreciated." The authors concluded, "It was suggested that complicated bacterial head and neck infections may represent an under recognized co-infection or secondary complication of infection with influenza virus, further stressing the importance of prevention and treatment of influenza infection." This article corresponding to this case is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction. This is 1 of the 2 valid cases reported in this literature article. It was unknown if the reporter considered the throat blister, pain in arm, sore throat, toothache and skin lesion to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information was reported as follows: The patient experienced a sore arm after the injection. The day after the injection, the patient started having a sore throat. By the end of the week, her throat was still sore, so the patient looked at it and saw blisters in her throat. Around 16th June 2019, after 3 weeks the blisters and sore throat were resolved. The patient did not seen her physician, she thought did place a call towards the end and an antiviral was prescribed which she never took because the symptoms resolved. On 7th July 2019, the sore throat and blisters were returned, along with lesions on her chest and back and lasted another 2 to 3 weeks. This time the patient had visited her physician and she was prescribed an antibiotic and antiviral. A culture of the throat was also taken, which was negative for strep. The symptoms were resolved about 4 days after starting the medications. Less than two months after vaccination, during this 2nd outbreak the patient also started having a toothache in a tooth that previously had a root canal. The patient had a regular dental visit scheduled on 19th July 2019, which happened to occur shortly after the resolution of the second outbreak of blisters. The patient's physician referred her to another provider, who advised that she would need to get an implant.  On 24th September 2019, the patient started having another outbreak of blisters in her throat that was still ongoing. The patient also noted that, her tooth was not aching and throbbing as much as it was, but she can still feel it when using her water pick. The reporter consented to follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 3.5 hours after getting the shot, I had massive chills and accompanying shaking -- hand and arm movements of 6-12 inches. I had difficulty walking, being very clumsy, bumping into things, and having to use fixed objects (doorways...) to help guide myself. Was weak -- took multiple tries to get up from a recliner. There was also stiffness in the muscles. The injection site was only slightly tender. Temperature for 8pm-12M varied slightly around 103.6 degrees. When I went to bed at 3am it was down to 102.2 degrees. At 7am it was 101.8; at 1pm 99.6. At 24 hours after the shot, still stillness. I have had annual flu shots for as long as I can remember, and never had anything more than a mild reaction.  Reporting this because the rapid onset of symptoms and the severity could put people in danger if they are out-and-about.
OTHER_MEDS: AM: Escitalopram (for Lexapro), Bupropion (for Wellbutrin) PM (just before bed): Trazodone, Tamsulosin (for Flomax)

First dose was July 2, 2019.   Had slight reaction....swollen red arm, some achiness, but able to work (though not to usual standard).   Anticipated perhaps same issue for second dose so I took one Ibuprofen within hour of receiving vaccination.     12 hours post vaccination: began low grade fever @100 degrees, severe body aches, headache, racing heart, nausea and extreme fatigue.  Took another ibuprofen. 21 hours post vaccination: above symptoms, plus balance issues, weakness and beginning vomiting.   Took another ibuprofen.  Cancelled all work and events for day.  Went back to bed and slept.   28 hours post vacc, was able to eat a little soup without vomiting.  Went back to bed and slept until 35 hours post vacc.  Got up and ate a very small plate.  Went back to bed with another ibuprofen at 36 hours post vacc.  Still slight fever.   45 hours post vacc. woke up without fever, but still achey.  Strong enough to eat more and do light work.   I usually do not have reaction to vaccinations, so was very surprised to encounter such a severe reaction.
